const SECTIONS = [{"id": "1.1","title": "International Progress in Palliative Medicine","chapter": "1.1","section": "1","sectionLabel": "Worldwide Status of Palliative Care","start": 3,"end": 12,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 1.1 International progress in the development of palliative medicine\n\nTable 1.1.1 List of palliative care development mapping studies\nRegion\n\nPalliative care components addressed\n\nStudies\n\nEurope\n\nAll elements of the WHO definition\n\nArias-​Casais et al., 2019\nCenteno et al., 2013\nMartin-​Moreno et al., 2007\nRocafort and Centeno, 2008\nWoitha et al., 2016\n\nPolicies\n\nChambaere, 2011\nVan Beek et al., 2013\nWoithaet et al., 2016\n\nEducation\n\nCarrasco et al., 2015\nSchiessl et al., 2013\n\nSpecialized service provision\n\nCenteno et al., 2007a, 2016\n\nOfficial certification for physicians\n\nCenteno et al., 2007b, 2014, 2015\n\nLatin America\n\nAll elements of the WHO definition\n\nDe Lima, 2015\nPastrana et al., 2012, 2014\n\nMiddle Eastern\nRegion\n\nAll elements of the WHO definition\n\nBingley and Clark, 2009\nFadhil et al., 2017\nMojen et al., 2017\nOsman et al., 2017\n\nAsia\n\nAll elements of the WHO definition\n\nChan et al., 2015\nYamaguchi et al., 2017\n\nAfrica\n\nAll elements of the WHO definition\n\nFraser et al., 2018\nKimani et al., 2017\nRhee et al., 2017a, 2017b, 2017c\nWeaver et al., 2015\n\nProvision levels\nHigh\n\nLow\n\nFig. 1.1.1 Specialized palliative care services across the world (specialized service provision levels of 170 of 234 countries are reported here).\nSource: data from Arias-​Casais, N. et al. (2019). EAPC Atlas of Palliative Care in Europe 2019. Vilvoorde, Belgium: EAPC Press. http://​hdl.handle.net/​10171/​56787; Lynch, T. et al.\n(2013). Mapping levels of palliative care development: a global update. J Pain Symptom Manage. 45(6):1094–​106. DOI: 10.1016/​j.jpainsymman.2012.05.011; Osman, H. et al.\n(2017). Atlas of Palliative Care in the Eastern Mediterranean Region. Houston, USA: IAHPC Press; Pastrana, T. et al. (2013). Atlas de Cuidados Paliativos en Latinoamérica. Houston,\nUSA: IAHPC Press; Rhee, J.Y. et al. (2017). APCA Atlas of Palliative Care in Africa. Houston, USA: IAHPC Press. https://​www.africanpalliativecare.org/​articles/​apca-​atlas-​of-​\npalliative-​care-​in-​africa/​; Yamaguchi, T. et al. (2017). Palliative care development in the Asia-​Pacific region: an international survey from the Asia Pacific Hospice Palliative Care\nNetwork (APHN). BMJ Support Palliat Care. 7(1):23–​31. DOI: 10.1136/​bmjspcare-​2013-​000588.\n\n55\n\n6\n\nSECTION 1 The worldwide status of palliative care\n\nFig. 1.1.2 Number and typology of palliative care services in Europe.\nAdapted with permission from Arias-​Casais, N. et al. (2019). EAPC Atlas of Palliative Care in Europe 2019. Vilvoorde, Belgium: EAPC Press. http://​hdl.handle.net/​10171/​56787.\n\ncountries have no hospice and palliative care services (Rhee\net al., 2017a) (Fig. 1.1.3). Only six countries (Botswana, Gambia,\nRwanda, South Africa, Swaziland, and Uganda) provide the ratio\nof 0.18 services per 100,000 inhabitants. The inequity of service\nprovision in Africa is possibly the most striking of all world regions, where just three countries, namely South Africa, Uganda,\nand Kenya, account for 71% of the total palliative"},{"id": "1.2","title": "Essential Medicines for Palliative Care","chapter": "1.2","section": "1","sectionLabel": "Worldwide Status of Palliative Care","start": 13,"end": 18,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "CHAPTER 1.2 Essential medicines for palliative care\n\nsodium picosulfate), and midazolam (instead of lorazepam) were\nincluded in the new section. Oxycodone and hydromorphone were\nmentioned as alternatives to morphine.\nMore recently, the 20th edition of the EML has seen the addition of\nfentanyl and (in a complementary list) methadone for management\nof cancer pain (WHO, 2017). Gabapentin had also been suggested\nfor inclusion in the EML with the indication of neuropathic pain, but\nin relation to the discussions on reporting bias and manipulation of\nresearch, results which threatened the validity of the published evidence, the WHO Expert Committee did not include gabapentin.\nAccess to essential medicines for palliative care was also one of\nthe major topics of discussion of the Lancet Commission on palliative care. The Commission described essential medicines, as well\nas essential equipment and human resources (Knaul et al., 2018).\nThis essential package was compiled with a special focus on the\nsituation in lower-​or middle-​income countries and was considered\nas the minimum standard in any health system, however resource-​\nconstrained. The Commission introduced the concept of serious\nhealth-​related suffering (SHS) and described 20 diseases and health\nconditions (e.g. cancer, HIV/​AIDS, or acute trauma) as the most\nfrequent causes of SHS. Most SHS conditions would require palliative care, either as a primary healthcare approach or as specialist\npalliative care for complex cases.\nThe essential package considered the health conditions and symptoms associated with SHS. Care was taken to include only off-​patent\nmedicines to keep the costs low. The list of medicines in the essential package was based on the WHO EML, but with some minor\nchanges following a review by a panel of palliative care physicians\nworking in lower-​income countries (Box 1.2.1).\nBox 1.2.1 Medicines in the essential package of the\nLancet Commission\n• Amitriptyline\n• Bisacodyl, or senna as alternative\n• Dexamethasone\n• Dexamethasone\n• Diazepam\n• Diphenhydramine—​chlorpheniramine, cyclizine, or dimenhydrinate\nas alternatives\n• Fluconazole\n• Fluoxetine or other selective serotonin-​reuptake inhibitors, such as\nsertraline or citalopram\n• Furosemide\n• Haloperidol\n• Hyoscine butylbromide\n• Ibuprofen—​naproxen, diclofenac, or meloxicam as alternatives\n• Lactulose—​sorbitol, or polyethylene glycol as alternatives\n• Loperamide\n• Metoclopramide\n• Metronidazole\n• Morphine oral immediate-​release and injectable\n• Naloxone\n• Omeprazole\n• Ondansetron\n• Paracetamol\n• Petroleum jelly.\nSource: data from Knaul, F.M. et al. (2018). Alleviating the access abyss in palliative care\nand pain relief-​an imperative of universal health coverage: The Lancet Commission\nreport. Lancet. 391(10128): 1391–​1454. DOI: 10.1016/​S0140-​6736(17)32513-​8.\n\nEssential medicines and indications\nEssential medicines lists, such as those from section 2 in the WHO\nEML or from the Lancet Commission, have been compiled to include "},{"id": "1.3","title": "Human Rights Issues","chapter": "1.3","section": "1","sectionLabel": "Worldwide Status of Palliative Care","start": 19,"end": 25,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 1.3 Human rights issues\n\nthat committee to outline their fulfilment of the rights enumerated\nin the covenant, including the right to health.\nThe content of the obligation on signatory countries in the provision of adequate pain management and palliative care can be\ngleaned from the Committee that oversees the ICESCR. In 2000\nit issued a General Comment on the right to health (General\nComment 14) (CESCR, 2000). General Comment 14 explores the\nintent of the right to health, or to give it the full description, the\nright to the enjoyment of the highest attainable standard of health\nand well-​being. In essence it stated that this right contained the following ‘interrelated and essential elements’: availability of health\ngoods and services, accessibility of health services to all citizens, acceptability in terms of culture and religious beliefs, and quality in\nterms of skills and expertise. These foundation stones—​availability,\naccessibility, acceptability, and quality—​are useful points of reference in assessing the adequacy of any nation in the fulfilment of its\nobligations in the provision of palliative care.\nThe Committee went on to describe the ‘core obligations’ of all\nsignatory nations, irrespective of resources. They included obligations to ensure access to health facilities, goods, and services on a\nnon-​discriminatory basis, to provide essential drugs, as defined by\nthe WHO, and to adopt and implement a national public health\nstrategy. Interpreting this Comment in the context of palliative care,\nthis would oblige nations to ensure a universal access to services,\nthe provision of basic medications for symptom control and terminal care, including analgesics and the adoption and implementation of national pain and palliative care policies. In addition to\nthe ‘core obligations’, the Committee also enumerated obligations\n‘of comparable priority’. These include: ‘To provide education and\naccess to information concerning the main health problems in the\ncommunity, including methods of preventing and controlling them’\nand ‘To provide appropriate training for health personnel, including\neducation on health and human rights’. In the context of palliative\ncare, a ‘main health problem’ in all countries, this would obligate\ngovernments to ensure the education of health professionals in the\nprinciples and practice of palliative care and, further, provide access\nto the general community to information regarding it. Signatory nations are required to respect, protect, and fulfil the right to health.\n\nTowards a transdisciplinary consensus on the\ncontent of the obligation\nDo the obligations that derive from human rights law accord with\nrecommendations articulated from other sources? And if so, is there\na synergy between them? The first source is the WHO; the second\nis the international palliative care community itself. The WHO laid\ndown minimum standards of palliative care expected of countries.\nThose standards included the adoption of national palliati"},{"id": "1.4","title": "Policy in Palliative Care","chapter": "1.4","section": "1","sectionLabel": "Worldwide Status of Palliative Care","start": 26,"end": 33,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "28\n\nSECTION 1 The worldwide status of palliative care\n\nagency. The accountable entity must develop an implementation\nplan, which typically involves communication with stakeholder\ngroups—​a process that may require new laws or regulations, or\nchanges in by-​laws or procedures; planned professional or public\neducation; development of an evaluation plan; and a budget process. When these actions are undertaken by a ministry, substantial\ntime is required for each step. Implementation funding, for example, may not be possible until it can be added to a new budget;\nthe budget cycle may itself take considerable time to happen if the\npolicy was not long anticipated.\n\nImplementation of palliative care policy\nThe most important element in the implementation of a policy to\nimprove access to palliative care is the availability of funding. If\nfunding is available, progress can be made even if all of the other\nsteps in the implementation process are not in place. The key elements to implementation, apart from funding, vary from country\nto country. To clarify what is essential, it is best to look at existing\nmajor country policies that have been implemented for guidance.\nFor example, many countries have developed policies or national\naction plans (NAPs) for dealing with the rise of dementia or cervical\ncancer. In Greece, the dementia NAP served as a template for the\ndevelopment of the NAP for palliative care, since the government\nhad approved it and at least had partially implemented it. This plan\nwas familiar to the Ministry of Health who had worked on it and\nit also served as a learning lesson to what worked and didn’t work.\nTo implement a palliative care policy, changes are usually needed\nto existing regulations that may govern licensure, reimbursement,\nor access to medicines. For this reason, an analysis of current law\nand regulation is needed to identify potential areas of conflict. New\nregulations may be needed to determine the professional credentials and training required of those who provide palliative care;\nothers may define the criteria used to determine which patients are\neligible to receive a new programme. Other regulations may focus\non the minimal requirements for care, which are usually based on\nstandards of operation. Palliative care professional associations may\nhave these standards, or may need to develop them; once identified,\nthese standards must be translated into the format used by the ministry to ensure competence and safety for the public. Finally, implementation may require revision of the laws or regulations governing\naccess to controlled essential medicines.\nThe implementation of palliative care policy is usually best done\nwith a national strategy and a NAP. The NAP should map out\nhow palliative care should be implemented in considerable detail,\nincluding the number of programmes to be established according\nto a timeline. It may take decades for such a policy to be fully implemented, if it is ever to meet all or most of the need in a "},{"id": "2.1","title": "Building Definitional Consensus in Palliative Care","chapter": "2.1","section": "2","sectionLabel": "The Challenge of Palliative Medicine","start": 35,"end": 43,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 2.1 Building definitional consensus in palliative care\n\nBox 2.1.1 Selected definitions for palliative care\nWorld Health Organization definition of palliative care\n‘Palliative care is an approach that improves the quality of life of patients\nand their families facing the problem associated with life-​threatening\nillness, through the prevention and relief of suffering by means of early\nidentification and impeccable assessment and treatment of pain and\nother problems, physical, psychosocial and spiritual. Palliative care:\n• provides relief from pain and other distressing symptoms;\n• affirms life and regards dying as a normal process;\n• intends neither to hasten or postpone death;\n• integrates the psychological and spiritual aspects of patient care;\n• offers a support system to help patients live as actively as possible\nuntil death;\n• offers a support system to help the family cope during the patient’s\nillness and in their own bereavement;\n• uses a team approach to address the needs of patients and their families, including bereavement counselling, if indicated;\n• will enhance quality of life, and may also positively influence the\ncourse of illness;\n• is applicable early in the course of illness, in conjunction with other\ntherapies that are intended to prolong life, such as chemotherapy or\nradiation therapy, and includes those investigations needed to better\nunderstand and manage distressing clinical complications’.\nReproduced under the STM agreement from World Health\nOrganization (WHO). (2019). WHO definition of palliative care. Geneva,\nSwitzerland: WHO. https://​www.who.int/​cancer/​palliative/​definition/​en/.​\n\nEuropean Association of Palliative Care definition of palliative care\n‘Palliative care is the active, total care of patients whose disease is not responsive to curative treatment. Palliative care takes a holistic approach,\naddressing physical, psychosocial and spiritual care, including the treatment of pain and other symptoms. Palliative care is interdisciplinary in\nits approach and encompasses the care of the patient and their family\nand should be available in any location including hospital, hospice and\ncommunity.\nPalliative care affirms life and regards dying as a normal process; it neither hastens nor postpones death and sets out to preserve the best possible quality of life until death’.\nReproduced with permission from European Association of Palliative\nCare (EAPC). (2019). What is palliative care? Vilvoorde, Belgium: EAPC.\nhttps://​www.eapcnet.eu/​about-​us/​what-​we-​do.\n\nInternational Association for Hospice and Palliative Care definition\nof palliative care\n‘Palliative care is the active holistic care of individuals across all ages with\nserious health-​related suffering due to severe illness, and especially of\nthose near the end of life. It aims to improve the quality of life of patients,\ntheir families and their caregivers.\nPalliative care:\n• Includes, prevention, early identification, comprehensive assessment and manageme"},{"id": "2.2","title": "Core Concepts in Palliative Care","chapter": "2.2","section": "2","sectionLabel": "The Challenge of Palliative Medicine","start": 44,"end": 54,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "4646\n\nSECTION 2 The challenge of palliative medicine\n\nThe corollary of this right is the responsibility of caregivers to ensure that adequate provisions are made for relief. The formulation\nof a therapeutic response to suffering, however, requires an understanding of the phenomenon of suffering and of the factors that\ncontribute to it. Indeed, the failure to appreciate, or to effectively\naddress, the full diversity of contributing factors may confound effective therapeutic strategies (Krikorian et al., 2011).\nIn the clinical setting, there are many barriers to an effective and\nsustainable response to the suffering associated with progressive\nand incurable illness. These barriers may be disease related (such as\nsymptoms or other causes of distress that are intrinsically difficult\nto relieve), related to the patient or their family, or related to larger\npragmatic, economic, geopolitical, or social reasons that make it\ndifficult to provide palliative care. These barriers, however, do not\nundermine the duty to prioritize the relief of suffering for people\nwith incurable illnesses and the families that support them.\n\nResilience\nAdherence to the core values of care, compassion, and empathy may\nchallenge the emotional resources of the care providers. In taking on\nthe task of palliative care, professional caregivers willingly accept the\nrole as first-​hand witness to physical, emotional, and existential distress. Caring for people at the end of life and their families day after\nday, often for years on end, exposes those involved in palliative care\nto stressors that can lead to burnout, compassion fatigue, and moral\ndistress (see Chapter 4.2). The ability of professional caregivers to\nmanage the emotional impact of this work may be diminished by\nmany factors, including exhaustion, overwork, conflicts, competing\npersonal concerns, and lack of supports. Each member of an interdisciplinary team brings personal needs and resources to the clinical\nexperience, and the different stressors borne by members of the team\ncan strain even the best of collaborative relationships.\nResilience is the quality that enables professional caregivers to\ncope, adapt, and continuing giving and growing, despite being witness to a tidal surge of suffering (Back et al., 2016; Hwang et al.,\n2018). Resilience is bolstered by the skills acquired through years of\ntraining, teamwork, mutual support, sense of mission, appropriate\ngoal setting, adequate resources, dedication, and good intentions.\nWithin an interdisciplinary team, resilience is the flexible, binding\nmatrix that keeps diverse people working constructively together\ndespite stress, conflict, interpersonal frictions, and grievances that\nwould potentially fragment or undermine the ability to deliver care\n(Mehta et al., 2016).\nCommon experience suggests that resilience characterizes many\nof the clinicians who choose palliative care as a career. These clinicians are self-​motivated and driven to develop the skills and relationship"},{"id": "2.3","title": "Epidemiology of Death and Symptoms","chapter": "2.3","section": "2","sectionLabel": "The Challenge of Palliative Medicine","start": 55,"end": 68,"pages": 14,"weight": 0.0112,"text": "CHAPTER 2.3 Planning for population-based palliative care\n\n2016\n\n2030\nIschaemic heart disease\nStroke\nCOPD\nLower respiratory infections\nAlzheimer disease, dementias\nTrachea, bronchus, lung cancers\nCOUNTRY\n\nDiabetes mellitus\n\nWorld\nHigh-income\nUpper-middle-income\nLower-middle-income\nLower-income\n\nRoad injury\nDiarrhoeal diseases\nTuberculosis\n20%\n\n15%\n\n10%\n\n5%\n\n0%\n\n0%\n\n5%\n\n10%\n\n15%\n\n20%\n\nFig. 2.3.1 Leading causes of death in the world: projections for 2016 and 2030 (based on 2016 data). Missing columns indicate specific cause of\ndeath was not in the top 10 for that income group of countries.\nSource: data from World Health Organization (WHO). (2018). Global Health Estimates 2016: Deaths by Cause, Age, Sex, by Country and by Region, 2000–​2016. Geneva,\nSwitzerland: WHO. http://​www.who.int/​en/​news-​room/​fact-​sheets/​detail/​the-​top-​10-​causes-​of-​death.\n\nbaseline projection estimates that deaths from this cause will increase from 2.8 million in 2002 to 6.5 million in 2030. Deaths from\nother infective conditions or perinatal conditions are projected to\nfall. Over the same time period, baseline projections of deaths from\ncancer suggest an increase from 7.1 million to 11.5 million, and\ncardiovascular deaths from 16.7 to 23.3 million. Combined deaths\nfrom cancer and chronic non-​infective and non-​cancer illnesses\nare expected to account for 70% of deaths in 2030. The third major\nmortality grouping is related to deaths from injury and accidents.\nProjections for this group saw a 40% expected increase largely accounted for by road traffic accidents with an estimated increase\nfrom 1.2 in 2002 to 2.1 million in 2030 (Mathers et al., 2006).\n\nPalliative care: needs, access, and service\nplanning\nHealth administrative data sets: how can these be used\nto assess needs and quality of care?\nSome information about population healthcare needs at the end\nof life has been provided by several large, well-​designed epidemiological studies (Seeman, 1992b; Addington-​Hall and McCarthy,\n1995; McNamara and Rosenwax, 2007; Coupland et al., 2010; Seow\net al., 2012; Cheung et al., 2015; Currow et al., 2015) and further information about the longitudinal nature and intensity of palliative\ncare needs would be helpful for service planning.\n\nWith the expanding potential to analyse large healthcare administrative data sets through record linkage, there is increased\ninterest in the role that information abstracted from these datasets\ncan play in assessing the quality of care (Eagar et al., 2010; Kamal\net al., 2015). Many studies of this nature from recent years examine\nthe period towards the end of life. These include large epidemiological studies that provide information about healthcare utilization\nover the period near to the end of life. Although a full review is\nbeyond the scope of this chapter, studies examining costs of care\n(Fassbender et al., 2005; Yabroff et al., 2007; Cheung et al., 2015),\npalliative care service use (Fassbender et al., 2005; Rosenwax and\nMcNamara, 2006"},{"id": "2.4","title": "Barriers to the Delivery of Palliative Care","chapter": "2.4","section": "2","sectionLabel": "The Challenge of Palliative Medicine","start": 69,"end": 75,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 2.4 Barriers to the delivery of palliative care\n\nalso challenging. The main barriers include a lack of resources and\nuncertainty as to which health professionals should provide care\n(specialist versus general palliative care providers and the role of\nspecialists in geriatric medicine). There may also be attitudinal differences in the elderly, which makes it less likely for these patients\nto be recognized as needing palliative care (Gardiner et al., 2011).\nOne of the ways that palliative care can be improved is to develop\nthe role of a link nurse, a trained nurse with specific palliative care\nskills, who may be engaged to help elderly patients obtain appropriate care. Barriers exist for this model as well, however, such as\nlack of management support, frequent changes in the workforce,\nand lack of adequate preparation (Hasson et al., 2008).\n\nHomeless people\nHomelessness is a problem in every country and providing palliative\ncare to homeless people can be a particular challenge. It is known\nthat homeless people often have complex needs due to higher levels\nof substance abuse and other mental illnesses, and that they often\nsuffer from complex and chronic comorbidities such as cirrhosis,\ncancer, and HIV. They often have a lack of social support and health\ninsurance, and they frequently die at much younger ages than the\ngeneral population (Klop et al., 2018).\nNumerous barriers hinder appropriate delivery of palliative care\nin this group of patients. Personal barriers include: life being led on\na ‘day-​to-​day’ basis, during which the focus is on necessity and survival rather than healthcare; seeking help late; inability or unwillingness to attend to schedules or accept recommended treatments;\nand illicit drug/​alcohol use, which is more common in this group\n(Klop et al., 2018).\nWhen drug abuse complicates homelessness, this presents some\nspecific challenges: patients are often concerned as to how withdrawal from drugs will be managed, and when opioids are needed\nmedically, patients may have high opioid tolerance; healthcare professionals often have fears about adverse reactions; and patients may\nhave a lack of trust in healthcare providers as well as concerns about\nprovider and system-​wide prejudices (such as anti-​drug policies)\n(McNeil and Guirguis-​Younger, 2012; Klop et al., 2018). Social barriers include a lack of social support from families and peers, and\ntransport difficulties. Behaviours observed by clinicians, such as a\nlack of insight, denial, continued use of drugs, and aggressive or\nchallenging behaviours, may induce reactions that further compromise care. At the same time, homeless people may feel ignored\nor discriminated against by healthcare providers and that they are\nshown disrespect.\nHealthcare providers often feel they have a lack of training and\nknowledge for how best to support homeless people, and there is\noften a lack of medical information and a lack of awareness of the\nunique issues facing the homeless (Klop et al., 2"},{"id": "2.5","title": "Ethnic and Cultural Aspects of Palliative Care","chapter": "2.5","section": "2","sectionLabel": "The Challenge of Palliative Medicine","start": 76,"end": 92,"pages": 17,"weight": 0.0136,"text": "78\n\nSECTION 2 The challenge of palliative medicine\n\nof palliative care services provided by hospices or other healthcare\ninstitutions in their home country. For example, the Observatory\ndocumented misperceptions about and stigmas regarding palliative\ncare in Mexico (Clark, 2007). As such, expectations for palliative\ncare may thus be lowered among Mexican immigrants who bring\nfrom their country of origin misperceptions or lowered priorities\nfor this type of care (Crawley and Chaudhary, 2006). In addition,\nsome immigrants may find accessing quality care and finding funds\nfor hospice, palliative care, and other end of life health services to\nbe a complex and potentially confusing process that may be compounded by unfamiliarity with laws and regulations of the host\ncountry. The immigrant’s knowledge of and preference for palliative\nor other healthcare may be influenced by factors related to immigration itself. For example, refugees and asylum seekers who have\nexperienced violence, or who may have been exposed to torture or\nother state-​sanctioned or war-​related trauma, may be mistrustful\nof government-​run healthcare or social service institutions and authorities (Gunaratnam, 2006). They may also face fears and uncertainties that accompany their experiences as an immigrant.\nImmigration also impacts the workforce that provides caregiving\nfor those who are dying. Foreign health and social care professional\nworkers are motivated to leave their native countries for reasons general to all immigrants—​educational, economic, or social advantage;\nfamily reunification—​or they may leave due to inadequate healthcare\ninfrastructures and technologies (Crawley et al., 2007). The consequence of some receiving countries is a growing immigrant workforce that bring their own unique cross-​cultural issues to healthcare\ndelivery systems. On the one hand, an increasingly diverse health and\nsocial care workforce may help improve outreach to diverse communities, particularly with access issues such as language barriers. On\nthe other hand, these workers will represent a spectrum of acculturation or assimilation of the language, customs, values, and perspectives of the host country. Just as there can be ‘native’ providers who\nlack cultural competency and sensitivity towards immigrant patients,\nthere can be those immigrant providers who lack these skills with ‘native’ patients. Central to this issue is communication capability.\n\nProviding equitable, culturally appropriate\npalliative care\nThe World Health Organization definition of palliative care specifies two goals: improving quality of life (QOL) of patients and\nfamilies and preventing and relieving suffering. It identifies three\nstrategies for meeting those goals: early identification, impeccable\nassessment, and (appropriate) treatment. Lastly, the definition addresses four domains of care: (1) problems related to pain, (2) other\nphysical conditions, (3) the psychosocial, and (4) the spiritual. The\nremaining sections of "},{"id": "2.6","title": "Health Economics for Palliative Care","chapter": "2.6","section": "2","sectionLabel": "The Challenge of Palliative Medicine","start": 93,"end": 101,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 2.6 Health economics for palliative care\n\nTable 2.6.2 Incremental cost-​effectiveness analysis of a new pain intervention compared with current standard of care\nMean costs\n(USD)\n\nMean LYs\n\nMean utility Mean QALYs\n\nIncremental costs (2-​step\nvs 3-​step) in USD\n\nIncremental QALYs\n\nICER (USD/​\nQALY)\n\nStandard care\n\n$10,500\n\n0.25\n\n0.4\n\n0.10\n\n–​\n\n–​\n\n–​\n\nNew intervention\n\n$11,900\n\n0.25\n\n0.6\n\n0.15\n\n$1900\n\n0.05\n\n38,000\n\nICER, incremental cost-​effectiveness ratio; LYs, life years; QALYs, quality adjusted life years; USD, United States dollars; Utility, health-​related quality of life weight.\n\nanalysis, the cost–​utility analysis is measuring the consequences in\nquality-​adjusted life years (QALYs). Most decisions on the adoption\nof new interventions within the UK National Health Service level are\nsupported by evidence from cost–​utility analyses. The clear benefit is\nthe outcome measurement: as QALYs are comparable across a wide\nvariety of healthcare contexts, the problem of non-​comparability of\ndisease-​specific outcome measures is overcome. Cost–​utility analysis can answer questions of technical and allocative efficiency,\ndepending on the scale of the analysis.\nExample of a cost–​utility analysis\nA clinical trial compared the costs and QALYs of a new pain intervention compared with current standard of care. The trial measured\nthe difference in survival (life years), the difference in quality of\nlife (measured on the Health-​Related Utility scale where 1.0 = full\nhealth and 0.0 = death) and the difference in costs. The results are\npresented in Table 2.6.2.\nThe implications of the analysis presented in Table 2.6.2 are that\nadoption of the new pain intervention will result in one additional\nQALY per $38,000 spend. If the health system is currently reimbursing other activity that produces lower QALYs per dollar, and\nthe total healthcare budget remains static, then the efficient strategy\nwould be to reimburse the new pain intervention and disinvest in\nthose less cost-​effective activities. Implicitly, the opportunity cost of\nadoption would be less than continued current standard care.\nIt is important to note that not all countries use the QALY as a\nuniversal outcome measure, with the implication that cost–​utility\nanalysis is not a universally used method.\n\nThe cost-​effectiveness threshold\nA standard measure in health economics is the incremental cost-​\neffectiveness ratio (ICER), which is defined as the difference in cost\nbetween two interventions or strategies divided by the difference\nin their effectiveness. This metric can fall into four different quadrants on what is called a cost-​effectiveness plane (Fig. 2.6.1). The\nbest ICERs are produced when outcomes improve and costs are\nless. The worst is when outcomes are worse and costs increase. Most\ninterventions in healthcare result in higher costs with improved\noutcomes, which makes cost-​effectiveness analysis and cost–​utility\nanalysis useful tools for producing an ICER and comparing these\ni"},{"id": "3.1","title": "Early Integration of Palliative Care","chapter": "3.1","section": "3","sectionLabel": "Service Delivery","start": 103,"end": 110,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 3.1 Issues in the early integration of palliative care\n\nTertiary palliative care: palliative\ncare specialists\n\nSecondary palliative care:\noncology teams\n\nTertiary palliative care: available\nin all care settings to support\nprimary and secondary\nproviders\n\nStandardised care\npathways, referral\nguidelines, and\ncollabora on\n\nPrimary palliative care:\nprimary care teams\n\nSecondary palliative care:\nmainly in hospitals and in cancer\ncentres\n\nPrimary palliative care:\nmainly in the community\n\nFig. 3.1.1 Primary, secondary, and tertiary palliative care.\nReproduced with permission from Kaasa, S. et al. (2018). Integration of oncology and palliative care: a Lancet Oncology Commission. Lancet Oncol. 19 (11): e588–​e653. https://​\ndoi.org/​10.1016/​S1470-​2045(18)30415-​7.\n\nof postgraduate medical training, although most of the literature\nto date comes from oncology. The European Society for Medical\nOncology has developed designated centres of integrated oncology\nand palliative care for cancer services to promote predetermined\nservice development targets and the delivery of higher-​\nquality\npalliative care (Cherny et al., 2010). A collaboration between the\nAmerican Society of Clinical Oncology and the American Academy\nof Hospice and Palliative Medicine outlines the core components of\nsecondary palliative care provision. These include regular attention\nto physical, psychological, and spiritual well-​being, as well as clear\ncommunication around goals of care, ACP, prognosis, and caregiver\nissues (Bickel et al., 2016).\nDespite these initiatives, there are no formal practice guidelines\naround secondary palliative care provision, and gaps in the delivery\nof secondary palliative care education are frequently reported.\nA 2011 study of US haematology/​oncology fellows in their second\nyear of training identified only 26% had completed a rotation in\npalliative care, with only a third receiving formal teaching around\nopioid rotation and assessing psychosocial needs (Buss et al., 2011).\nOncology trainees who have had exposure to palliative care training\nare more likely to refer to palliative care services (Wentlandt et al.,\n2012). A review of the RCTs of EPC interventions to identify key\nelements and techniques that can be easily translated into routine oncology care was published in 2017. This recommends routine standardized physical, psychological, and spiritual distress\nscreening at each oncology visit, along with greater attention to\ncaregiver needs, patient’s illness understanding, and formal discussions around ACP. This equates to an additional 1 hour per patient\neach month, and ideally requires input from the multidisciplinary\nteam (Bakitas et al., 2017). There are no specific data relating to secondary palliative care for other medical specialties, to our knowledge, although many of the same principles could be extrapolated\nfrom oncology programmes.\n\n‘Tertiary palliative care’ is the care provided by specialist palliative care providers working as part of an"},{"id": "3.2","title": "Palliative Care Delivery Models","chapter": "3.2","section": "3","sectionLabel": "Service Delivery","start": 111,"end": 120,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 3.2 Palliative care delivery models\n\nclinical care for all people who have progressive, life-​limiting or end\nof life conditions, while specialist palliative care is offered by specialists, and is concerned with patients with the more complex needs.\n\nGeneralist palliative care\nGeneralist palliative care is usually defined as palliative care provided for those affected by life-​limiting or progressive illness as\nan integral part of standard clinical practice by any healthcare\nprofessional who is not part of a specialist palliative care team\n(Shipman et al., 2008). In the community, generalist palliative\ncare is provided by primary care teams, district nurses, nursing\nand residential home care staff, and other community support\nservices. In hospitals, it is provided by general medical and surgical teams, and specialists for specific diseases or circumstances,\nsuch as oncology, respiratory, renal, intensive care, and cardiac\nteams (Shipman et al., 2008). Condition-​specific specialist nurses\noften work across the interface between hospital and community\n(Aspinal et al., 2012).\n\nTherefore, an optimal model is one that supports and bolsters\ncentres of excellence, collaborating and offering a hub of expertise,\nthat work with collaborative networks, and research active palliative care services and others (Kaasa and Radbruch, 2008). Such\nan approach is recognized as an optimal way to grow capacity, expertise, skills, knowledge, collaboration, and influence national\nand international policy and practice (Kaasa and Radbruch, 2008).\nFlagship centres of excellence, including purpose-​built units such as\nthe Cicely Saunders Institute, can drive forward large collaborative\nendeavours to test the solutions for care now and tomorrow, build\ncapacity and long-​lasting impact, as well as develop the methods\nfor research in the field, improving our understandings and design\nof ethics, trials, public engagement, reporting, and outcome measurements (Eagar et al., 2010; Evans et al., 2013a; Gysels et al., 2013;\nHigginson et al., 2013).\nExtent of need for specialist palliative care\n\nSpecialist palliative care is palliative care provided by those who have\nundergone specific training and/​or accreditation in palliative care/​\nmedicine working in the context of an expert interdisciplinary team\nof palliative care health professionals. Specialist palliative care may\nbe provided by inpatient palliative care units (PCUs) or hospices,\nhospital palliative care teams, community palliative care or hospice\nteams, and paediatric specialist palliative care teams. Increasingly,\nspecialist palliative care services need to meet standards developed\nnationally, work exclusively in palliative care, and have staff who\nhave completed specialist training.\nSpecialist palliative care services usually have three components: (1) directly provide care for the more complex patients and\nfamilies, (2) provide education and support to generalists, and\n(3) undertake or collaborate in research t"},{"id": "3.3","title": "Palliative Medicine in the ICU","chapter": "3.3","section": "3","sectionLabel": "Service Delivery","start": 121,"end": 132,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "CHAPTER 3.3 Palliative medicine in the intensive care unit\n\nmisunderstandings, and talk about issues such as goals of care,\nprognosis, and contingency planning. Initial meetings should focus\non a description of the patient’s status, the measures undertaken to\nattempt to stabilize their condition, the level of risk, and the likelihood of recovery, death, or permanent dependence on life support.\nGood communication and regular family meetings not only improve the psychological well-​being of family members (Wall et al.,\n2007; Gries et al., 2008) but may also be associated with a reduced\nlength of ICU stay (Lilly et al., 2003; Norton et al., 2007).\nSubsequent family meetings should be held when a change occurs in the medical status of the patient (Kon et al., 2016). This is\nparticularly true if the treating clinicians believe that the goals of\ncare should be reassessed and transitioned to palliation care, or\nconflicts exist among family members, or between the family and\ntreating clinicians.\nParticipants in family meetings should include the family members, and the patient’s physician, nurse, social worker, and other\nmembers of the clinical team. These meetings should be led by a\nfacilitator nominated from the clinical team (Kon et al., 2016). In\nmost circumstances the family has no pre-​existing relationship with\nthe ICU staff. Therefore, participation of the patient’s primary clinician is highly desirable.\nTo avoid presentation of conflicting information, it is prudent\nfor the staff to communicate with one another about the prognosis\nand goals of care. It is also important that the multidisciplinary ICU\nteam coordinate their evaluation and plans in preparation for each\nmeeting. In situations where differences of opinion exist regarding\nmanagement or prognosis, these should be explained to the family\nin a balanced manner that shows respect for all of the involved\nclinicians.\nAdditional factors that have been shown to improve satisfaction\nfrom family–​clinician meetings include the ability of the clinician to\nlisten, encourage questions, show empathy, provide emotional support, be attentive to a patient’s values, and allow family members\nsufficient opportunity to express themselves (Billings, 2011a, 2011b;\nBillings and Block, 2011; Curtis et al., 2005; Stapleton et al., 2006;\nKon et al., 2016). Empathic statements by providers during family\nconferences have been shown to be associated with increased family\nsatisfaction with provider communication (Selph et al., 2008).\nFormal communication between providers and the family should\nbe a continual process. Informal meetings with individual family\nmembers can occur in parallel even more frequently to provide updates and discuss pertinent issues and concerns.\nDiscussing prognosis\nMeaningful participation in decision-​making processes requires\nan understanding of prognosis. Additionally, regular discussion of\nprognosis helps families prepare for the possibility of the patient’s\ndeath. Discussion of prognosis"},{"id": "3.4","title": "Palliative Care in the Emergency Department","chapter": "3.4","section": "3","sectionLabel": "Service Delivery","start": 133,"end": 142,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 3.4 Palliative care in the emergency department\n\nP-CaRES Screening Tool for Unmet Palliative Care Needs\nStep 1. Does the Patient Have ≥ 1 Pre-Existing Serious Illness?\nAdvanced Dementia or CNS Disease (e.g. history of Stroke, ALS, Parkinson’s):\nAssistance needed for most self-care (e.g. ambulation, toileting) and/or Minimally verbal.\nAdvanced Cancer:\nMetastatic or locally aggressive disease.\nEnd Stage Renal Disease:\nOn dialysis or Creatinine > 6.\nAdvanced COPD:\nContinuous home O2 or chronic dyspnea at rest.\nAdvanced Heart Failure:\nChronic dyspnea, chest pain or fatigue with minimal activity or rest.\nEnd Stage Liver Disease:\nHistory of recurrent ascites, Gl bleeding, or hepatic encephalopathy.\nSeptic Shock (i.e. signs of organ failure due to infection):\nRequires ICU admission and has significant pre-existing comorbid illness.\nProvider Discretion - High chance of Accelerated Death:\nExamples: Hip fracture > age 80; Major trauma in the elderly (multiple rib fractures, intracranial bleed),\nAdvanced AIDS, etc\n\nONE or More:\nCONTINUE screening\n\nNone\nSTOP: Screening in Complete\n\nStep 2. Does the Patient Have ≥ 2 Unmet Palliative Care Needs?\nFrequent Visits:\n2 or more ED visits or hospital admissions in the past 6 months.\nUncontrolled Symptoms:\nVisit prompted by uncontrol symptom: e.g. pain, dyspnea, depression, fatigue, etc.\nFunctional Decline:\ne.g. loss of mobility, frequent falls, decrease PO, skin breakdown, etc.\nUncertainty about Goals-of-Care and/or Caregiver Distress\nCaregiver cannot meet long-term needs; Uncertainty/distress about goals-of-care.\nSurprise Question:\nYou would not be surprised if this patient died within 12 months.\n\nLess than TWO\nSTOP! Screening is Negative\n\n≥2 Items:\nPC Referral Recommended\n\nFig. 3.4.2 P-​CaRES screening tool for unmet palliative care needs.\nReproduced courtesy of Naomi George, Department of Emergency Medicine, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Massachusetts, USA.\n\n2012). Pain is the most common reason patients seek emergency\ncare, yet analgesics are frequently underutilized, and delays to treatment are common (Todd et al., 2007). Historically, there have been\nbarriers to optimal pain management in the ED, including lack of\ntraining (Lamba et al., 2012), inadequate assessment (Stalnikowicz\net al., 2005), misinterpretation of reasons for seeking care (Wilsey\net al., 2008), and disparities in treatment practices among clinicians\n(Cone et al., 2003; Pletcher et al., 2008). Therefore, patients coming\nto the ED with severe breakthrough cancer pain may be justifiably\n\nfearful that their pain may not be addressed in a timely or adequate\nmanner.\nAssessing severity of malignant pain in the ED using a standardized pain scale such as the numerical rating scale is an important\nfirst step (Todd, 2005). Severe pain in malignancy has been referred\nto as a ‘cancer pain emergency’ and rapid titration of parenteral\nopioids has been demonstrated to provide effective and safe control\nof pain while concurrently addressing oth"},{"id": "3.5","title": "Palliative Care in the Nursing Home","chapter": "3.5","section": "3","sectionLabel": "Service Delivery","start": 143,"end": 157,"pages": 15,"weight": 0.012,"text": "CHAPTER 3.5 Palliative care in the nursing home\n\nessential for optimizing care outcomes and reducing unnecessary\nhospitalization.\nIn 2005, there were potentially US$3.1 billion of avoidable US\nhospitalizations, with 85% of these total costs related to nursing\nhome residents being transferred to acute care (Ouslander and\nBerenson, 2011). Suboptimal communication between nursing\nhome personnel, residents and families, inadequate care processes,\nlack of access to necessary equipment and/​or skilled onsite personnel, and a failure to determine the preferred goals of care all\ncontribute to potentially avoidable hospitalizations (Unroe et al.,\n2018). It is estimated that one in four older people admitted to a US\nnursing home directly from hospital has an acute care readmission\nwithin 30 days (Ouslander and Berenson, 2011). Any potentially\navoidable hospitalizations increase healthcare costs (Ouslander and\nBerenson, 2011).\nOver the past decade, reducing nursing home hospitalization rates\nhas been a policy priority in high-​income countries (Grabowski\net al., 2008), largely driven by the need to reduce both the adverse\neffects of hospitalization and excessive healthcare costs (Kelley et al.,\n2011). Averting this trend requires multifaceted interventions that\nstrategically build nursing homes’ capacity to align the resident’s\ngoals of care with hospitalization decisions, and change institutional\npatterns of care, physician practice patterns, and resident and family\npreferences (Kelley et al., 2011). Tested interventions to reduce the\nhospitalization of older adults have largely focused on standardizing\nclinical practice, geriatric specialist services, and influenza vaccination (Graverholt et al., 2014). For example, the Interventions to\nReduce Acute Care Transfers II (INTERACT II) quality improvement project achieved a 17% reduction in hospitalizations across\n25 US nursing homes and improved the identification, evaluation,\nand management of residents’ acute changes by providing tools, on-​\nsite education, and fortnightly teleconferences facilitated by a nurse\npractitioner (Ouslander et al., 2011).\n\nAccess to hospice and specialist palliative care input\nIn the US, the Medicare Hospice Benefit supports delivery of hospice care across all care settings, including nursing homes where\n36% of all beneficiaries reside. Three quarters (76%) of US nursing\nhomes now have an established contract with a hospice provider\n(Gozalo and Miller, 2007). Hospice care increases the residents’\naccess to care protocols and pain management, and reduces hospitalization rates during the last month of life (Gozalo and Miller,\n2007) and the number of residents who die in hospital (Munn et al.,\n2006; Gozalo et al., 2008). In contrast, hospitalized patients with dementia are more likely than non-​demented patients to have a longer\nterminal stay (Guijarro et al., 2010) and less likely to receive palliative treatment or have their families involved in decision-​making\n(Afzal et al., 201"},{"id": "4.1","title": "The Core and Extended Palliative Care Team","chapter": "4.1","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 159,"end": 165,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 4.1 The core team and the extended team\n\nrecognized as a valuable tool for professional growth and support\nand has an important role in preventing and solving team conflicts\n(Speck, 2006, pp. 95–​115).\n\nPhilosophy and attitudes toward teamwork\nTeam members’ attitudes towards teamwork have been shown to be\ncrucial for team performance (Reese and Sontag, 2001; Crawford\nand Price, 2003). These attitudes are rooted in their understanding\nof what teamwork really means. Freeman and co-​workers identified\nthree philosophies of teamwork (Freeman et al., 2000):\n• The directive philosophy is based on the assumption of hierarchy\nin the team. One person takes the lead by virtue of status and\npower and directs the actions of the other team members.\n• The integrative philosophy assumes that each professional’s contribution has equal value. All team members are seen as team\nplayers, and communication and discussions within the team are\ngiven vital importance.\n• The elective philosophy of teamwork is held by professionals who\nprefer clear and distinct team roles to operate autonomously and\nonly relate briefly to other team members when they see a need\nfor it themselves.\n\nInterdisciplinary team development\nThe majority of palliative care teams have started from an enthusiastic individual convinced of the need for and usefulness of\nspecialist palliative care. Although probably no team may come\ninto being without at least one such committed person, a structured planning process will save time and frustration (Dunlop and\nHockley, 1998; Doyle, 2009).\nThe size and composition of the team should be based on a thorough needs assessment which in turn leads to clear task objectives\nand careful job descriptions (Doyle, 2009). In many cases, the team\nwill be formed from practitioners already employed by the institution, brought together from different departments and grouped\ninto a team. This situation is not ideal and calls for a dedicated team\nleader, well-​defined roles for the team members, and strong support\nfrom the institution’s management and organization.\nTheory describing the phases of team development has been\nbased on years of research related to group processes (Tuckman and\nJensen, 1977; Drinka, 1994; Speck 2006, pp. 117–​136) and may be\nhelpful to understand team dynamics and guide a team in the right\ndirection:\n• Forming is the first phase when the group constitutes itself and\nfaces its task for the first time. The team members feel insecure\nand test out behaviour in the group. The group is dependent on a\nformal leader. In this phase, it is important to develop rules and\nmethods for the work on the team and define the tasks for each\nteam member.\n• Storming is the characteristic phase of turbulence, critical opposition, and power struggle which often follows once the team is\nestablished. Conflicts arise between subgroups, and differences in\nopinion and competition between team members appear.\n\n• Norming characterizes the next phase when the team player"},{"id": "4.2","title": "Burnout, Compassion Fatigue, and Moral Distress","chapter": "4.2","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 166,"end": 180,"pages": 15,"weight": 0.012,"text": "168\n\nSECTION 4 Healthcare professionals in palliative care\n\ndistress, in turn, may be precipitated by the perceived inability to\nlive up to one’s own standards or provide an idealized, and often\nunattainable, vision of the ‘good death’.\nReward\nLimited or inadequate financial rewards for the extremely challenging work of palliative care can contribute to burnout (Hammig\net al., 2012; van der Doef et al., 2012; Tang et al., 2018). Lack of\nreward may also relate to the lack of institutional reward to support\nthe development of palliative care services or to provide for the psychosocial and supervision requirements of the clinical staff.\nEmotion work variables\nWhen patients die, professional caregivers may experience grief,\nloss, or chronic grief, particularly if the relationships was long\n(Vachon, 1999; Merluzzi et al., 2011). Coping with grief reactions\nmay be especially difficult when patients or their children are\nyoung, the patient’s distress was poorly uncontrolled, staff feel that\nthey were unable to deliver the best possible care, or the death was\ncontextually inappropriate (such as deaths arising from the side effects of treatment). Repeated intense involvement with the distress\nof patients and their families in the time leading up to and after\nthe death can traumatize healthcare providers and contribute to\n‘the compassion fatigue syndrome’ (Slocum-​Gori et al., 2011) (see\n‘Compassion fatigue’), characterized by avoidance of contact with\nthe patient, a negative self-​assessment of performance, and a host\nof other responses that may adversely impact personal and professional well-​being and function. Professionals must continually\nbalance support for those facing death with the need to avoid being\noverwhelmed by the patient’s suffering.\n\nThe resulting combination of an exaggerated sense of responsibility, doubt, and guilt can have an enormous impact on clinicians’\nprofessional, personal, and family lives (Spickard et al., 2002;\nShanafelt et al., 2006). An increased risk of burnout also has been\nobserved among clinicians with passive coping styles (Yu et al.,\n2016); lower levels of agreeableness, conscientiousness, extraversion, and openness (De la Fuente-​Solana et al., 2017); and negative\nattitudes towards emotional expression (Granek et al., 2017).\n\nDemographic variables associated with burnout\nAge\nYounger professionals report more stressors and exhibit more manifestations of stress, fewer coping strategies (Vachon, 1995), and a\nhigher risk of burnout and stress reactions (Kuerer et al., 2007). The\nprevalence of burnout among young oncologists has been reported\nto be extremely high (72%) (Banerjee et al., 2017). Furthermore,\nsome studies have found that caregivers with more years of experience are less likely to report stress-​related symptoms and burnout\n(Vachon, 1995; Whippen et al., 2004); this, however, has not been a\nconsistent finding (Allegra et al., 2005).\nGender\nThe data on gender as a risk factor is conflicted and inconclusive.\nAl"},{"id": "4.3","title": "Nursing Education in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.3","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 181,"end": 190,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 4.3 Nursing education in palliative care\n\nBox 4.3.1 AACN CARES competencies: 17 new competencies\nfor educating undergraduate nursing students to improve\npalliative care\nCompetencies new nurses need to have completed by the end of their\nundergraduate nursing education are the following:\n1 Promote the need for palliative care for seriously ill patients and\ntheir families, from the time of diagnosis, as essential to quality care\nand an integral component of nursing care.\n2 Identify the dynamic changes in population demographics,\nhealthcare economics, service delivery, caregiving demands,\nand financial impact of serious illness on the patient and\nfamily that necessitate improved professional preparation for\npalliative care.\n3 Recognize one’s own ethical, cultural, and spiritual values and\nbeliefs about serious illness and death.\n4 Demonstrate respect for cultural, spiritual, and other forms of diversity for patients and their families in the provision of palliative\ncare services.\n5 Educate and communicate effectively and compassionately with\nthe patient, family, healthcare team members, and the public about\npalliative care issues.\n6 Collaborate with members of the interprofessional team to improve palliative care for patients with serious illness, to enhance the\nexperience and outcomes from palliative care for patients and their\nfamilies, and to ensure coordinated and efficient palliative care for\nthe benefit of communities.\n7 Elicit and demonstrate respect for the patient and family values,\npreferences, goals of care, and shared decision-​making during serious illness and at end of life.\n8 Apply ethical principles in the care of patients with serious illness\nand their families.\n9 Know, apply, and effectively communicate current state and federal\nlegal guidelines relevant to the care of patients with serious illness\nand their families.\n10 Perform a comprehensive assessment of pain and symptoms\ncommon in serious illness, using valid, standardized assessment\ntools and strong interviewing and clinical examination skills.\n11 Analyze and communicate with the interprofessional team in\nplanning and intervening in pain and symptom management,\nusing evidence-​based pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic\napproaches.\n12 Assess, plan, and treat patients’ physical, psychological, social, and\nspiritual needs to improve quality of life for patients with serious\nillness and their families.\n13 Evaluate patient and family outcomes from palliative care within\nthe context of patient goals of care, national quality standards,\nand value.\n14 Provide competent, compassionate, and culturally sensitive care\nfor patients and their families at the time of diagnosis of a serious\nillness through the end of life.\n15 Implement self-​care strategies to support coping with suffering,\nloss, moral distress, and compassion fatigue.\n16 Assist the patient, family, informal caregivers, and professional\ncolleagues to cope with and build resilience for dealing with\nsuffering, grief, loss"},{"id": "4.4","title": "Social Work in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.4","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 191,"end": 197,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 4.4 Social work in palliative care\n\nbe understood as the integrated collection of socially determined\nand transmitted customs and beliefs, shaping the values of a given\ngroup of people, influencing how they behave and interpret the\nworld around them (Kemp, 2005; Young-​Laing, 2009). Therefore,\nhow an individual understands quality of life, pain and suffering,\ncaregiving, illness, and spiritual and social functioning, for example,\ncan be inextricably linked to their culture. Clinicians able to identify\nculturally syntonic ways to intervene or connect with community\nresources, may help facilitate positive clinical outcomes and sustain\nthe patient and family as they transition through levels of care and\nstages of illness.\nThe assessment process may include screening and/​or assessment\ntools. Alternatively, it may be based in questions and conversation\ndesigned to validate the person and family beyond the illness, discover or elaborate areas of strength and resilience, concerns, sources\nof distress and suffering, and practical needs. At the heart of assessment is relationship grounded in communication, verbal and non-​\nverbal, critical thinking, and reflection. As such, assessment also\nacts as an intervention. The critical thinking that informs discussion\nand conversation often serves to uncover relevant history and the\nmeanings or interpretations attributed by patient and family to the\nvarious aspects of the illness experience. Inquiry about mood, sleep,\nintimacy, or pleasure may assist in identifying anxiety, depression,\nfatigue, or pain leading to an interdisciplinary treatment plan. Social\nworkers with knowledge of symptoms bring valuable observations\nto medical and nursing colleagues for the purpose of exploring aetiology, informing a treatment plan responsive to multidimensional\nfactors that often shape patient and family experience of symptoms\n(Cagle and Altilio, 2011; Walsh and Hedlund, 2011; Altilio and\nEskra Tropeano, 2015).\nThe following aspects of biopsychosocial-​spiritual assessment\ninform and enrich the comprehensive, patient-​centred, person-​\nin-​environment approach that is essential to palliative care. The\nelements in Box 4.4.1 are synthesized from Gwyther et al.’s competency document (2005), the National Association of Social Workers\n(2004) standards for palliative and end of life care, and the Oxford\nTextbook of Palliative Social Work.\nSocial work interventions link to assessment, setting, and the\nunique circumstance of the patient and their families. Table 4.4.1\nincorporates interventions reflecting a potential range of skills and\ntechniques integrated into palliative social work.\n\nFamily meetings: enhancing communication\nPalliative care seeks to address the needs of the whole patient\nincluding, in most instances, family who assist in contextualizing\nthe patient’s life and are also affected by the illness. In the most generic sense, family encompasses biological families, families of creation, friends, and other persons "},{"id": "4.5","title": "The Role of the Chaplain in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.5","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 198,"end": 205,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "200\n\nSECTION 4 Healthcare professionals in palliative care\n\nThis definition was agreed to by a large international group from\nmany faith and non-​faith traditions and philosophical backgrounds\nand disciplines. The focus on ‘meaning and purpose’ and ‘connectedness’ are themes in most definitions of spirituality.\nReligion is one expression of spirituality. ‘Religion is an organized\nsystem of beliefs, practices, rituals, and symbols designated (a) to facilitate closeness to the sacred or transcendent (God, higher power,\nor ultimate truth/​reality), and (b) to foster understanding of one’s\nrelationship and responsibility to others living in a community’\n(Koenig et al., 2001, p. 18).\nBut there are other expressions including nature, art, and humanism, among others.\nAnother ambiguity in the field is the frequent conflation of ‘spiritual care’, ‘chaplaincy care’, and ‘pastoral care’. The US Association of\nProfessional Chaplains and others have adopted the following distinctive definitions:\n• Spiritual care: ‘Interventions, individual or communal, that facilitate the ability to express the integration of the body, mind,\nand spirit to achieve wholeness, health, and a sense of connection to self, others, and[/​or] a higher power’ (Health Ministries\nAssociation, 2005)\n• Chaplaincy care: ‘Care provided by a board certified chaplain or\nby a student in an accredited clinical pastoral education program,\ne.g., ACPE. Examples of such care include emotional, spiritual,\nreligious, pastoral, ethical, and/​or existential care’ (Peery, 2009).\nPastoral care is now understood as a term that comes out of the\nChristian tradition and generally describes the care given by a faith\nleader to members of his or her community (LaRocca-​Pitts, 2006).\nAs such, it is inconsistent with the current multifaith emphasis.\nAll members of the healthcare team participate in spiritual care\nto some degree as they all participate in psychosocial and to some\ndegree physical care. Chaplaincy care encompasses those functions\nwhich require the spiritual care specialist on the team with the degree of training required. Pastoral care under this definition could\nbe part of what the particular chaplain does when he or she is caring\nfor people from his or her own faith tradition. Otherwise, it is generally part of what Christian clergy do when they care for their own\ncongregants. Pastoral care is still the term used in many parts of the\nworld to encompass what is here called chaplaincy care and maybe\neven spiritual care. We believe that the definitions proposed here,\nbesides being more commonly accepted, clear some confusion and\nare useful to the present model and the principles of palliative care.\n\nModel for chaplaincy in palliative care\nIn the model of interprofessional spiritual care, the role of the chaplain is to be the spiritual care lead on the team and, as such, the spiritual care specialist (Handzo and Koenig, 2004). All other members\nof the team are spiritual care generalists. Thus, social w"},{"id": "4.6","title": "Occupational Therapy in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.6","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 206,"end": 212,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "208\n\nSECTION 4 Healthcare professionals in palliative care\n\nthrough helping them to maintain as much independence as possible during the advanced stages of disease and this in turn helps to\ndecrease the burden of care on the family and caregiver.\nRehabilitation in palliative care improves quality of life through\neasing mobility, activities of daily living, endurance, and the psychological well-​being of the person (Barawid et al., 2015). A patient feels empowered and their self-​confidence is enhanced when\nthey are actively involved in their rehabilitation and regain a sense\nof control over their daily activities (Okamura, 2011). It is essential that the occupational therapist maintains a flexible approach\nregarding the varying symptoms that the patient may exhibit as a\nresult of advanced disease and adapting goals as a person’s clinical\ncondition changes.\nGoal setting is a vital component of therapeutic interventions and\nits value has been demonstrated within the palliative care setting\n(Jennings, 2010). Through collaboration with the patient and their\ncarers if appropriate, the occupational therapist sets specific, realistic, achievable, and measurable goals for what the patient wants\nto achieve.\nBy applying grading techniques to an activity, the occupational\ntherapist can adjust it depending on how the patient is managing.\nThis is done by adapting the environment—​\nsuch as moving\nfurniture—​\nor providing equipment. Additionally, techniques\nsuch as backward and forward chaining may be used. Backward\nchaining requires the occupational therapist to complete all the\nnecessary steps; for example, the occupational therapist would\nassist with showering the patient and let them complete the last\nstep. Forward chaining means that the patient completes the first\nstep and the occupational therapist completes the remainder of\nthe activity. Increasing the number of steps which the patient\ncan manage helps build up their stamina and skills. Similarly,\nwhen a person deteriorates, engaging that person and the family\nin a staged functional decline can help them adjust to changing\ncircumstances and will enable them to not feel as vulnerable\n(Jeyasingam et al., 2008).\nSafety is a vital issue which must not be taken lightly. Safety can\nbe improved by providing appropriate equipment, but the patient\nand carers may be put at risk if a thorough assessment is not carried out and all the potential hazards are not taken into consideration. For example, a motorized wheelchair or stair lift might sound\nas though it would be the answer to someone’s mobility problems,\nbut the person’s cognitive skills, physical balance, abilities, general\nstamina, and financial situation would all need very careful assessment by the occupational therapist. Equally, patients and their caregivers may choose to accept some risks if these are discussed with\nthe occupational therapist and mutually agreed.\n\nManagement of cognitive and perceptual\nimpairments\nCognitive and perceptual deficits, inc"},{"id": "4.9","title": "Physiotherapy in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.9","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 225,"end": 230,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "CHAPTER 4.9 Physiotherapy in palliative care\n\n• To gather information on disease history, co-morbidities, rate of deterioration and life expectancy,\nmedication, cognition, mood, current symptoms, functional status, and social situation.\nVerbal\nassessment\n\nPhysical\nassessment\n\nVisual\nassessment\n\n• Discussion with patient and family on how symptoms and functional limitations affect everyday\nactivities and their ability to cope. Therefore, identifying caregiver needs as well as patient needs.\n\n• Physical examination as required to assess respiratory, muscular, or neurological problems.\n• Identification of deformities or limitations related to disease, i.e. resticted range of movement in\njoints.\n\n• Observation of patient’s current function and ability to do functional tasks.\n• Identification of how certain impairments limit function such as breathelssness or lack of confidence.\n• Assessment of home environment and environmental or social factors influencing a patient’s function.\n\n• Negotiate and set patient goals based on what the patient identifies as important to them and\ntheir current functional ability relating to that goal.\nGoal setting\n\n• Set a realistic time frame to achieve the goal based on patient’s condition and available time and\nresources.\n\n• Identifiy activities/intervention required to address symptoms/functional limitations aimed at\nimproving function and achieving patient-set goals.\nTreatment\nplan\n\n• Treatment plans should be individualized and based on the patient’s overall prognosis, potential to\nmaintain or regain function, and motivation to participate in the programme.\n\nFig. 4.9.2 Process of physiotherapy assessment and treatment planning in palliative care.\n\nCounteracting declining physical function\nFunctional decline during progressive illness is multifaceted and\nmay be sudden or gradual (Amblas-​Novellas et al., 2016). Gradually\ndeclining function, exemplified by patients with neurological conditions such as multiple sclerosis and Parkinson’s disease, may be\nengaged by physiotherapists over long periods, with constant reassessment and adjustments to care. More rapid decline, such as occurs when metastatic spinal cord compression complicates cancer,\nmay offer opportunities for the physical therapist to help in a more\ncompressed timeframe. Indeed, spinal cord compression may be an\noncological emergency and the physiotherapist may be positioned to\nalert the team so that treatment with radiotherapy or surgery, if indicated, can be optimized (Al-​Hakim et al., 2006). If loss of motor, sensory, and autonomic function below the level of compression evolves,\nthe physiotherapist can help the patient to adapt to a rapid reduction\nin functional ability and to develop coping strategies (Lee et al., 2012).\nPhysiotherapists have expertise in movement analysis and functional assessment, enabling them to develop individual treatment\nplans with each patient. Their scope of practice includes improving\nfunction where the patient has capacity, m"},{"id": "4.11","title": "Clinical Psychology in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.11","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 241,"end": 247,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 4.11 Clinical psychology in palliative care\n\n4.11\n\nClinical psychology in palliative care\nE. Alessandra Strada\n\nIntroduction\nIn the past decade, the field of palliative care has grown at an impressive rate. This growth has increased the availability of specialist\npalliative care services and improved the quality and sophistication\nof the care provided. As a result, specialist palliative care has expanded beyond the management of pain and other distressing physical symptoms to include ongoing assessment and management of\npsychological and psychiatric distress. Careful attention to the needs\nof the patient and family caregivers in the psychological domain\nshould begin at diagnosis and be ongoing throughout treatment\nand transitions of care. This specialist-​level and evidence-​based\npsychological assessment and intervention is critically important\nto support emotional well-​being, address challenging personal and\nfamily dynamics, improve communication with the treating team,\nand manage psychological distress that has become pathological.\nDue to their training and expertise, clinical psychologists can\nprovide essential contributions to palliative care. This is evident\nby the American Psychological Association description of clinical\npsychology as ‘the psychological specialty that provides continuing\nand comprehensive mental and behavioral care for individuals and\nfamilies; consultations to agencies and communities; training, education, and supervision; and research-​based practice. It is a specialty\nin breadth—​one that is broadly inclusive of psychopathology—​and\nmarked by comprehensiveness and integration of knowledge and\nskills from a broad array of disciplines within and outside of psychology proper. The scope of clinical psychology encompasses all ages,\nmultiple diversities, and varied systems’ (American Psychological\nAssociation, 2016).\nClinical psychologists with specialist knowledge and skills in\npalliative care can be described as palliative psychologists. Like\nother disciplines (palliative social work, palliative nursing, palliative medicine), clinical psychology should identify and promote\nthe competencies associated with palliative psychology. A working\ndefinition is: ‘a specialty of psychology aimed at relieving physical,\npsychological, and existential distress and suffering in patients with\nserious and advanced illness and their family caregivers. Palliative\npsychology is patient-​centered, and it involves the specialized use\nof psychological assessment and intervention to improve pain and\nother physical symptoms, as well as psychological distress. Palliative\npsychology is grounded in a holistic and strength-​based approach\n\nthat aims at promoting psychological well-​being for the patient and\nfamily caregivers throughout transitions of care, including the death\nand dying process and in bereavement’ (Strada, 2018, p. xx).\nWhether as core members of a palliative care team or as consultants, palliative psychologists can become inv"},{"id": "4.12","title": "The Clinical Pharmacist in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.12","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 248,"end": 254,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "250\n\nSECTION 4 Healthcare professionals in palliative care\n\nSanso, N., Galiana, L., Oliver, A., Pascual, A., Sinclair, S., and Benito, E.\n2015. Palliative care professionals’ inner life: Exploring the relationship\namong awareness, self-​care, and compassion, satisfaction and fatigue,\nburnout, and coping with death. J Pain Symptom Manage, 50, 200–​207.\nSchildman, E. and Schildman, J. 2014. Palliative sedation therapy: a\nsystematic literature review and critical appraisal of available guidance on indication and decision making. J Palliat Med, 17, 601–​611.\nSchuler, T. A., Zaider, T. I., Li, Y., et al. 2017. Perceived family functioning predicts baseline psychosocial characteristics in US participants of a family focused grief therapy trial. J Pain Symptom\nManage, 54, 126–​131.\nShear, M. K., Reynolds, C. F., 3rd, Simon, N. M., et al. 2016. Optimizing\ntreatment of complicated grief: a randomized clinical trial. JAMA\nPsychiatry, 73, 685–​694.\nSkritskaya, N. A., Mauro, C., Olonoff, M., et al. 2017. Measuring maladaptive cognitions in complicated grief: introducing the typical beliefs questionnaire. Am J Geriatr Psychiatry, 25, 541–​550.\nStrada, E. A. 2013. Grief and Bereavement in the Adult Palliative Care\nSetting. New York: Oxford University Press.\nStrada, E. A. 2018. Palliative Psychology: Clinical Perspectives on an\nEmerging Specialty. New York: Oxford University Press.\nStrada, E. A. and Breitbart, W. 2015. Training psychologists and psychiatrists in palliative care. In: Holland, J. C., Breitbart, W. S., Butow, P. N.,\nJacobsen, P. B., Loscalzo, M. J., and McCorkle, R. M. (Eds.), Psycho-​\nOncology, 3rd ed. (pp. 259–​263). New York: Oxford University Press.\nStrada, E. A. and Portenoy, R. K. 2015. Psychological, rehabilitative,\nand integrative therapies for cancer pain. UpToDate. [Online]\nAvailable at: https://​www.uptodate.com/​contents/​psychological-​\nrehabilitative-​and-​integrative-​therapies-​for-​cancer-​pain\nVeloso, V. I. and Tripodoro, V. A. 2016. Caregivers burden in palliative\ncare patients: a problem to tackle. Curr Opin Support Palliat Care,\n10, 330–​335.\nYu, D. S. F., Chan, H. Y. L., Leung, D. Y. P., Hui, E., and Sit, J. W. H.\n2016. Symptom cluster and quality of life among patients with advanced heart failure. J Geriatr Cardiol, 13, 408–​414.\n\nCHAPTER 4.12 The contribution of the clinical pharmacist in palliative care\n\n4.12\n\nThe contribution of the clinical\npharmacist in palliative care\nEbtesam Ahmed\n\nIntroduction to the contribution of the clinical\npharmacist in palliative care\nPalliative care is defined as ‘an approach that improves the quality of\nlife of patients and their families facing the problem associated with\nlife-​threatening illness, through the prevention and relief of suffering\nby means of early identification and impeccable assessment and\ntreatment of pain and other problems—​physical, psychosocial, and\nspiritual’ (World Health Organization, 2017). In order to fulfil the\ncomplex needs of terminally ill patients, palliative"},{"id": "4.13","title": "Medical Rehabilitation in Palliative Care","chapter": "4.13","section": "4","sectionLabel": "Healthcare Professionals","start": 255,"end": 265,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 4.12 The contribution of the clinical pharmacist in palliative care\n\nDickman, A. and Schneider, J. 2011. The Syringe Driver: Continuous\nSubcutaneous Infusions in Palliative Care. Oxford: Oxford\nUniversity Press.\nDiScala, S. L., Onofrio, S., Miller, M., Nazario, M., and Silverman, M.\n2016. Integration of a clinical pharmacist into an interdisciplinary\npalliative care outpatient clinic. Am J Hosp Palliat Care, 34, 814–​819.\nDispennette, R., Hall, L. A., and Elliott, D. P. 2015. Activities of palliative care and pain management clinical pharmacists. Am J Health\nSyst Pharm, 72, 999–​1000.\nGilbar, P. and Stefanuik, K. 2002. The role of the pharmacist in palliative care: results of a survey conducted in Australia and Canada. J\nPalliat Care, 18, 287–​292.\nHanif, N. 1991. Role of the palliative care unit pharmacist. J Palliat\nCare, 7, 35–​36.\nHerndon, C. M., Strassels, S. A., Strickland, J. M., et al. 2012.\nConsensus recommendations from the strategic planning summit\nfor pain and palliative care pharmacy practice. J Pain Symptom\nManage, 43, 925–​944.\nHolmes, H. M. and Todd, A. 2015. Evidence-​based deprescribing of\nstatins in patients with advanced illness. JAMA Intern Med, 175,\n701–​702.\nHorneber, M., Bueschel, G., Dennert, G., Less, D., Ritter, E., and\nZwahlen, M. 2012. How many cancer patients use complementary\nand alternative medicine: a systematic review and metaanalysis.\nIntegr Cancer Ther, 11, 187–​203.\nHussainy, S., Box, M., and Scholes, S. 2011. Piloting the role of a\npharmacist in a community palliative care multidisciplinary\nteam: an Australian experience. BMC Palliat Care, 10, 16.\nJiwa, M., O’Connor, M., Hughes, J., et al. 2007. The Role of the\nPharmacist in the Provision of Palliative Care. Canberra: Australian\nGovernment Department of Health and Ageing.\nKato, T. 2011. The role of home palliative care by health insurance\npharmacy. Jpn J Cancer Chemother, 38(Suppl. 1), 56–​58.\nKominek, C. and DiScala, S. 2014. Quality improvement project of\npharmacist-​assisted medication reconciliation and regimen review following veteran discharge to hospice. J Pharm Pharmacol, 2, 489–​500.\nLatuga, N. M., Wahler, R. G., and Monte, S. V. 2012. A national survey\nof hospital administrator and pharmacist perspectives on pharmacist services and the impact on medication requirements and cost.\nAm J Hosp Palliat Care, 29, 546–​554.\nLindsay, J., Dooley, M., Martin, J., et al. 2015. The development and evaluation of an oncological palliative care deprescribing guideline: the\n‘OncPal deprescribing guideline’. Support Care Cancer, 23, 71–​78.\nMa, J. D., Tran, V., Chan, C., Mitchell, W. M., and Atayee, R. S. 2016.\nRetrospective analysis of pharmacist interventions in an ambulatory palliative care practice. J Oncol Pharm Pract, 22, 757–​765.\nMolassiotis, A., Fernadez-​Ortega, P., Pud, D., et al. 2005. Use of complementary and alternative medicine in cancer patients: a European\nsurvey. Ann Oncol, 16, 655–​663.\nMonash University. 2018. Palliative care. [Online] Ava"},{"id": "5.1","title": "Communication with Patient and Family","chapter": "5.1","section": "5","sectionLabel": "Communication","start": 267,"end": 276,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 4.13 Medical rehabilitation and the palliative care patient\n\nSECTION 5\n\nCommunication and\npalliative medicine\n5.1 Communication with the patient and family 267\nThomas W. LeBlanc and James Tulsky\n5.2 Practical considerations including difficult\nconversations 277\nSusan D. Block\n\n5.3 Advance care planning 286\nJudith Rietjens, Ida Korfage, and Jane Seymour\n\n269\n\n270\n\nSECTION 5 Communication and palliative medicine\n\nCHAPTER 5.1 Communication with the patient and family\n\n5.1\n\nCommunication with the patient\nand family\nThomas W. LeBlanc and James Tulsky\n\nIntroduction\nHigh-​quality palliative medicine care depends upon good communication. Effective, empathic communication can enhance the\nquality of care provided while also improving patient and family\nsatisfaction (Kaplan et al., 1989; Roter et al., 1995; Bertakis et al.,\n1991). Good communication fosters informed decision-​making by\nincreasing the likelihood that patient choices remain consistent with\nindividuals’ stated goals, values, and preferences. This is particularly\ntrue at moments when patients and families face clinical dilemmas\nwhich require relatively sudden and difficult decisions to be made,\noften without sufficient certainty about the likely outcomes. Finally,\nby guiding terminally ill patients away from ineffective treatments\ntowards care that is more likely to help them achieve realistic goals,\ngood communication may also increase the delivery of high-​value\ncare (Wright et al., 2008). Common conceptions of palliative care\n\nas being focused on convincing patients not to pursue aggressive\ntreatments are thereby misguided; goal-​concordant care is the true\nobjective of high-​quality communication in palliative medicine\n(Sanders et al., 2018).\nMuch of palliative medicine practice involves helping patients\nand families come to terms with serious illness and establish a care\nplan that reflects their values and priorities. For example, in the US,\nwhere 88% of hospitals with over 300 beds now have available specialist palliative care consult teams, a significant proportion of the\nwork done by these services involves the management of difficult\ncommunication scenarios in critical care or advanced illness such\nas incurable cancer or end-​stage heart failure (Center to Advance\nPalliative Care, 2012). Although symptom management is also\nkey, communication is perhaps the most important and powerful\nskill that specialist palliative care clinicians bring to these cases.\nIn fact, many palliative care clinicians believe that their specialist\n\nTable 5.1.1 Evidence-​based communication strategies\nTechnique\n\nExample\n\nReference\n\n‘I wish . . .’\n\n‘I wish the scan had turned out better for you’\n\nQuill, T.E., Arnold, R.M., and Platt, F. (2001). ‘I wish things were\ndifferent’: expressing wishes in response to loss, futility, and\nunrealistic hopes. Ann Intern Med. 135(7), 551–​555. DOI: 10.7326/​\n0003-​4819-​135-​7-​200110020-​00022.\n\n‘Hope for the\nbest . . .’\n\n‘I hope this treatment works well too. Let’s "},{"id": "5.2","title": "Practical Considerations and Difficult Conversations","chapter": "5.2","section": "5","sectionLabel": "Communication","start": 277,"end": 285,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 5.1 Communication with the patient and family\n\nthat ignores emotional content, and may actually be more efficient\n(Fogarty et al., 1999; McDonagh et al., 2004; Kennifer et al., 2009).\nProactively addressing patients’ needs, setting an agenda for each\nvisit, and ensuring that patients feel heard can actually be done\nrelatively quickly, and can avoid time-​consuming problems later.\nIt probably also improves the patient–​doctor relationship (Fenton\net al., 2018).\nHigh-​\nquality empathic communication also depends upon\nthe mindset of the clinician. When clinicians feel harried or disconnected in their practise of medicine, they are unable to focus\nmeaningfully on the patient’s concerns. ‘Mindfulness’ refers to\nthe practice of being consciously present in everyday activities.\nAn intervention that helps clinicians achieve such mindful practice has been associated with less burnout and mood disturbance\namong primary care physicians, and at least a subjective sense of\nbeing more present with patients (Krasner et al., 2009). Finally, it is\npossible that conscious daily practice of empathic communication\nbehaviours leads to longer-​term improvements in communication\nskill (Fallowfield et al., 2003).\n\nConclusion\nCommunication in clinical practice is not intuitive, and requires\nconscious practice in order to achieve competency. This is especially true in the palliative care setting, where specialists are increasingly expected to help navigate difficult clinical situations,\nmany of which involve communication challenges, or prior communication mistakes that complicate future encounters. Good\ncommunication can be deconstructed and conceptualized as a\nseries of discrete behaviours. It is thus measurable, teachable, and\nlearnable. Research shows that clinicians tend to overestimate\ntheir communication abilities, and that patients and families want\nbetter communication from the medical team, especially in settings of serious illness or at the end of life. They prefer open-​ended,\nempathic communication and honest disclosure, even in the face\nof a bad prognosis. Family members expect to be listened to, and\nheard, to be involved in decision-​making, and hope to be attended\nto even after the death of their loved one. As compassionate caregivers, palliative care specialists, and indeed all clinicians, we owe\nit to our patients and families to improve the quality of our communication, and to make this a conscious component and focus of\nour daily practice.\n\nREFERENCES\nAlexander, S. C., Keitz, S. A., Sloane, R., and Tulsky, J. A. 2006. A controlled trial of a short course to improve residents’ communication\nwith patients at the end of life. Acad Med, 81, 1008–​1012.\nApatira, L., Boyd, E. A., Malvar, G., et al. 2008. Hope, truth, and preparing for death: perspectives of surrogate decision makers. Ann\nIntern Med, 149, 861–​868.\nApter, A. J., Paasche-​\nOrlow, M. K., Remillard, J. T., et al. 2008.\nNumeracy and communication with patients: they are counting on\nus. J "},{"id": "5.3","title": "Advance Care Planning","chapter": "5.3","section": "5","sectionLabel": "Communication","start": 286,"end": 292,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "288\n\nSECTION 5 Communication and palliative medicine\n\nand the clinician’s own vulnerabilities. Authenticity, honesty, and\nempathy are essential. Achieving a balance between hope and\nrealism as a serious illness progresses requires its own juggling for\nthe clinician. Supporting the patient’s self-​care and efforts towards\ncontrol and mastery, while also appreciating the intense vulnerabilities and dependency that serious illness brings, calls for flexibility\nand a delicate touch. For the clinician, maintaining morale in the\nface of failed or disappointing efforts to relieve suffering, intense,\noverwhelming emotional distress, and intolerable systems dysfunction necessitates self-​knowledge, a commitment to ongoing,\nsometimes painful self-​reflection, and the support of colleagues. All\ncommunication is more challenging when these conditions are not\nmet. Burnout lurks in the wings.\nThese difficulties are magnified when patients, families, and\nclinicians bring particular vulnerabilities and coping styles to the\nencounter.\nUnderlying an understanding of communication challenges in\nthis context is the premise that communication is a dyadic/​triadic\nphenomenon, in which both clinician and patient (and family) all\nplay interacting roles. A calm and reserved patient whose family\nmembers are extremely anxious will require a different communication approach than a highly anxious patient with a distant and\ndetached family—​applying the same approach to both is likely to\nescalate, rather than ameliorate distress. This chapter reviews commonly encountered communication challenges in patients, family\nmembers, and clinicians that arise in conducting conversations\nabout serious illness and proposes strategies (and language) that\ncan be used to address them. Prognostic discussions are especially\nchallenging to patients, families, and clinicians and are dealt with in\na special section.\n\nCommonly encountered patient-​related\ncommunication issues\nAnxiety\nAnxiety is a normal and appropriate response to a perceived threat.\nIt arises especially in situations of uncertainty, helplessness, and\nbeing out of control. It is a virtually universal feature of serious\nillness; the content of anxiety usually focuses on survival, suffering,\nand concerns about loved ones. Both normal and dysfunctional\nanxiety that interferes with medical care, communication, relationships, and decision-​making arise in the clinical encounter, and can\nbe manifested as difficulty asking questions, retaining information,\navoidance, denial, and distrust (Miovic and Block, 2007). When\nasked, patients can often, but not always, acknowledge worry or\nnervousness.\nCommunication can play a major role in both mitigating and\nescalating anxiety. Gentle, honest, directness is a cornerstone of effective communication.\nOne of the key tasks of the clinician is helping the patient to tolerate the anxiety that arises in conversations about serious illness.\nAll patients, and especially those who demonstrate high level"},{"id": "6.1","title": "Family Dynamics in Serious Illness","chapter": "6.1","section": "6","sectionLabel": "Family and Caregivers","start": 295,"end": 302,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 5.3 Advance care planning\n\nthat is aligned to patients’ preferences and goals, to the benefit of\npatients and their relatives.\n\nREFERENCES\nAll Ireland Institute of Hospice and Palliative Care. 2014. Public Awareness\nCampaign: Report on public awareness raising, Palliative Care Week\n2014, October 6–​11. Dublin: All Ireland Institute of Palliative Care.\nBernacki, R. E., Block, S. D., and American College of Physicians High\nValue Care Task Force. 2014. Communication about serious illness\ncare goals: a review and synthesis of best practices. JAMA Intern\nMed, 174, 1994–​2003.\nBrinkman-​Stoppelenburg, A., Rietjens, J. A., and Van Der Heide, A.\n2014. The effects of advance care planning on end-​of-​life care: a systematic review. Palliat Med, 28, 1000–​1025.\nCandib, L. M. 2002. Truth telling and advance planning at the end\nof life: problems with autonomy in a multicultural world. Fam Syst\nHealth, 20, 213–​228.\nClayton, J. M., Hancock, K., Parker, S., et al. 2008. Sustaining hope\nwhen communicating with terminally ill patients and their families: a systematic review. Psychooncology, 17, 641–​659.\nCon, A. 2007. Cross-​Cultural Considerations in Promoting Advance\nCare Planning in Canada. Vancouver: Health Canada.\nCouncil of Europe. 2014. Guide on the Decision-​\nMaking Process\nRegarding Medical Treatment in End-​of-​Life Situations. Strasbourg:\nCouncil of Europe.\nDe Vleminck, A., Houttekier, D., Pardon, K., et al. 2013. Barriers and\nfacilitators for general practitioners to engage in advance care planning: a systematic review. Scand J Prim Health Care, 31, 215–​226.\nDillon, P. J., Roscoe, L. A., and Jenkins, J. J. 2012. African Americans\nand decisions about hospice care: implications for health message\ndesign. Howard J Comm, 23, 175–​193.\nErsek, M., Kagawa-​Singer, M., Barnes, D., Blackhall, L., and Koenig, B.\nA. 1998. Multicultural considerations in the use of advance directives. Oncol Nurs Forum, 25, 1683–​1690.\nFahner, J. C., Beunders, A. J. M., Van Der Heide, A., et al. 2019.\nInterventions guiding advance care planning conversations: a systematic review. J Am Med Dir Assoc, 20, 227–​248.\nFried, T. R., Redding, C. A., Robbins, M. L., Paiva, A. L., O’Leary, J.\nR., and Iannone, L. 2016. Development of personalized health\nmessages to promote engagement in advance care planning. J Am\nGeriatr Soc, 64, 359–​364.\nGauvin, F. P. and Lavis, J. N. 2013. Evidence Brief: Improving End-​of-​life\nCommunication, Decision-​making and Care in Ontario. Hamilton,\nON: McMaster Health Forum.\nHorne, G., Seymour, J., and Payne, S. 2012. Maintaining integrity in\nthe face of death: a grounded theory to explain the perspectives of\npeople affected by lung cancer about the expression of wishes for\nend of life care. Int J Nurs Stud, 49, 718–​726.\nHouben, C. H., Spruit, M. A., Groenen, M. T., Wouters, E. F., and\nJanssen, D. J. 2014. Efficacy of advance care planning: a systematic\nreview and meta-​analysis. J Am Med Dir Assoc, 15, 477–​89.\nInstitute of Medicine, Committee on Ap"},{"id": "6.2","title": "Caregiver Burden and Distress","chapter": "6.2","section": "6","sectionLabel": "Family and Caregivers","start": 303,"end": 311,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 6.1 Family dynamics in the context of serious illness\n\nthat they wish they had been taught some of the skills required for\ntheir caring role by healthcare providers rather than having to work\nthem out for themselves through ‘trial and error’. There are several\nunmet needs among caregivers. Some of the most commonly reported needs include:\n\nIn addition to these psychological and physical needs of the family,\nthere are considerable costs involved with caring for a loved one\nwith serious illness. These can be both direct and indirect, with at\nleast 25% of family carers being unable to continue employment,\nthus suffering substantial losses of income (Schofield et al., 1998).\nMany carers also find they lose friends (though others are surprised\nby those who are supportive), and are unable to continue prior\nlevels of involvement with sport or other interests. Given the wide-​\nranging effects of the caregiving role, comprehensive assessment is\nrequired when considering supportive care of these families.\n\nof advanced disease, as the family becomes more involved with\ncare, and is continued into bereavement to maintain continuity\nof care. Such an approach to screening families, with preventive\nintervention for those at risk, will become the necessary working\nmodel for the future.\nFamily assessments should be aimed at leading the health professional to an increased understanding of the medical and psychosocial situation of the family system. Developing an understanding\nof the major concerns of individual members and the family as a\nwhole empowers planning of appropriately focused interventions.\nWe find a checklist as portrayed in Box 6.1.1 helpful to ensure that\nfamily assessments are thorough in their detail.\nUnderstanding the impact of practical issues on the family is also\nimportant for effective functioning. Practical issues include the financial impact of serious illness on the family, the impact on work\nand home life, division of labour in the family, availability of family\nmembers to provide the care needs required, and the appropriateness of the physical surroundings to care for someone.\nIn addition to the specific concerns of the family, the clinician\nneeds to consider each family’s ability to adjust to change that is\ninevitable during palliative care. While a normal grief response is\nexpected following each change in disease status, the level of intervention required will depend on the ability of family members to\ncomfort and support each other.\n\nAssessing the family for intervention\n\nFamily-​centred principles for intervention\n\nWhile the impact of serious illness can be catastrophic enough to\nargue for an evaluation of each family, this is clearly not a practical option. It is more common for staff to develop concerns for\nfamily members when they are not providing expected practical or\nemotional support. This is also not an effective basis for decisions\nabout resource allocation. What is necessary is the ability to screen\nfor those familie"},{"id": "7.1","title": "Definition and Assessment of Chronic Pain","chapter": "7.1","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 313,"end": 320,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 7.1 Definition and assessment of chronic pain in advanced disease\n\ncommunity, 93% of those patients who experienced cancer pain at\nleast several times a month rated the severity as moderate to severe,\n44% described it as severe, and 3% regarded it as the worst pain imaginable (Breivik et al., 2009).\nLike pain itself, under-​treatment has many influencing factors.\nDiscrepancies between patient and physician rating of pain severity\nare one such predictor (deAndrea et al., 2008). Under-​treatment\nalso is more likely when patients have a better performance status\nor are in the early stages of their diseases, findings that may suggest\na reluctance to believe that those with early disease can have severe\npain or an increased likelihood that those with advanced disease are\nmanaged by specialists (deAndrea et al., 2008).\nIt is not clear if older age has an effect on pain management.\nEvidence from the cancer population suggests that there are no\ndifferences in pain intensity but older people may require less or\nmore analgesia than the younger population, perhaps due to altered physiology (Vigano et al., 1998; Hall et al., 2003; Mercadante\net al., 2006; Mercadante and Arcuri, 2007; van den Beuken-​van\nEverdingen et al., 2007a; Bennett et al., 2009). Older patients also\ndo not have more adverse effects or more need for opioid switching\n(Mercadante et al., 2006). However, they may have different attitudes towards opioids and therefore may be more reluctant to use\nthese drugs (Yeager et al., 1997; Closs et al., 2009).\n\nCharacterizing the pain complaint\nAssessing a patient’s pain should be a continual process supported\nby communication between patient, carer, and clinician. The aims\nare to characterize the complaint, correctly identify the underlying\npathophysiology, and determine the effect of pain on the patient’s\nlife. All of this information informs the management plan. Without\nthis focus on a comprehensive assessment, pain treatment becomes\nless targeted and less effective.\nA history and clinical examination are vital for pain assessment\nand radiological and laboratory tests may be indicated. Inadequate\npain control is most often due to a poor history and examination\n(Grossman et al., 1992; Von Roenn et al., 1993). Establishing the\neffect of pain on the person’s quality of life and activities of daily\nliving, recording previous effects of analgesic treatments, and exploring the patient’s goals and expectations are crucial in being\nable to effectively treat all aspects of pain’s impact on the person.\nCreating a trusting, open relationship encourages communication\nand allows patients to be involved in the management of their pain.\nConcerns generated by the experience of fear, such as worry about\ncancer progression or about the risks of addiction or tolerance to\nopioids, may affect the information given to the clinician.\n\nThe clinical history of pain\nThe acronym SOCRATES is useful in prompting systematic assessment of pain characteristics: Site, Onse"},{"id": "7.2","title": "Pathophysiology of Pain in Cancer","chapter": "7.2","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 321,"end": 332,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "CHAPTER 7.2 Pathophysiology of pain in cancer and other terminal illnesses\n\nTable 7.2.1 Algogenic ligands: their origins and their cognate\nreceptors\nLigand\n\nOrigin\n\nReceptor\n\nH+\n\nTissue damage, macrophages\n\nASIC, TRPV1\n\nBradykinin\n\nMacrophages, mast cells\n\nB2/​B1 (TRPV1)\n\nHistamine\n\nMast cells\n\nH1\n\nProstaglandins\n\nMast cells, fibroblasts\n\nEP\n\nNerve growth factor\n\nMacrophage, fibroblasts\n\nTrkA\n\nATP\n\nPlatelets, sympathetic terminals\n\nP2X3\n\nAdenosine\n\nTissue damage\n\nA1/​A2\n\n5-​HT\n\nPlatelets, mast cells\n\n5-​HTr\n\nIL-​1\n\nMacrophage\n\nIL-​1r\n\nHeat\n\nExogenous, inflammation\n\nTRPV\n\nCold\n\nTRPM8\n\nPeripheral sensitization also involves change in ion channels.\nTRPV1 is a ligand-​gated ion channel that is responsive to noxious heat and capsaicin, the pungent component of chili peppers\n(Caterina and Julius, 2001). Normally, this channel can drive a\nneural response when exposed to noxious heat; with inflammation,\nhowever, decreased tissue acidity can potentiate the response so\nthat it is active at temperatures nearer body temperature (Caterina\nand Julius, 2001). This is a good example of how inflammation may\ncause a lowering of the nociceptive threshold in peripheral fibres\nand how hyperalgesia can result. Intriguingly, a receptor for noxious\nmechanical transduction, a more obvious clinical issue, has yet to\nbe fully elucidated. In the future, therapy that targets a cognate receptor for mechanical noxious stimuli may be of great benefit.\n\nIon channels\nIon channels, which play a key role in normal electrical activity\nwithin sensory nerves, may change function after nerve damage\n(Suzuki et al., 2002), leading to the altered transduction and disordered neural activity associated with neuropathy. The opening\nof sodium channels depolarizes neurons and generates the action\npotential. Injury to a peripheral nerve can alter the normal arrangement of these channels along the length of a nerve. Neuromas that\ndevelop after axons are injured are associated with ‘ectopic’ electrical\nactivity, which results from the accumulation of sodium channels at\nthe site of injury. Adjacent nerves also may exhibit altered distribution and levels of these channels. Some inherited pain disorders\narise from genetic mutations that either increase or decrease the\nfunctioning of a specific sodium channel subtype known as Nav1.7\n(Yang et al., 2004; Cox et al., 2006) and less dramatic polymorphisms\nin this channel can have a clinical impact. The latter observation\nsuggests that inherited variations in channel function might be behind some of the variability in pain within patient groups (Reimann\net al., 2010). Blockers of Nav1.7 and Nav1.8, the major pain-​related\nchannels, have been described but have yet to reach the clinic and\ncurrent treatments use non-​selective blockers, such as lidocaine and\nsome anticonvulsants (e.g. carbamazepine (Suzuki et al., 2002)).\nImportantly, human data with oxcarbazepine, a sodium channel\n\nblocker, reveal that the drug is only effective in patients with evoked\nhyp"},{"id": "7.3","title": "Acute Cancer Pain Syndromes","chapter": "7.3","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 333,"end": 344,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "CHAPTER 7.3 Acute cancer pain syndromes\n\nextravasation may produce intense pain followed by desquamation\nand ulceration (Boulanger et al., 2015). Finally, a brief venous flare\nreaction is often associated with intravenous administration of the\nanthracycline, doxorubicin. The flare is typically associated with\nlocal urticaria and some patients report pain or stinging (Vogelzang,\n1979; Curran et al., 1990).\nHepatic artery infusion pain\nCytotoxic infusions into the hepatic artery (for patients with hepatic\nmetastases) are often associated with the development of a diffuse\nabdominal pain (Barnett and Malafa, 2001). Continuous infusions\ncan lead to persistent pain. In some patients, the pain is due to the\ndevelopment of gastric ulceration or erosions (Shike et al., 1986), or\ncholangitis (Batts, 1998). If the latter complications do not occur,\nthe pain usually resolves with discontinuation of the infusion.\nA dose relationship is suggested by the observation that some patients will comfortably tolerate reinitiating of the infusion at a lower\ndose (Kemeny, 1992).\nIntraperitoneal chemotherapy pain\nA transient, mild abdominal pain, associated with sensations of\nfullness or bloating, is reported by approximately 25% of patients\nafter intraperitoneal chemotherapy (Almadrones and Yerys, 1990;\nJaaback and Johnson, 2006; American College of Obstetricians and\nGynecologists, 2008). A further 25% of patients report moderate\nor severe pain necessitating opioid analgesia or discontinuation of\ntherapy (Almadrones and Yerys, 1990). Moderate or severe pain\nis usually caused by chemical serositis or infection (Jaaback and\nJohnson, 2006). Chemical serositis is a common complication of\nintraperitoneal infusion of the anthracycline agents mitoxantrone\nand doxorubicin and with Taxol®, but it is relatively infrequent with\n5-​fluorouracil or cis-​platinum. Pain may indicate suboptimal drug\ndistribution within the abdominal cavity. Some patients experience\ndiscomfort related to sensing abdominal distention, or from intercostal nerve irritation (Topuz et al., 2000). Abdominal pain associated with fever and leucocytosis in blood and peritoneal fluid is\nsuggestive of infectious peritonitis.\nHyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy pain\nThis refers to the administration of heated intraperitoneal chemotherapy which is indicated for mucinous carcinomas such as\nappendiceal carcinoma and pseudomyxoma peritonei after open\nsurgical debulking. This is a high-​risk procedure that is often complicated by shock, pain, and complications as such as peritonitis and\nanastomotic leaks (Yan et al., 2009).\nIntravesical chemo-​or immunotherapy\nIntravesical bacillus Calmette–​Guérin (BCG) therapy for transitional cell carcinoma of the urinary bladder usually causes a transient bladder irritability syndrome characterized by frequency\nand/​or micturition pain (Palou et al., 2001; Shelley et al., 2003,\n2004). Similarly, intravesical doxorubicin (Matsumura et al., 1992),\nmitomycin-​\nC (Shelley et al., "},{"id": "7.4","title": "Chronic Cancer Pain Syndromes","chapter": "7.4","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 345,"end": 363,"pages": 19,"weight": 0.0152,"text": "CHAPTER 7.4 Chronic cancer pain syndromes\n\nspinous processes). Spinal tenderness to percussion, which may be\nsevere, often accompanies the pain.\nImaging modalities\nDefinitive imaging of the epidural space confirms the existence of\nepidural compression (and thereby indicates the necessity and urgency of treatment), defines the appropriate radiation portals, and\ndetermines the extent of epidural encroachment (which influences\nprognosis and may alter the therapeutic approach).\nMagnetic resonance imaging\nMRI is non-​invasive and offers accurate imaging of the vertebrae\nand intraspinal and paravertebral structures. When available, it is\ngenerally the preferred mode of evaluation (Al-​Qurainy and Collis,\n2016; Ropper and Ropper, 2017). Whenever possible, total spine\nimaging should be performed since multiple-​level involvement is\ncommon and, other sites may be clinically occult. In a study of 65\npatients with cord compression, 32 (49%) showed multiple-​level involvement and of these, 28 (66%) were clinically occult (Heldmann\net al., 1997). MRI has multiple advantages: metastases can be distinguished from other pathological processes involving the axial\nskeleton, epidural and intradural space, and spinal cord. This is\nparticularly true for bacterial abscesses, leptomeningeal carcinomatosis, intradural extramedullary or, rarely, intramedullary metastases or primary tumours, and infectious or inflammatory myelitis.\nMRI is relatively contraindicated in patients with severe claustrophobia or certain metallic implants, and is absolutely contraindicated for patients with cardiac pacemakers or aneurysm clips.\nSeveral other groups who may not be suitable for MRI include very\nobese patients and those with severe kyphosis or scoliosis.\nComputed tomography\nSimilar to MRI, computed tomography (CT) scanning is non-​\ninvasive, and it provides excellent visualization of the vertebrae,\nvertebral structural integrity, paravertebral soft tissues, and of the\nvertebral foramina. The improved resolution observed with contemporary spiral techniques facilitates very clear imaging of the\nspinal canal contents. CT scanning of regions identified by either\nplain X-​ray or bone scan usually provides excellent visualization of\ncortical integrity; the intervertebral foramina and canal contents\nand correlation with MRI findings demonstrate very high sensitivity and specificity (Crocker et al., 2011). Bone and soft tissue\nwindows are used in a complementary manner; bone windows\nallow evaluation of bony integrity and, in particular, of cortical\nbreach, and soft tissue windows are used to evaluate the contents of\nthe spinal canal. Using this approach one can reserve more expensive and less readily available MRI for equivocal cases, when leptomeningeal metastases are suspected, or when total spinal imaging\nis required.\n\nPain syndromes of the bony pelvis and hip\nThe pelvis and hip are common sites of metastatic involvement.\nLesions may involve any of the three anatomical regions of the\npe"},{"id": "7.5","title": "Principles of Drug Therapy","chapter": "7.5","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 364,"end": 371,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "366\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\nTherapeutic benefit and risk\nFrom the clinical perspective, the expectation of benefit must be\ncompared to the expectation of risk to determine whether treatment or a change in treatment is justified. Although it can be difficult to estimate the balance between the potential risks and benefits\nin an individual case, it is necessary to do so before action is taken.\nThe likelihood of benefit or risk in the individual is informed by\nan understanding of likely outcomes in the population overall.\nTwo broad measures that can be useful as part of this assessment\nare number needed to treat (NNT) and number needed to harm\n(NNH). The NNT estimates the number of patients that would need\nto be given a treatment for one of them to achieve a desired outcome (e.g. 50% pain relief). The NNH is calculated for adverse effects in a similar way. Although these measures have been criticized\nbecause they are derived from controlled clinical trials data, they\nnevertheless provide a useful point of comparison among drugs\n(Christensen and Kristiansen, 2006).\nThe cut-​offs in pain relief or severity of an adverse effect used to\ncalculate the NNT and NNH, respectively, are accepted by convention. In fact, perceived benefit or risk may be strongly influenced\nby individual variation or therapeutic context. For example, patients\nwith severe pain may feel that a 30% or smaller reduction in pain\nrelief is clinically meaningful. In addition, some patients may be\nwilling to tolerate mild/​moderate side effects to achieve a small improvement in pain control if this translates into improved function\nor quality of life. Knowledge of the patient’s drug history in terms of\nprevious successes or failures of treatment will also guide choice of\ndrug in prescribing. Prescribers also must always check individual\npatient factors, such as renal function and known allergies, to further\ninform assessment of risk/​harm and potential for drug interactions.\nInformation about side effects of a drug must continue to be gathered after the drug is licensed. This is particularly important when\na drug is used in the palliative care context, which is usually characterized by patients with advanced illness and the use of multiple\ndrugs adapted for off-​label indications. In these situations, the use\nof a drug may be associated with a side effect liability quite different\nthan that expected based on clinical trials information.\n\nPrinciples of clinical pharmacology\nClinical pharmacology is broadly divided into pharmacokinetics\n(‘what the body does to the drug’) and pharmacodynamics (‘what\nthe drug does to the body’). In palliative medicine, drugs are not\noften used to cure or modify underlying disease but are predominantly focused on improving symptoms. They often are administered\nwith the intent to continue treatment until death. Knowledge of\npharmacokinetic variation, between patients and across time as disease worsens, combined with an understanding of the basic modes\nof drug action"},{"id": "7.6a","title": "Opioid Therapy: Pharmacology and Initiation","chapter": "7.6a","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 372,"end": 390,"pages": 19,"weight": 0.0152,"text": "374\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\n(a)\nCortex 1\n\nThalamus 2\nSpinal cord\n\n7 Amygdala\n\n8\nDorsal root\nganglion\n\n9\n\nInsula 3\n\nNucleus accumbens 4\n\nPeriaqueductal gray 5\nRostral ventromedial medulla\n\n6\n\n1\n\n6\n\nAnalgesia:\n\n2\n\n3\n\n4\n\n5\n\n7\n\n8\n\n10 Peripheral nerve\n(skin, joints, viscera)\n\n9 10\n\n(b)\nThalamo-cortical circuit 2\nVestibular apparatus\n\nCortex 1 1 1\n\nAdrenal glands\n\nThalamus 3\n\nAmygdala\n11 11\n\n13\n\nHypothalamus\n4 4\n12\nInsula 5\n\nNucleus accumbens 6\nHippocampus 7\n\nGastrointestinal tract\n\nCarotid body\n\n7\n\nVentral tegmental area 8\n\n10 10\nMedulla 9\n\n15\n\n9\n\nRespiratory depression (µ) 9\n\n14 14\n10\n\n1\n\n3\n\n11 15\n\nReward/euphoria, dependence/withdrawal (µ),\naversion/dysphoria (κ) 8 6 11 1 7 5\nSedation (µ,κ) 4 10\nConvulsions (δ) 7 2\nConstipation (µ) 14\nNausea and vomiting (µ) 9\nDiuresis (κ) 4 13\n\n1 12 14\n\nFig. 7.6.1 Representation of body structures involved in opioid-​induced analgesia (a) and side effects (b).\nAdapted under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license from Machelska, H and Celik, MÖ (2018) Advances in Achieving Opioid Analgesia\nWithout Side Effects. Front. Pharmacol. 9:1388. https://​doi.org/​10.3389/​fphar.2018.01388.\n\nCHAPTER 7.6 Optimizing analgesic outcomes\n\n(a)\n\n(b)\n\nGαi/o\n\nGαi/o\n\nGαi/o\n\nµ\nµ κ\nµ\nµ\nµ δ κ\nµ\nκ\n\nFig. 7.6.2 Mechanisms of opioid-​induced side effects. (a) G-​protein-​mediated side effects in response to activation of opioid receptors (OR).\n(1) Respiratory depression: Gbg-​dependent activation of GIRK channels. (1 and 2) Sedation and constipation: Gbg-​dependent activation of GIRK\nchannels (1) and inhibition of Cav channels (2). (3) Nausea and vomiting: Gai/​o-​mediated inhibition of AC, decreased cAMP levels and PKA activity,\nand inhibition of Cav channels; this is based on indirect evidence (indicated by a question mark). (4 and 5) Analgesic tolerance, reward/​euphoria,\ndependence/​withdrawal, or aversion/​dysphoria: Gbg-​mediated AC activation, elevated cAMP levels, enhanced PKA activity, and activation of Nav\nchannels (4). Phosphorylation of OR by various kinases (5), including PKA and activated by Gbg PKC, CaMK II, and mitogen-​activated protein kinase\n(MAPK), which results in OR uncoupling form G protein-​mediated effects. (b) Beta-​arrestin-​dependent actions. After even brief activation by an\nopioid, OR are phosphorylated by GRK recruited by Gbg, followed by beta-​arrestin binding to phosphorylated OR (1), which terminates G protein\ncoupling and signalling (2), and leads to OR internalization (3). Dephosphorylated OR can be recycled to the cell membrane (4) or directed to\nlysosomes and degraded (5). Beta-​arrestin-​2 might also promote morphine-​induced respiratory depression, constipation, analgesic tolerance, and\nkappa-​receptor-​mediated aversion, and dampen morphine-​induced reward. Some of these effects may involve MAPK activation (6), but mechanisms\nare unknown (indicated by question marks).\nAdapted under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license from Machelska, H and Celik, M"},{"id": "7.6b","title": "Opioid Therapy: Dose Titration and Side Effects","chapter": "7.6b","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 391,"end": 415,"pages": 25,"weight": 0.02,"text": "CHAPTER 7.6 Optimizing analgesic outcomes\n\nimplant for the maintenance treatment of opioid use disorder was\napproved in the US in 2016. Probuphine® is designed to provide a\nconstant, low-​level dose of buprenorphine for 6 months in patients\nwho are already stable on low-​to-​moderate doses of other forms of\nbuprenorphine, as part of a complete treatment programme.\nBuprenorphine also was developed in a transdermal system for\nuse in chronic pain. The drug is incorporated in a polymer adhesive\nmatrix which controls the release of the drug by diffusion. Doses\nup to 200 micrograms/​h have been reported during pain treatment (O'Brien et al., 2019). There are two preparations, one with\na 4-​day duration and the other with a 7-​day duration. The 4-​day\nbuprenorphine patch is available in three dose sizes: 35, 52.5, and\n70 micrograms/​h. Therapeutic plasma concentrations are achieved\nwithin 11–​21 hours and steady state is approached between the\nsecond and third applications of the patch. The 7-​day buprenorphine\npatch also is available in three sizes, but at lower doses: 5, 10, and\n20 micrograms/​h.\nMixed agonist–​antagonist analgesics\nAs noted previously, the pharmacology of the agonist–​antagonist\nopioid drugs has largely relegated their use to the context of acute\npain management. They produce analgesia in the opioid-​naïve patient but may precipitate withdrawal in patients who are physically\ndependent on morphine-​like drugs. They also possess a ceiling dose\nfor analgesia.\nPentazocine, butorphanol, and nalbuphine are mu antagonists and kappa agonists or partial agonists. When given by injection, pentazocine is one-​sixth to one-​third as potent as morphine,\nnalbuphine is roughly equipotent with morphine, and butorphanol\nis 3.5–​7 times as potent. A single dose of each drug has a duration\nof analgesia similar to that of morphine (3–​4 hours). At the doses\navailable, oral pentazocine is closer in analgesic efficacy to aspirin\nand paracetamol than to other opioids, and neither nalbuphine nor\nbutorphanol is available as an oral formulation. Butorphanol is no\nlonger available in any form in the UK.\nTramadol\nTramadol is a centrally acting analgesic which possesses opioid\nagonist properties and may also activate monoaminergic spinal inhibition of pain (Leppert, 2009; Wiffen et al., 2017a). It has modest\naffinity with MORs, with weak affinity to DORs and KORs, and its\nanalgesic effect is partly reversed by naloxone. Unlike other opioids, it also inhibits the uptake of noradrenaline and serotonin,\nand in an animal model, systemically administered yohimbine or\nritanserin blocks tramadol-​induced analgesia, suggesting that its\nmonoaminergic effects contribute significantly to the drug’s analgesic action (Leppert, 2009; Wiffen et al., 2017a).\nTramadol can be administered orally, rectally, intravenously, subcutaneously, or intramuscularly. In many countries, it is available\nin both normal-​and sustained-​release formulations. Parenterally,\n50–​150 mg of tramadol "},{"id": "7.7","title": "Opioid Therapy: Managing Risks of Abuse and Addiction","chapter": "7.7","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 416,"end": 423,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "418\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\nTable 7.7.1 Numerous risk factors for OUD have been identified but it is thought that risk factors from more than one domain are more\nsuggestive of risk for OUD than any single risk factor or two or more risk factors from the same domain\nHealth-​related factors\n\nPsychosocial factors\n\nDrug-​related factors\n\nGenetics\n\nDemographics\n\nMore intense and more\nfrequent pain reported\n\nCriminal history, problems with\nthe law, having been incarcerated\n\nPersonal history of substance\nuse disorder, current or prior\n\nFamily history of substance use\ndisorder, current or prior\n\nCaucasian race\n\nSeemingly exaggerated\nreports of pain\n\nPain-​related functional limitations Current smoker\n\nCaucasian race\n\nMale sex\n\nBack pain\n\nPost-​traumatic stress disorder\n\nCurrent use of illicit drugs;\ncurrent or prior use of cocaine\n\nMental health disorder\n\nYounger age\n\nPain at multiple sites or\nmultiple types of pain\n\nEmotional distress\n\nCurrent use of alcohol\n\nVariations in certain opioid\nreceptor genes (OPRM1,\nOPRK1, PENK, and others)\n\nUnemployed\n\nPersons living with\nHIV/​AIDs\n\nMental health disorder\n\nCurrent use of cannabis\n\nVariations in FKBP5 gene\nmodulating stress response\n\nUnmarried\n\nPoor to fair health\n\nDramatic reports of pain or\nsuffering\n\nSelf-​reported craving for drugs\n\nConvicted of driving under the\ninfluence\n\nHistory of polydrug abuse\n\nPoor or limited social support\n\nHistory or current opioid\ntreatment with high daily doses\n(>120 MME/​day)\n\nLower educational level\n\nMME, milligram morphine equivalent.\nSource: data from Kaye, A.D. et al. (2017). Pain Physician, 20(2S): S93–​S109; Reisfield, G.M. et al. (2009). Pain Med, 10(8):1434–​41; Reisfield, G.M. et al. (2010). J Pain Palliat Care\nPharmacother, 24(4): 356–​61; Levran, O. et al. (2014). Psychoneuroendocrinology, 45: 67–​76; Ives, T.J. et al. (2006). BMC Health Serv Res, 6: 46; Webster, L.R. (2017). Anesth Analg,\n125(5): 1741–​1748; Larowe, L.R. et al. (2018). Subst Use Misuse, 10;53(13):2210–​2219; and Jamison, R.N. et al. (2009). Pain Med, 10(6):1084–​94.\n\ntheir continuing behaviours as risk factors for OUD; these behaviours are dynamic, not static (Pergolizzi et al., 2012). The problem\nwith aberrant drug-​related behaviours is that they may occur in\nthose without OUD and do not reliably occur in those with OUD.\nNevertheless, these so-​called aberrant drug-​related behaviours may\noften serve as a good starting point for a frank conversation with the\npatient. See Table 7.7.2.\n\nRisk assessment\nAlthough risk assessment for OUD has not been rigorously studied\nin large clinical trials, there are many tools for clinicians to help\nquickly and reasonably accurately evaluate an individual’s particular\nrisk for developing OUD. Some of these are validated instruments\naimed at helping to analyse and quantify an individual’s risk.\n\nRisk stratification\nRisk stratification attempts to evaluate an individual’s prospective\nrisk for OUD when exposed to therapeutic opioids, but since it\nhas not been subject to ri"},{"id": "7.8","title": "Non-Opioid Analgesics","chapter": "7.8","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 424,"end": 432,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "426\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\nTable 7.8.1 Choice of oral NSAIDs\nPharmacokinetics\n\nDosage\n\nNSAID\nIbuprofen\n\nDiclofenac\n\nNaproxen\n\nFlurbiprofen\n\nIndomethacin\n\nMeloxicam\n\nPeak Cp\n\n15–​30 min\n\nProtein binding\n\n99%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n2–​4 h\n\nPeak Cp\n\n2–​3 h\n\nProtein binding\n\n99%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n1–​2 h\n\nPeak Cp\n\n1h\n\nProtein binding\n\n99%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n14 h\n\nPeak Cp\n\n1–​2 h\n\nProtein binding\n\n99%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n6h\n\nPeak Cp\n\n1–​2 h\n\nProtein binding\n\n90%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n2.5 h\n\nPeak Cp\n\n5–​10 h\n\nProtein binding\n\n99%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n24 h\n\nPeak Cp\n\n2–​4 h\n\nProtein binding\n\n97%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n6–​12 h\n\n400–​800 mg 3–​4 times/​day\n\n50–​75 mg 3 times/​day\n\n500 mg twice/​day\n\n100 mg 2–3 times/​day\n\n25 mg 2–​3 times/​day\n\n7.5–​15 mg once/​day\n\nCOX-​2-​inhibitors\nCelecoxib\n\nEtoricoxib\n\nPeak Cp\n\n1h\n\nProtein binding\n\n92%\n\nHalf-​life\n\n20–​26 h\n\n200–​400 mg twice/​day\n\n60–​120 mg once/​day\n\nCp, plasma concentration.\n\nClinical efficacy of NSAIDs alone and in combination\nwith opioids\nAlthough NSAIDs have been found to be effective in various chronic\npain conditions (Ecclestone et al., 2017), a recent Cochrane review\nconcluded that there is low evidence to support the use of NSAIDs\nalone or in combination with opioids for the three steps of the World\nHealth Organization cancer pain ladder. There is very low-​quality\nevidence that some people with moderate or severe cancer pain can\nobtain substantial levels of benefit within 1 or 2 weeks (Derry et al.,\n2017a). The evidence is not adequate to determine comparative efficacy or safety across NSAIDs, and the relative efficacy of NSAIDs\nin different cancer-​related pain mechanisms cannot be established.\nGiven the short duration of studies, the long-​term safety of NSAIDs\nfor patients with cancer pain also has not yet been established.\n\nSide effects and toxicity of NSAIDs\nNSAIDs administered alone or in combination with other analgesics should be used carefully. Potential adverse effects must be\nweighed carefully against potential advantages on a case-​by-​case\nbasis, especially during chronic use. Given the broad role that PGs\n\nhave in modifying physiological mechanisms, potential adverse effects vary widely.\n\nGastrointestinal effects\nThe most common adverse effects of the NSAIDs are GI (Table\n7.8.2). The effects vary from symptoms such as nausea, pyrosis, dyspepsia, pain, or bloating, to more serious problems, such as gastric\nand/​or intestinal ulcerations. Compared to non-​users, patients who\nreceive long-​term treatment with a non-​selective NSAID have an\napproximate fivefold higher risk of peptic ulcer disease and a fourfold higher risk of upper GI bleeding (Brune and Patrignani, 2015).\nPatients receiving COX-​2 selective inhibitors have a significantly\nlower risk of GI toxicity than those receiving a non-​selective COX\ninhibitor (Lanas, 2010); systematic reviews of randomized controlled trials have confirmed this observation (Bjarnason et al.,\n2018), demonstrating that the incidence of bleeding events and\nsymptomatic ulcers was consistently about half o"},{"id": "7.9","title": "Adjuvant Analgesics: Principles of Use","chapter": "7.9","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 433,"end": 442,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 7.9 Adjuvant analgesics: principles of use\n\n(Wang et al., 2018). There is high-​quality evidence that some of\nthe SNRIs—​mainly duloxetine, but also milnacipran, venlafaxine,\nand desvenlafaxine—​are analgesic (Saarto and Wiffen, 2007; Chan\net al., 2009; Lee and Chen, 2010; Dharmshaktu et al., 2012; Watson\net al., 2013; Griebeler et al., 2014; Finnerup et al., 2015). One trial\ndemonstrated that duloxetine 30–​60 mg per day relieved pain from\nchemotherapy-​induced peripheral neuropathy (Smith et al., 2013),\nand others showed that venlafaxine can ameliorate oxaliplatin-​\ninduced painful neuropathy and post-​mastectomy pain (Reuben\net al., 2004; Durand et al., 2012). In contrast to the SNRIs, there\nis limited evidence for a few of the SSRIs, specifically paroxetine,\ncitalopram, and escitalopram (Dharmshaktu et al., 2012; Griebeler\net al., 2014; Finnerup et al., 2015). For this reason, the SNRIs are\nselected when pain is the primary indication.\nDuloxetine is usually preferred, given the number of positive trials.\nLow starting doses for the SNRIs generally overlap the effective dose\nrange and dose titration may or may not be needed. In the absence\nof treatment-​limiting side effects, such as nausea, mental clouding,\nor sexual dysfunction, dose escalation is reasonable if the response\nis inadequate, but usually is stopped when the dose is at the upper\nrange of the antidepressant range. When stopping or switching a\nSNRI or SSRI, dose tapering is advised to avoid the so-​called antidepressant discontinuation syndrome (Wilson and Lader, 2015).\n\nAlpha-​2 adrenergic agonists\nThe alpha-​\n2 adrenergic agonists, clonidine, tizanidine, and\ndexmedetomidine, presumably activate monoamine-​dependent endogenous pain modulating pathways in the spinal cord and brain.\nClonidine is available orally, transdermally, and intraspinally. A controlled trial of epidural clonidine demonstrated efficacy for varied\ntypes of cancer-​related pain (Eisenach et al., 1995). Tizanidine, an\noral drug approved as an antispasticity agent, also has evidence of\nanalgesic efficacy (Malanga et al., 2002; Yazicioglu et al., 2016). Like\nclonidine, it may cause somnolence and hypotension, but its hypotensive effects are less prominent. Dexmedetomidine is an injectable\nformulation most often used as a sedative/​hypnotic in the critical\ncare setting. It, too, has analgesic effects (Arain et al., 2004) and has\nbeen proposed as a drug to consider for the management of delirium and pain in patients with advanced illness (Prommer, 2011).\nThere is limited experience with these drugs as adjuvant analgesics but it appears that tizanidine may be particularly useful when\nstarted with a night-​time dose of 2–​4 mg to manage pain complicated by insomnia. If beneficial, the dose may then be titrated up\nand divided between morning and night.\n\nCannabinoids\nCannabinoids are related to the chemical constituents of cannabis, bind to cannabinoid receptors, and produce an array of effects, among which is ana"},{"id": "7.10","title": "Interventional Approaches for Chronic Pain","chapter": "7.10","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 443,"end": 453,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 7.10 Interventional approaches for chronic pain\n\net al., 2011). The technique may be useful when conventional RF has\nuncertain indications, such as when targeting the pudendal nerve\n(Petrov-​Kondratov et al., 2017) or dorsal root ganglion (Cohen\net al., 2006).\n\nSympathetic nervous system block\nBlockade of structures within the sympathetic nervous system\nwith local anaesthetic or neurolytic solutions has been used to\nmanage a variety of chronic neuropathic, ischaemic, and visceral\npain syndromes, as well as pain from several acute processes (e.g.\nrenal colic, or ischaemic crises in Raynaud’s disease or obliterative\narteriopathies) (Breivik and Cousins, 2009). Local anaesthetic blocks\nalso have been used to predict response to sympathetic neurolysis,\nbut a positive response must be interpreted with caution because of\nthe analgesic effect of absorbed (systemic) local anaesthetic and/​or\nplacebo response. Injection with botulinum toxin A also has been\nused for sympathetic blocks, specifically in the treatment of complex regional pain syndrome (Carroll et al., 2009); a recent study\nsuggests that botulinum toxin B may be more effective in this condition (Lee et al., 2018).\nIn advanced malignancy, neurolytic blocks of structures involved\nin the sympathetic nervous system are used for visceral pain syndromes; these blocks interrupt both sympathetic efferent fibres and\nthe visceral afferent nociceptive fibres that traverse these structures.\nDepending on the targeted structure, blocks are used to treat abdominal (coeliac plexus block), pelvic (superior hypogastric plexus\nblock), or perineal (ganglion impar block) pains. The procedures\nare generally done with fluoroscopic or computed tomography (CT)\nimaging to guide needle placement; ultrasound guidance is also an\noption (Bhatnagar et al., 2012) and magnetic resonance imaging\n(MRI)-​guided coeliac plexus neurolysis has been described (Liu\net al., 2016). Patients with mixed somatic and visceral pain may experience incomplete relief that is nonetheless clinically meaningful.\nCoeliac plexus/​splanchnic nerve block\nNeurolytic coeliac plexus block (NCPB) and neurolytic splanchnic\nblock are used for upper abdominal pain from unresectable pancreatic or other upper abdominal malignancies (Burton et al., 2009).\nNCPB produces good to excellent relief in 85–​90% of patients; pain\nrelief persists until death in 70–​90% of responders (Eisenberg et al.,\n1995), with significantly improved quality of life. A Cochrane review concluded that NCPB reduces opioid consumption and adverse effects (Arcidiacono et al., 2011) and a recent retrospective\nstudy of 507 patients reported significant reduction of pain scores\nand opioid use for up to 6 months after NCPB (Rahman et al., 2018).\nGiven a favourable risk:benefit ratio, NCPB is widely accepted as\nthe next step for pain due to upper abdominal malignancy that responds inadequately to systemic analgesics. In one study, NCPB\nwas associated with longer survival in patients wi"},{"id": "7.11","title": "Neurostimulation in Pain Management","chapter": "7.11","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 454,"end": 460,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "456\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\nCranial electrotherapy stimulation\nCranial electrotherapy stimulation (CES) is a technique that delivers\nalternating low-​intensity current (usually 0.1–​16 mA) to the surface of the head. Available devices vary in the number of electrodes\nand their positions, and their stimulation patterns; the frequencies range from 0.5 to 15,000 Hz and may include high-​frequency\nbursts to overcome the high impedance of the skull (Mindes et al.,\n2015). Although the mechanisms have not yet been elucidated, recent neuroimaging studies indicate that CES impacts resting-​state\nfunctional connectivity of the default mode network (Feusner et al.,\n2012), which relates to normal resting state brain activity. Further,\nthere is evidence indicating that CES may affect endogenous brain\noscillations (Schroeder et al., 2001), and interact with neurotransmitters, such as serotonin, GABA, and catecholamines (Warner\net al., 1990, 1994), endorphins (Kuzin et al., 1984; Radman et al.,\n2007), or hormones (Shealy, 1988). It also may have an impact on\nthe autonomic nervous system (Podzolkov et al., 1992).\nClinical applications of CES include management of symptoms\nsuch as anxiety, depression, insomnia, hypertension, visual field\ndeficits after optic nerve injury, substance abuse withdrawal, and\npain. In pain management, CES has been used for headache, postoperative pain, and fibromyalgia (Lee et al., 2013; Taylor et al., 2013;\nShekelle et al., 2018). Although the evidence on the efficacy for pain\nis very limited, CES is a user-​friendly method with promising clinical potential.\n\nTranscranial direct current stimulation\ntDCS employs a battery-​powered device that delivers low-​intensity\nelectric stimulation (1 or 2 mA) to the surface of the head, usually with two large (20–​35 cm2) saline-​soaked sponge-​electrodes\n(Nitsche and Paulus, 2000). The primary mechanisms are believed to\ninvolve modulation of neuronal excitability and other neuroplastic\nchanges. tDCS interacts with neurotransmitters involved in pain-​\nprocessing pathways, including GABA, serotonin, dopamine, and\nacetylcholine, and can up-​and downregulate functional connectivity in networks containing these pathways (Nitsche et al., 2004a,\n2004b, 2004c, 2006, 2009). Stimulation of at least several minutes\ninduces glutamatergic calcium-​\ndependent neuroplasticity with\nmodulation of NMDA receptors (Antal et al., 2010; Nitsche et al.,\n2012). Alterations of neural activity can be detected in distant cortical and subcortical areas (Polania et al., 2011; DaSilva et al., 2012;\nStagg et al., 2013). So-​called anodal tDCS enhances excitability,\nwhereas cathodal tDCS has inhibitory effects, if delivered within\ncertain parameters (Batsikadze et al., 2013; Monte-​\nSilva et al.,\n2013). Chronic pain is associated with pathological alterations in\nneural excitability and neuroplasticity in various brain structures,\nand by modulating neural plasticity, tDCS may be able to normalize\nthese pathological changes (Birbaumer "},{"id": "7.12","title": "Behavioural and Psychosocial Interventions for Pain","chapter": "7.12","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 461,"end": 470,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 7.12 Behavioural and psychosocial interventions for pain management\n\nmisdeeds—​which appeared to be directly connected to increased\nfeelings of sadness and guilt.\nTo cope with pain, patients with advanced disease typically rely\non a variety of behavioural and cognitive pain coping strategies.\nThese strategies can include changing daily activities and the use\nof relaxation, prayer, imagery, and other distraction methods (Zaza\nand Baine, 2002). Patients with advanced disease vary with regard\nto their beliefs about their ability to use such strategies to effectively control their pain (Keefe et al., 2005; Syrjala et al., 2014). Along\nthese lines, patients who engage in pain catastrophizing (i.e. ruminate about pain, magnify pain sensations, and feel helpless in the\nface of pain) are much more likely to report more severe pain, less\nhope, and higher levels of pain-​related behaviours such as avoidance of activity and distorted pain avoidant posturing (Keefe et al.,\n2003b; Lai et al., 2003).\n\nSocial factors\nInterpersonal factors (e.g. social support, communication) can impact pain and its management. Research shows that patients with\npain who report higher levels of satisfaction with their social support are much more likely to experience better symptom management, improved health-​related quality of life (i.e. emotional, social,\nphysical, and functional well-​being), and less psychological distress\n(Bradley et al., 2018). The pathways by which social support can\ninfluence pain include receiving practical support (e.g. increased\nhelp with household responsibilities), emotional support (e.g. willingness of a caregiver to discuss thoughts and feelings about serious\nillness and pain), and informational support (e.g. information about\nstrategies for managing pain) (Uchino, 2004).\nPain can disrupt relationships and contribute to social isolation\nand interpersonal conflicts (Lloyd et al., 2016). It is common for\npatients with advanced disease to withdraw from social interactions\nbecause of fears that their pain and pain-​related emotions may be\ntoo much of a burden for their loved ones. Avoidance of social situations may reduce distress in the short term, but over time typically\nexacerbates distress and symptoms. Decreases in perceived social\nsupport and increased social isolation are both associated with increased pain severity and pain interference, higher levels of depressive symptoms, greater cognitive decline, and increased mortality\n(Holt-​Lunstad et al., 2015; Bradley et al., 2018).\nWhen pain is poorly controlled it often impacts those closest to\nthe patient. Caregivers of patients with more severe pain report\nhigher levels of burnout, fatigue, and psychological distress and are\nat increased risk of early mortality (Hudson et al., 2010). Caregivers\nwho report low levels of confidence in their ability to help patients\nmanage pain also are much more likely to experience worse mood\nand higher levels of caregiver strain (Keefe et al., 2003a). Mor"},{"id": "7.13","title": "Integrative Medicine Therapies in Pain Management","chapter": "7.13","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 471,"end": 477,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 7.13 Integrative medicine therapies in pain management\n\nTo date, there are more than 28,000 scientific publications on acupuncture (US National Library of Medicine and National Institutes\nof Health, 2018), and the treatment is considered to be safe when\nprovided by qualified acupuncturists and under medical supervision. Extra care is needed when treating patients with impaired immune function or coagulopathy. Acupuncturists treating oncology\npatients require additional training, encouraging standardized\npractices (Lu and Rosenthal, 2010). Clinical practice guidelines for\nsafe practice in this setting are available (Filshie and Hester, 2006;\nDeng et al., 2009).\nResearching the effects of acupuncture presents a number of\nchallenges, primarily the design of a control treatment. Many\nstudies employ ‘sham acupuncture’, which entails the needling of\nacupuncture points considered to be ‘inactive’ in accordance with\nTCM. Others use ‘placebo’ or ‘Streitberger’ needles, which are\nplaced on true or sham acupuncture points without penetrating the\nskin (Streitberger and Kleinhenz, 1998). The use of these methods\nis problematic since sham points are only ‘inactive’ according to\nTCM. Both sham and placebo needles can induce physiological effects which are similar to ‘true’ acupuncture. As a result, the efficacy\nof control treatments is frequently equivocal or only slightly lower\nthan that of true acupuncture treatment (Samuels, 2009).\nAcupuncture research may also be limited by factors which it\nshares with other integrative medicine modalities. These include\nnon-​specific effects reflecting the patient–​acupuncturist relationship; the anamnesis which is unique to TCM-​based therapies; and\nthe use of touch to ‘feel’ the acupuncture points prior to inserting\nthe needle, shown to induce additional effects in patients with irritable bowel syndrome (Kaptchuk et al., 2008). Researchers often\nneed to choose between the use of a set list of acupuncture points,\nor to allow each acupuncturist to choose their own list of points\n(Cherkin et al., 2009).\nDespite these challenges, there has been sufficient evidence to\nrecommend acupuncture for pain and other symptoms. A 1997\nConsensus Conference on Acupuncture at the US National\nInstitutes of Health found ‘promising’ evidence supporting its use\nfor adult postoperative and dental pain, and for chemotherapy-​\ninduced nausea and vomiting. Other indications for which acupuncture ‘may be useful as an adjunct treatment or an acceptable\nalternative’, include headaches, menstrual cramps, tennis elbow,\nfibromyalgia, myofascial pain, osteoarthritis, low back pain, and\ncarpal tunnel syndrome (National Institutes of Health, 1998).\nClinical research using controlled trials, as well as systematic\nreviews of these studies, are supportive in the use of acupuncture\nfor the treatment of pain. In a controlled trial, 67 postmenopausal\nwomen with breast cancer suffering from aromatase inhibitor-​\ninduced arthralgia were randomly allocated"},{"id": "7.14","title": "Management Issues in Bone Pain","chapter": "7.14","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 478,"end": 484,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "480\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\n(31% vs 23%) and reduced appetite (66% vs 56%) but no overall increase in later toxicity and no difference in QoL was documented.\nThe trial was d\n­ esigned as a non-​inferiority trial with a prespecified\nmargin of 10%; the 95% CI was below this for the intention-​to-​treat\nanalysis (9.2%) but not for the per protocol analysis (13.2%). The\nmost important conclusion from this study was that re-​irradiation\ncan be effective in patients with recurrent bone pain after previous\nirradiation. Unfortunately, the dose fractionation question remains\nunanswered but any marginal benefit from 20 Gy must be offset\nagainst the clear increase in acute toxicity for an individual patient.\nA subgroup analysis of this study including the 528 patients\nevaluable for response to retreatment at 2 months, which was the\nprimary end point, evaluated the relation between response and\nfunctional status and QoL using the European Organization for\nResearch and Treatment QLQ-​C30 and the Brief Pain Inventory\n(Chow et al., 2014a). There was a clear advantage for responders\nwith improvements in sleep and role functioning alongside pain.\nIn patients with a meaningful response defined by an improvement\nin at least 10 points on the analgesia and pain score, physical, role,\nemotional, and social functioning, global QoL, fatigue, pain, and appetite were all significantly improved compared to non-​responders.\nIn summary, patients should be offered re-​treatment for painful\nbone metastases with around one third benefitting both in a reduction of pain and clinically important improvements in function and\nQoL. A single dose of 8 Gy will be suitable in most cases.\n\nFracture risk and management\nof pathological fracture\nPathological fracture at a site of bone metastasis may occur spontaneously or as a result of minor trauma, particularly in weight-​\nbearing bones. Several tools have been described to estimate the\nrisk of fracture from metastatic disease (Benca et al., 2016) (see also\nChapter 14.5). One of the most widely used validated scores is the\nMirels’ score (Mirels et al., 1989):\n• score 1: upper limb, mild pain, blastic lesion, less than one-​third\ndiameter involved\n• score 2: lower limb, moderate pain, mixed lytic/​blastic lesion and\none-​third to two-​thirds diameter involved\n\n• score 3: peritrochanteric, severe pain, lytic, greater than two-​\nthirds diameter involved.\nA sum score is then derived based on assessment of site, pain severity, radiological appearance, and size, ranging from 4 to 12.\nA score of 9–​12 indicates a high risk of fracture and such patients\nshould be considered for prophylactic treatment. The Dutch Bone\nMetastasis Study undertook an analysis of pathological fracture in\n102 patients from the total population of 1157 with femoral metastases in whom there were 14 fractures (van der Linden, 2004).\nThey identified axial cortical involvement greater than 30 mm and\ncircumferential cortical involvement greater than 50% were predictive of fracture. "},{"id": "7.15","title": "Management Issues in Neuropathic Pain","chapter": "7.15","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 485,"end": 490,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "CHAPTER 7.15 Management issues in neuropathic pain\n\n(Finnerup et al., 2015). In the treatment of cancer pain, the quality\nof the available evidence on the effectiveness of analgesics, recommended as first-​line treatment for neuropathic pain, is low (van\nden Beuken-​van Everdingen et al., 2017). Results from studies in\nother neuropathic pain syndromes are therefore important when\nchoosing between different analgesics. There is at present no reason\nto believe that treatment for neuropathic pain caused by cancer\nsurgery should be different from treatment of other post-​surgical\nneuropathic pain and similarly for painful CIPN compared to\npainful diabetic polyneuropathy.\n\nAnticonvulsants\nAnticonvulsant drugs are used primarily for the treatment of epilepsy. They have several pharmacological actions that can interfere\nwith processes involved in neuronal hyperexcitability, either by\ndecreasing excitatory or increasing inhibitory transmission, thereby\nexerting a net neuronal depressant effect. These effects may underlie\nthe analgesic effects that some of these drugs exert in neuropathic\npain states (see Chapter 7.9).\nGabapentin and pregabalin\nGabapentin and pregabalin are structurally related compounds.\nTheir analgesic effect in neuropathic pain is thought to be mediated through antagonism of the alpha-​2-​delta subunit of voltage-​\ndependent calcium channels at presynaptic sites. The effects of\ngabapentin and pregabalin are well established in post-​herpetic\nneuralgia, painful diabetic neuropathy, and spinal cord injury pain\n(Finnerup et al., 2015). Both drugs seem equally effective, with\naverage numbers needed to treat (NNTs) for 50% pain reduction\naround 7.5 (see Chapter 7.9).\nBoth gabapentin and pregabalin are generally well tolerated.\nNeither drug has any known drug–​drug interactions. Somnolence\nand dizziness are the most common side effects and peripheral oedema, weight gain, nausea, vertigo, asthenia, dry mouth, and ataxia\nmay occur. Side effects may resolve over time or improve with dose\nreduction. Gabapentin is usually administered three times daily.\nDosing is initiated slowly, for example, starting with 300 mg the\nfirst day and increasing by 300 mg every 1–​7 days. The final daily\ndose is between 1800 and 3600 mg, but side effects may limit dose\nescalation. Pregabalin may be initiated with 75 or 150 mg daily and\nincreased every 3–​7 days by 150 mg, up to 600 mg in two divided\ndoses. Both gabapentin and pregabalin undergo renal excretion and\nrenal impairment requires dosage adjustment.\nOther anticonvulsants\nThe main action of carbamazepine, and its analogue oxcarbazepine,\nis blocking of sodium channels. Carbamazepine and oxcarbazepine\nare first-​line drugs for trigeminal neuralgia, but the evidence is inconsistent for other neuropathic pain conditions (Finnerup et al.,\n2015), although a phenotype-​stratified study suggested efficacy in\na subgroup of patients with hypersensitivity to thermal or mechanical stimuli and preserved small-​fibre func"},{"id": "7.16","title": "Management Issues in Visceral Pain","chapter": "7.16","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 491,"end": 498,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 7.16 Management issues in visceral pain\n\narray of inflammatory products and candidate receptors for different organs and nerves, with interest in the role of serotonin receptors, sodium channels, nitric oxide, and TRPV channels (Page\net al., 2009; Blackshaw et al., 2010).\n\nCentral sensitization\nCentral sensitization is operationally defined as an amplification of\nneural signalling within the central nervous system. Like peripheral sensitization, it is a process that can result in the experience\nof spontaneous pain, the perception of pain related to non-​noxious\nstimuli, or hypersensitivity to noxious events. Examples of visceral\npain that could be related to central sensitization are oesophageal\nnon-​cardiac chest pain and pain due to chronic pancreatitis. The\nN-​methyl D aspartate receptor is important for central sensitization\nto visceral pain (Willert et al., 2004).\n\nOther mechanisms\nThere is increasing evidence in preclinical models that products\nof the gut microbiota can cause both peripheral and central sensitization, potentially leading to changes in visceral pain perception\n(O’Mahony et al., 2017). In stress-​related visceral pain, changes in\nthe central nervous system, which may occur in discrete regions\nsuch as the amygdala, can lead to central sensitization and visceral\nhypersensitivity (Greenwood-​van Meerveld and Johnson, 2017).\n\nClinical aspects of visceral pain\nIn the US, unexplained abdominal pain is the most frequent cause of\nmedical visits by the general population. In large surveys of cancer\npain patients, 16% of patients had purely visceral pain, mixed somatic and visceral pain occurred in 12%, and mixed visceral and\nneuropathic pain was noted in 3%.\nPain that occurs in association with injury to visceral structures\nmay have distinctive clinical features. If it is related to obstruction\nor injury to hollow viscus, the pain tends to be poorly localized\nand described as vague, gnawing, or crampy; the pain may become\nintermittently severe in association with visceral contractions. In\ncontrast, injury to solid organs or to organ capsules or related fascia tends to be better localized and described as sharp or stabbing.\nAll types of visceral pain may be referred in specific patterns and\nalso may be associated with autonomic symptoms, such as nausea\nand vomiting. Visceral pain may be accompanied by highly aversive\nemotional reactions.\nIn a comparison of pain caused by cutaneous heat with pain\ncaused by oesophageal balloon distention, subjects undergoing\noesophageal distention used a wider range of descriptors, more affective descriptors, and reported more anxiety. Descriptors used by\npatients in experimental studies include nauseating, suffocating,\nand deep. Burning pain has been described for oesophageal and\nbladder pain.\n\nReferred pain\nPain associated with visceral injury commonly refers to somatic\nsites. Viscerosomatic ‘referred’ pain may result from convergence of\nvisceral and somatic afferent fibres on the same lamina i"},{"id": "7.17","title": "Chronic Pain Following Cancer Therapy","chapter": "7.17","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 499,"end": 505,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 7.17 Management issues in chronic pain following cancer therapy\n\nTable 7.17.2 Cancer therapies associated with peripheral\nneuropathy\nEpothilones\n\n•\t\u0007Ixabepilone\n\nPlatinum agents\n\n•\t\u0007Carboplatin\n•\t\u0007Cisplatin\n•\t\u0007Oxaliplatin\n\nTaxanes\n\n•\t\u0007Cabazitaxel\n•\t\u0007Docetaxel\n•\t\u0007Paclitaxel\n\nImmunomodulatory agents\n\n•\t\u0007Lenalidomide\n•\t\u0007Pomalidomide\n•\t\u0007Thalidomide\n\nProteasome inhibitors\n\n•\t\u0007Bortezomib\n•\t\u0007Carfilzomib\n\nVinca alkaloids\n\n•\t\u0007Etoposide\n•\t\u0007Vinblastine\n•\t\u0007Vincristine\n•\t\u0007Vinorelbine\n\nduloxetine was supported for treatment of existing CIPN (Smith\net al., 2013; Hershman et al., 2014). Subsequently an encouraging\nstudy using scrambler therapy by Loprinzi and Smith has opened\nthis as an option (Loprinzi et al., 2019).\nPainful peripheral neuropathy related to chemotherapy can have\nimplications for the adequacy of anticancer treatment, with patients\nreceiving reduced doses or shortened courses of therapy, potentially\naffecting survival (Bhatnagar et al., 2014). Gait alterations and impaired balance can lead to falls (Tofthagen et al., 2012; Kolb et al.,\n2016; Monfort et al., 2017; Winters-​Stone et al., 2017) and orthostatic hypotension can occur with CIPN-​associated autonomic nervous system dysfunction (Adams et al., 2015).\n\nHormonal therapy\nAromatase inhibitors (including anastrozole, exemestane, and\nletrozole) play a key role in breast cancer survival, with recommendations for use 5–​10 years after initial anticancer therapy. However,\narthralgias as a result of this therapy are painful, reduce quality\nof life, and may impair adherence to this potentially life-​saving\ntherapy. Arthralgias often occur within 6 weeks of onset of treatment (Castel et al., 2013). Predictors for arthralgia associated with\naromatase inhibitors include elevated body mass index, previous\nchemotherapy utilizing a taxane, stage III cancer, and a duration of\nmenopause of 5–​10 years (Beckwee et al., 2017). Pre-​existing joint\nsymptoms may also foretell arthralgia (Castel et al., 2013). For men\nwith prostate cancer, antiandrogen therapy (including bicalutamide\nor flutamide) can lead to painful gynaecomastia, or mastodynia, in\nas many as 70% of patients (Fagerlund et al., 2015).\n\nof the conditioning regimen (ablative versus non-​myeloablative)\n(Lazaryan et al., 2016). Pain is a significant consequence of chronic\nGVHD, involving most organ systems (Ma et al., 2018). These include skin, gastrointestinal, urogenital, ophthalmological, musculoskeletal, and nervous systems.\nPainful chronic syndromes seen after HSCT can also be related to\nthe conditioning chemotherapy or the immunosuppressant agents\nused before and after transplant, as well as GVHD. Peripheral\nneuropathy and muscle cramps have been reported in this population (Kraus et al., 2012). Corticosteroids, commonly used prior\nto, during, and after HSCT can lead to avascular necrosis (Kraus\net al., 2012; Li et al., 2014; Ma et al., 2018). Reactivation of varicella zoster is common and results from the immunosuppression\nseen with HS"},{"id": "7.18","title": "Paediatric Pain Control","chapter": "7.18","section": "7","sectionLabel": "Pain","start": 506,"end": 523,"pages": 18,"weight": 0.0144,"text": "508\n\nSECTION 7 Pain\n\nTable 7.18.1 Common myths and the scientific evidence\nMyth\n\nScientific evidence\n\n1 Newborns do not have a\nmature nervous system to\nexperience pain\n\nBy 26 weeks, a fetus in utero is capable of experiencing pain. Pain pathways and the cortical and subcortical pain centres are\nwell developed. At birth, a newborn is highly sensitive to pain (Anand, 1999)\n\n2 Children do not feel as much\npain as adults\n\nChildren feel as much pain as adults, and perhaps even more (McGrath, 2005)\n\n3 Children will get used to pain. If\na young child experiences pain,\nthey have no memory and it will\nhave no lasting effect\n\nContinuing pain has deleterious effects and causes long-​term changes in the nervous system (Schmelzle-​Lubiecki et al.,\n2007). Data suggest that early pain experience may produce permanent reorganization of developing neural pathways,\nwhich in turn may impact negatively on future pain experience (Anand and the International Evidence-​Based Group for\nNeonatal Pain, 2001; Fitzgerald and Walker, 2009)\n\n4 Children cannot explain their\npain reliably\n\nIf asked, children are capable at a very young age (even at 20 months) of saying where it hurts, how much it hurts, and what\nmakes the hurt feel better\n\nResponse to pain in young infants has been well documented in behavioural and physiological studies and the newborn is\nwell able to feel pain (Fitzgerald et al., 1988; Fitzgerald and McIntosh, 1989; Fitzgerald, 1991)\n\nChildren can report pain intensity at the age of 3 years\nChildren as young as 4 years old can indicate pain on a body chart without being able to name their body parts\n(Craig and Korol, 2008)\n5 If a child can be distracted, the\nchild is not in pain\n\nChildren use distraction and play as a coping mechanism for pain (Kuttner, 1996)\n\n6 If a child says that he/​she is in\npain but does not appear in\npain, the child does not need\nrelief\n\nThe child is the authority on whether or not he or she is in pain. Adults and medical professionals:\n• Consistently and significantly under-​rate children’s pain\n• Often have concern that children exaggerate pain which causes them to discount pain\n• Diminish the seriousness of the pain and suffering as the pain may be difficult to treat (Craig et al., 1996; Pillai Riddell et al., 2008)\n\n7 A sleeping child is a\ncomfortable child\n\nSleep may be due to exhaustion from pain. Disturbed sleep patterns are common, this does not mean the child never sleeps\n(Long et al., 2008)\n\n8 Opioid analgesics are\ndangerous for children and\nmay result in addiction\n\nOpioid analgesics are powerful pain-​relieving medications that are invaluable for children in pain. Children are no more at\nrisk of psychological dependence than adults\n\nAdapted with permission from Kuttner L. (2004). A Child in Pain, How to Help, What to Do. Vancouver, Canada: Hartley and Marks Publishers.\n\nSome of these characteristics are relatively fixed: age, developmental\nlevel, and family and cultural background. Others, such as emotional,\nbehavioural, and"},{"id": "8.1","title": "Dysphagia, Dyspepsia, and Hiccups","chapter": "8.1","section": "8","sectionLabel": "Gastrointestinal Symptoms","start": 525,"end": 533,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 8.1 Dysphagia, dyspepsia, and hiccups\n\nOesophageal dysphagia\nGastro-​oesophageal endoscopy allows visualization of the oesophageal mucosa, allows biopsies to be taken and, if needed, oesophageal\ndilatation and insertion of a stent. This is usually a well-​tolerated\ninvestigation that can be performed under sedation. The main concern is the risk of oesophageal perforation either as the result of\nbiopsies, dilation, or stent insertion.\nOesophageal pH monitoring is considered the optimal diagnostic\ntool to diagnose reflux disease. This is undertaken by inserting a\nnaso-​oesophageal probe which allows recording of pH levels.\n\nManagement of oesophageal dysphagia\nPalliative management of dysphagia aims to maximize swallowing\nfunction. This is both to allow adequate nutrition and participation\nin the social activities of eating and drinking. Management strategies differ depending upon whether the problem is localized to the\noropharynx or the oesophagus, the chronicity of the underlying disease, and the overall prognosis.\nWhen considering the management of oropharyngeal dysphagia,\nfor those able to participate in structured programmes, swallowing\nmay be improved through modification of a number of factors.\nFor example, a pureed diet together with thickened fluids is most\nappropriate for patients who are experiencing difficulties with the\noral phase of swallowing. Other behavioural recommendations\ninclude increasing the number of times food is chewed and the\nnumber of swallows per bolus. An important component of feeding\nis to consider how diet may best contribute to maintaining nutrition and hydration. Patients at risk of aspiration are much more\nlikely to develop complications of aspiration when they are malnourished as resistance to infections is compromised and defence\nmechanisms such as cough are impaired. Malnutrition may result\nin deteriorating performance status, anaemia, increased risk of\npressure sores, impaired wound healing, and accelerated osteoporosis. Inadequate hydration also places patients at risk of metabolic\ncomplications and aspiration, increasing the risk of pneumonia as\nsalivary flow may be reduced, leading to alterations in the normal\noropharynx flora.\nEnsuring good oral hygiene is important as an additional aid to\navoid aspiration complications. Patients with impaired clearance of\nthe oropharynx are at risk of altered colonization due to retained\nsecretions, poor nutrition, and dehydration. Simple measures such\nas regular mouth washes and artificial salvia are recommended.\nAnticholinergic medications should be minimized.\nSpeech pathologists provide invaluable support when considering whether an exercise routine might be useful to improve the\nsafety of swallowing.\nWhen trying to improve the strength of muscles involved in\nswallowing, exercises are targeted to the site of the pathology. For\nexample, lip exercises may improve a patient’s ability to prevent\ndrooling when attempting to swallow. Tongue exercises may improve a pa"},{"id": "8.2","title": "Nausea and Vomiting","chapter": "8.2","section": "8","sectionLabel": "Gastrointestinal Symptoms","start": 534,"end": 544,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "536\n\nSECTION 8 Gastrointestinal symptoms and disorders\n\ncingulate cortex, supporting involvement of the limbic system\n(Napadow et al., 2013). The orbitofrontal cortex is also activated\n(Napadow et al., 2013), which appears to be involved in decision-​\nmaking and learning (Schoenbaum et al., 2011). Activity in the inferior frontal gyrus (implicated in risk aversion) is correlated with\nintensity of nausea (Farmer et al., 2015).\n\n• Trying to establish the underlying cause or causes (often\nmultifactorial)\n• Investigating if appropriate (e.g. blood test to check for uraemia\nor hypercalcaemia)\n• Discussing options and agreeing a plan with the individual,\nincluding appropriate review.\n\nThe enteric nervous system\n\nIn practice, clinical assessment will need to be tailored to the\nindividual’s needs. Someone who is vomiting profusely will be unlikely to want to engage in a detailed discussion of the impact on\ntheir mood; immediate support is the first priority.\nManagement of nausea and vomiting includes relieving underlying causes, where appropriate (e.g. constipation, hypercalcaemia,\nor cerebral oedema). Non-​pharmacological and pharmacological\nstrategies are summarized in the following sections. Empathy, supportive care, and attention to the concerns of the individual and\ntheir family are important.\nMuch research into interventions has focused on nausea and\nvomiting associated with chemotherapy or surgery. We have a\nsmaller—​though growing—​evidence base in palliative care unrelated to anti-​cancer therapies.\n\nIt has been suggested that ‘the brain can be conceived as being a functionally specialised piece of gut tissue that evolved at the consuming\nend of the gut as a tool for recognising food’ (Max, 1992). The gut\nhas an enteric nervous system which communicates with the central nervous system. Numerous neurotransmitters are present in the\ngastrointestinal tract, including serotonin (5-​hydroxytryptamine\n(5-​HT); 14 receptor subtypes have been identified), dopamine,\nghrelin, cholecystokinin, and gamma-​aminobutyric acid (Mittal\net al., 2017). Calcium-​dependent signalling is involved in the release\nof several neurotransmitters (including dopamine, serotonin, and\nsubstance P) and in mediating their effects (including neurokinin\n1 (NK1), 5-​HT3, dopamine type 2 receptor (D2), muscarinic, histamine) (Zhong et al., 2017).\nThe stomach has a usual cyclical pattern of activity, contracting\naround three times every minute (Stern et al., 2011). Gastric dysrhythmias can be triggered by motion, apparent motion, morphine, or ipecac, and are associated with nausea (Stern et al., 2011).\nThere may be tachygastria (>4 cycles per minute) or bradygastria\n(<2 cycles per minute); gastric myoelectrical activity becomes irregular and this is associated with gastroparesis (Stern et al., 2011).\nInterstitial cells of Cajal in the antrum of the stomach act as gastric pacemaker cells. They can be depleted in gastroparesis (e.g.\ncaused by diabetes) (Koch, 2017b). Delayed gastric em"},{"id": "8.3","title": "Constipation and Diarrhoea","chapter": "8.3","section": "8","sectionLabel": "Gastrointestinal Symptoms","start": 545,"end": 555,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 8.3 Constipation and diarrhoea\n\nexample, age, frailty, poor oral intake, inability to sit comfortably on\nthe toilet, and a lack of privacy when toileting (Dukas et al., 2003;\nWinge et al., 2003). Bowel function is an intensely private action\nand the need for caregivers or family members to assist in this function can lead to minimizing or avoiding use of the toilet. The need\nfor a sensitive and dignified approach to management is essential,\nenabling privacy to be maintained.\nOpioid-​induced constipation\nOIC is the most common example in palliative care patients given\nthe high incidence of opioid use in this population. Overall incidence is conservatively estimated at 60%, although variable, based\non dose and type of opioid used. Most practitioners agree anecdotally that 100% of patients receiving opioids will experience some\ndegree of constipation, irrespective of opioid used. There is some\nevidence that both transdermal fentanyl and methadone (mediated\nthrough the N-​methyl-​D-​aspartate receptor) are less constipating\nthan other opioids such as morphine (Radbruch et al., 2000), oxycodone (Ackerman et al., 2004), and hydromorphone, (Mancini\net al., 2000). Other analgesics such as tramadol, tapentadol, and\nalfentanil may also be less constipating than morphine.\nOpioid analgesics impact bowel fluid handling acting on mu-​\nreceptors throughout the gastrointestinal tract, resulting in reduced\nperistalsis, increased fluid reabsorption, and increased sphincter\ntone (Larkin et al., 2018). There is no evidence that reducing opioids\nalone results in a concomitant reduction in constipation and so, a\nkey practice principle is that laxative prescription should always accompany opioid initiation.\nOpioid effects may be seen both locally and centrally in the\nbrain and spinal cord. Widespread opioid receptor distribution\nthroughout the gastrointestinal tract concentrates in the stomach\nand proximal colon, notably mu-​and kappa-​\nopioid receptors.\nExogenous and endogenous opioid impacts on the gastrointestinal\ntract have been well studied in humans and animal models. Opioids\naffect smooth muscle, involving both intrinsic and extrinsic nerve\ninnovation. A lack of sensation of gut and rectal distension can lead\nto impaction, notably in older people where this may be already diminished. Intestinal secretions (from the pancreas and biliary tract)\nare inhibited by opioid administration and combined with fluid reabsorption leads to the pronounced constipation of dry, hard, small\nstool that is difficult to pass. Opioid use in the context of disorders\nnoted in Table 8.3.1 exacerbates already challenging health problems. Most medications cited here are in common use in palliative\ncare. Given the range of functional factors which impact negatively\non bowel function, a particular role for the healthcare professional\nis education of both patient and family that OIC cannot be managed effectively by an altered diet and fluid intake (e.g. increasing\nfibre consumption) "},{"id": "8.4","title": "Jaundice, Ascites, and Encephalopathy","chapter": "8.4","section": "8","sectionLabel": "Gastrointestinal Symptoms","start": 556,"end": 566,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "558\n\nSECTION 8 Gastrointestinal symptoms and disorders\n\nTreatment consists of corticosteroids and withholding offending\nmedication (Suzman et al., 2018; Lleo et al., 2019).\nThere appears to be little solid evidence that there is an increased risk\nof drug-​related hepatotoxicity in individuals with pre-​existing liver disease (Teschke et al., 2017). However, most analgesics are metabolized\nthrough the liver, and their metabolism can be altered as liver disease\nworsens. For example, in those with cirrhosis, the half-​life of paracetamol is twice that seen in healthy controls and it is recommended\nthat a safe daily dose not exceed 2 g (Chandok and Watt, 2010).\nSepsis\nHepatobiliary dysfunction is common in the setting of sepsis, particularly bacterial, and isolated jaundice can also occur (Torous et al.,\n2017). In the setting of sepsis, cholestasis may also result from hypotension and low hepatic blood flow with microcirculatory failure.\nIn the setting of shock, the liver does not receive adequate blood\nsupply for its oxygen demand, leading to ischaemia/​reperfusion injury (hypoxic hepatitis) (Woźnica, 2018). Medications used to treat\nthe sepsis may also contribute.\nCardiac failure and the liver\nAltered liver function is common in severe heart failure (congestive\nhepatopathy). Elevated right-​sided heart pressures lead to hepatic\ncongestion which causes damage to the bile canaliculae (Lemmer\net al., 2018). Over time, congestive hepatopathy can progress to\nbridging fibrosis, cirrhosis, and potentially hepatocellular carcinoma (Lemmer et al., 2018; Nandwana et al., 2018). Significant\nhypotension secondary to infarction or severe valvular disease can\nlead to an ischaemic or hypoxic hepatitis signalled by a massive rise\nin aminotransferases and prolonged prothrombin time (Woźnica,\n2018). Fatal acute liver failure may result.\nVenous occlusion\nHepatic venous outflow obstruction, with hepatomegaly, ascites,\nand liver failure in the absence of cardiac disease is termed Budd–​\nChiari syndrome (Singh and Srinivas, 2018). Primary Budd–​Chiari\nsyndrome is the most frequent type and is usually associated with\nhypercoagulable states. Secondary Budd–​\nChiari syndrome involves direct tumour invasion or extrinsic compression of the hepatic venous outflow (van Wettere et al., 2018). Malignancy is clearly\nassociated with Budd–​\nChiari syndrome both through increased\nthrombogenicity and local obstruction of the venous system by solid\ntumours. Untreated acute Budd–​Chiari syndrome requires an urgent and aggressive approach to management. Inferior vena caval\nor hepatic vein stenting and transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic\nshunt (TIPS) formation are relatively non-​invasive procedures that\ncan be of significant benefit in selected individuals (Das et al., 2018).\nVeno-occlusive disease, renamed as sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (SOS), can occur due to chemotherapy induced damage to\nhepatic sinusoidal endothelial cells manifesting clinically as sudden\nonset abdominal pa"},{"id": "8.5","title": "Anorexia-Cachexia Syndrome","chapter": "8.5","section": "8","sectionLabel": "Gastrointestinal Symptoms","start": 567,"end": 578,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "CHAPTER 8.5 Aetiology, classification, assessment, and treatment of the anorexia-cachexia syndrome\n\nBMI kg/m2\n28\n\n25\n\n22\n\n20\n\n0\n\n0\n\n1\n\n1\n\n3\n\n1\n\n2\n\n2\n\n2\n\n3\n\n2\n\n3\n\n3\n\n3\n\n4\n\n3\n\n3\n\n3\n\n4\n\n4\n\n3\n\n4\n\n4\n\n3\n\n4\n\nWeight loss %\n\n2.5\n\n6\n11\n\n15\n\nGrade\n\n0\n\n1\n\n2\n\n3\n\n4\n\nP\n\nColon\n\n28.3\n\n22.8\n\n21.6\n\n17.3\n\n7.3\n\n0.002\n\nOesophagus\n\n18.4\n\n12.8\n\n10.3\n\n7.6\n\n4.4\n\n0.003\n\nPalliative\ncare\n\n5.8\n\n5.0\n\n3.9\n\n3.7\n\n3.2\n\n0.002\n\nLung\n\nintake is caused by primary anorexia (i.e. central nervous system\nlevel) and may be compounded by secondary impairments to\noral intake. Concurrent hypermetabolism, hypercatabolism and\nhypoanabolism aggravate the associated weight loss and are provoked by systemic inflammation and tumour-​derived catabolic factors that may act peripherally and via the central nervous system.\nCachexia is thus a multidimensional problem and therefore it may\nnot be possible to reflect the physiological change and clinical risks\nthe patient sustains by a single measurement (e.g. loss of weight or\nskeletal muscle mass).\nOn the basis that risk derives from several key elements of cachexia, a classification system based on the severity of weight loss,\nimpaired food intake, and systemic inflammation was proposed\n(Fearon et al., 2006). Individually, these features associate with\nphysiological impairment and reduced survival: Martin et al. (2015)\ndescribe the risk of mortality associated with weight loss, Quinten\net al. (2009) described the risk of mortality associated with reduced\nfood intake, and Dolan et al. (2017) reviewed the role of systemic\ninflammatory response in predicting clinical outcomes in patients\nwith advanced cancer. Of key clinical importance is that patients\nwith an early stage of disease who demonstrate these features are\nat high risk of early demise and are therefore a key group to target\nfor early and effective intervention. The current international consensus classification system (Fearon et al., 2011) includes these\nthree essential features but has extended the assessment domains\nto include anorexia/​intake, muscle depletion, tumour-​derived catabolic drivers, and functional and psychosocial impairment.\n\nClinical assessment and treatment strategy\n\n11.3\n\n9.9\n\n8.2\n\n5.6\n\n4.2\n\n0.001\n\nFig. 8.5.2 (BMI-​adjusted) Weight loss grade. Grading scheme is based\non groupings showing distinct median survival. Different colours denote\ndistinct survival duration (weeks) (P <0.001; adjusted for age, sex, disease\nsite, stage, and performance status).\nAdapted with permission from Martin, L. et al. (2015). Diagnostic criteria for the\nclassification of cancer-​associated weight loss. J Clin Oncol. 33(1):90–​9. DOI 10.1200/​\nJCO.2014.56.1894.\n\ndetermined by dual-​energy X-​ray absorptiometry (men <7.26 kg/​\nm2; women <5.45 kg/​m2); lumbar skeletal muscle index determined\nfrom oncology computed tomography imaging (men <52.4 cm2/​m2;\nwomen <39 cm2/​m2); and whole-​body fat-​free mass index without\nbone determined by bioelectrical impedance (men <14.6 kg/​m2;\nwomen <11.4 kg/​m2). Th"},{"id": "8.6","title": "Parenteral Nutrition in Palliative Care","chapter": "8.6","section": "8","sectionLabel": "Gastrointestinal Symptoms","start": 579,"end": 587,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 8.6 Parenteral nutrition\n\nTable 8.6.1 Expected duration of treatment required to result\nin clinical benefit\nTreatment\n\nDuration\n\nHydration\n\nHours to days\n\nProviding energy, proteins, and other nutrients\n\nWeeks\n\nImproving physical activity\n\nWeeks\n\nMetabolic modulation\n\nDays to weeks\n\nnutrition may be questioned. On the other hand, PN may well be\njustified in a patient with a fairly stable oncological situation but severely compromised tolerance for oral or enteral food.\nIf there is complete intolerance of oral and enteral nutrition, substituting all requirements by the intravenous route has been termed\n‘total PN’, while supplying nutrient infusions in addition to ongoing\noral intake is being termed ‘supplemental PN’. It is obvious that the\neffect of total PN will be greater than that of supplemental PN. Thus,\nsurprisingly long survival times have been reported for total PN in\npatients with advanced relatively indolent cancer and complete intestinal failure (Fan, 2007), while a proof of concept of supplemental\nPN is still lacking.\n\nNutrition as a basic human right versus an indicated\nmedical therapy\nNutrition may be conceptualized as a basic human right, which\nneeds to be fulfilled independently of other arguments. Applying\nthis to the situation of patients unable to eat normally, leads some\nauthorities to the conclusion that PN should be a basic entitlement\n(Bozzetti, 2003).\nIn contrast, ethical guidelines and directives of medical associations state that nutrient or fluid infusions are not essential approaches in dying patients (Bundesärztekammer, 2011; Druml\net al., 2016). The potential benefits, burdens, and risks of PN need\nto be considered and, furthermore, it needs to be acknowledged that\nnutritional requirements decrease towards the end of life and that\nnutritional and metabolic loading in these situations may even be\nharmful (Arends et al., 2017).\n\nthe infusions are technically challenging and time-​\nconsuming.\nIf cyclic infusions are used, the patient will be connected to the\nfeeding line and the infusion bag for up to 14 or 15 hours. This may\ninterfere with normal activity and limit social interactions.\nIntravenous nutrient infusions carry risks of metabolic derangements (electrolytes, glucose, lipids), occlusion of the access device,\nand, most importantly, episodes of bacteraemia and sepsis, which\nmay be life-​threatening. Other complications are less frequent, such\nas catheter-​related venous thrombosis or technical catheter defects.\nReported rates of adverse events observed in high-​volume expert\ncentres treating mainly patients with benign diseases are 0.5–​10 episodes of catheter-​related bloodstream infections and 0.1 episodes\nof catheter occlusion per 1000 catheter days (Pironi et al., 2016).\nComplication rates may be much higher in smaller centres and\nthose with less expertise (Pironi et al., 2016) and in patients with\nadvanced cancer (Chow et al., 2016).\nTo avoid prolonged hospitalization, patients requiring PN for\nweeks"},{"id": "9.1","title": "Breathlessness and Respiratory Symptoms","chapter": "9.1","section": "9","sectionLabel": "Cardiorespiratory Symptoms","start": 589,"end": 603,"pages": 15,"weight": 0.012,"text": "CHAPTER 9.1 Breathlessness and other respiratory symptoms in palliative care\n\nstage, breathlessness was also a predictor for survival in multivariate\nanalysis in 30–​50% of studies (Trajkovic-​Vidakovic et al., 2012).\nIn people with COPD, breathlessness correlates better with survival than with pulmonary functions tests (Nishimura et al., 2002).\nBreathlessness is one of the six parameters used in the Palliative\nPrognostic Score that predicts 30-​day survival of palliative care patients (Pirovano et al., 1999).\nBreathlessness is associated with reduced ability to carry out activities of daily living (Smith et al., 2016), increased use of primary\n(Currow et al., 2013) and emergency care services (Hutchinson\net al., 2017; Kelly et al., 2017), and hospital admissions (Parshall\net al., 1999; Hutchinson et al., 2017). A recent observational consecutive cohort of patients brought to the emergency department by\nambulance showed that one-​third were living with chronic breathlessness, and one-​fifth had attended that day because of acute-​on-​\nchronic breathlessness (Hutchinson et al., 2017). Once in hospital,\nbreathlessness is associated with adverse events and increased\nlength of stay (Stevens et al., 2016, 2018).\nBreathlessness also has a major impact on daily life. A recent systematic review and qualitative synthesis drew together 101 qualitative studies exploring the experience of breathlessness from the\nviewpoint of patients, their families, and their healthcare professionals. This illustrated clearly the widespread effects of breathlessness irrespective of underlying diagnosis including loss of social\nfunction, leading to dependence and loss of role (Hutchinson\net al., 2018).\nBreathlessness often brings panic, fear, anxiety, depression, hopelessness, a sense of loss of control, and impending death to patients (Gysels et al., 2007). Breathlessness is closely associated with\nfatigue, pain, and depression, interfering with general activities,\nmood, and enjoyment of life (Reddy et al., 2009). The meaning of\nbreathlessness may vary between patients with cancer, COPD, heart\nfailure, and motor neurone disease (Gysels and Higginson, 2011).\nFor people with cancer, breathlessness, apart from being a signal\nof cancer, is also a reminder of mortality, despite their optimism\nwith treatment. In people with COPD, breathlessness is perceived\nas self-​inflicted resulting from tobacco use. People are alarmed by\nthe debilitation caused by breathlessness—​often in the later stages\nof disease because of its insidious nature. For people with heart\nfailure, breathlessness is associated with functional limitations and\ncontributes to the negative effects of other symptoms. In people\n\nwith motor neurone disease, breathlessness makes people realize\nthat the illness affects mechanisms essential for living (Gysels and\nHigginson, 2011).\nUnder-​recognition of breathlessness by healthcare workers adds\nto people’s helplessness. The ‘invisibility’ of chronic breathlessness\n(Gysels "},{"id": "9.2","title": "Cough and Other Pulmonary Symptoms","chapter": "9.2","section": "9","sectionLabel": "Cardiorespiratory Symptoms","start": 604,"end": 611,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "606\n\nSECTION 9 Cardiorespiratory symptoms and disorders\n\nGram-​\nnegative organisms (Klebsiella pneumonia, Haemophilus\ninfluenzae, Escherichia coli). Corticosteroids are ineffective in\nchemical pneumonitis and may be associated with the development\nof Gram-​negative pneumonia (Waybright et al., 2013). For malignant oesophago-​respiratory fistulas, self-​expandable coated stents\nmay be used in selected cases.\n\nSymptomatic treatment of cough\nBased on the best available evidence, a stepwise approach in managing cough in palliative care and lung cancer respectively has been\nsuggested, both starting with an initial trial of simple linctus or\ncough demulcents (Wee et al., 2012; Molassiotis et al., 2017). If there\nis no response to simple linctus, a switch to centrally acting opioid\nantitussives or a trial of sodium cromoglycate before switching is\nsuggested (Wee et al., 2012). This is followed by peripherally acting\nantitussives if the cough is opioid resistant. If still ineffective, local\nanaesthetics may be considered. If all these fail, one may consider\ngabapentin (Molassiotis et al., 2017).\nAntitussives can be centrally or peripherally acting. Centrally\nacting antitussives include opioid derivatives acting on the mu\nopioid receptors, dextromethorphan, and neuromodulators of\ncough reflex including amitriptyline, gabapentin, and pregabalin.\nBoth codeine and dextromethorphan are common ingredients in\nover-​the-​counter cough syrups. Codeine, previously regarded as\na gold standard drug in controlling cough, has little supportive\nevidence, and may carry side effects of somnolence, nausea, and\nconstipation. Dextromethorphan is a non-​opioid antitussive with\naction on N-​methyl-​D-​aspartate receptors and may be preferred\nby patients (Wee et al., 2012). It is metabolized in the liver by the\ncytochrome P450 isoform CYP2D6 and hence potential drug interactions should be noted.\nPeripherally acting antitussives including sodium cromoglycate,\nlevodropropizine, and local anaesthetics target the sensory afferents\n(Chung, 2017; Ryan et al., 2018).\nMost of the randomized, double blind, placebo-​controlled studies\non antitussives involved patients with chronic stable cough without\nsignificant lung disease or non-​cancer patients (Ryan et al., 2018).\nDrugs shown to be more effective than placebo in these randomized controlled trials (RCTs) include morphine sulphate 5 mg twice\ndaily for 4 weeks (n = 27) (Morice et al., 2007), gabapentin at a maximum daily dose of 1800 mg for 10 weeks (n = 62 patients) (Ryan\net al., 2012), pregabalin 300 mg and speech therapy for 14 weeks\n(n = 40) (Vertigan et al., 2016), erythromycin 250 mg daily for 12\nweeks (n = 30) (Yousaf et al., 2010), and azithromycin 500 mg daily\nfor 3 days followed by 250 mg three times daily for 8 weeks (n = 44)\n(Hodgson et al., 2016).\nLess evidence is available on the use of antitussives in patients\nwith advanced cancer. Sodium cromoglycate was shown to be safe\nand more effective than placebo in reducing cou"},{"id": "10.1","title": "Skin Problems in Palliative Care","chapter": "10.1","section": "10","sectionLabel": "Skin and Oral Symptoms","start": 613,"end": 621,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 10.1 Skin problems in palliative care\n\nPressure damage prevention\nMaida et al., (2012) demonstrate in their prospective case series in\npatients with advanced illness, that 282 patients had 823 wounds, of\nwhich 61.5% (n = 506) were pressure ulcers, underscoring the need\nfor comprehensive assessment and prevention strategies. The use of\nrisk assessment tools needs to be combined with clinical judgement\nand patients’ preferences. The Hunters Hill Marie Curie Centre risk\nassessment tool has been developed specifically for palliative care\npatients who are, in the main, at considerable risk of developing\npressure ulcers (Chaplin, 2000). Patients require regular repositioning on pressure redistribution devices (mattresses, seating).\nRepositioning is also essential to maintain movement in joints, to\nhelp prevent contractures and pain from immobility, and for psychological reasons. The frequency of position change will be based\non assessment of risk, the general condition of the patient, and the\nequipment being used.\nSkin condition is the best indicator of how often position changes\nneed to occur. This is assessed by lightly pressing an area of skin\non which the patient was lying prior to turning. The skin should\ngo white (blanche) and then return to its normal colour. The time\ntaken to return to normal should be no longer than twice the length\nof time for which the finger pressure was applied. A fixed, red mark\nthat does not fade within 20 minutes after pressure has been relieved\nis indicative of pressure damage, loss of tissue viability, and varying\ndegrees of skin breakdown and ulceration (National Pressure Ulcer\nAdvisory Panel, 2014).\nPatients with no evidence of pressure damage simply require\ngood skin care and ongoing monitoring. However, pressure ulcers\ncan still occur in spite of rigorous assessment and monitoring, and\nthe use of pressure-​relieving devices for beds and chairs.\nThe development of a pressure ulcer is understandably distressing\nfor patients, families, and clinicians. Once an ulcer is established,\ncare and management revolve around pressure relief, local wound\nmanagement, including the management of moisture, and symptom\nmanagement.\nThe nature and stage of the damage dictates treatment interventions together with curative or palliative goals. Strategies for healing\nand/​or palliation are discussed in the section on local wound management and symptom control, using the conceptual framework of\nwound bed preparation (WBP). See Table 10.1.1.\n\nPrevention of skin damage from moisture\nMoisture lesions can be confused with sacral pressure ulcers, because of their location. However, the skin damage is associated with\nbody fluids (urine, faeces, sweat) as opposed to pressure and shear\n(Bianchi, 2012). If the patient also has a pressure ulcer, the exudate\nfrom the ulcer will contribute further to the moisture damage unless it is managed effectively with local wound management strategies. In conjunction with good skin care, interventions"},{"id": "10.2","title": "Palliative Wound and Ostomy Care","chapter": "10.2","section": "10","sectionLabel": "Skin and Oral Symptoms","start": 622,"end": 647,"pages": 26,"weight": 0.0208,"text": "624\n\nSECTION 10 Skin and oral symptoms and disorders\n\npressure injury if a wound appears despite the performance of all of\nthese practices.\nUnavoidable pressure injuries occur in the very ill. A retrospective\nstudy of 20 patients with unavoidable pressure injury identified ten\ncommon comorbidities: hypoalbuminemia, severe anaemia, respiratory failure with intubation, hypoxia with sedation or chemical paralysis, hypotension, infection or sepsis, malignancy, diabetes, renal\nfailure, and/​or congestive heart failure (Levine et al., 2009). Other\nfactors include advanced age, malnourishment, dehydration, obesity,\ntreatment with corticosteroids or vasopressors, and hospitalization\nin a critical care unit (Levine et al., 2009; Lyder, 2012; McIntyre et al.,\n2012; Cox and Roche, 2015; Cox and Schallom, 2017).\n\nSymptoms and signs in complex and\nnon-​healing wounds\nPatients with pressure injuries or other wounds may experience\npain, discomfort from bulk dressings, pruritus, odour, exudates,\nor bleeding; these complications may be exacerbated by local infection or lymphoedema (Langemo et al., 2015; Woo et al., 2015;\nTilley et al., 2016). Wound management begins with a comprehensive assessment, which should be performed weekly or with any\nchange in condition. The use of a comprehensive assessment tool is\nrecommended (Box 10.2.1). The care plan for wound management\nBox 10.2.1 Systematic wound assessment\n1 Etiology/​type of skin damage\n2 Location\n3 Stage (pressure injuries only)\n4 Dimensions: (length [head-​to-​toe], width [hip-​to-​hip], depth [use a\nq-​tip], height)\n5 Undermining/​tunneling (stage III or IV pressure injuries only):\n• Measure undermining clockwise, then the deepest part of the\nundermining\n• Measure depth of sinus tract/​tunnel and give direction by the\nclock method\n6 Wound base description:\n• Granulation: pink or beefy red, shiny, moist, granular\n• Necrotic tissue: gray to black and moist\n• Eschar: gray to black and dry/​leathery\n• Slough: yellow to white and may be stringy (loose) or appear as a\nlayer over the wound base (adherent)\n• Epithelial: new or pink shiny tissue\n• May be mixed so approximate in percentages\n7 Drainage:\n• Amount: scant, moderate, or copious\n• Color/​consistency: serous, serosanguineous, purulent, or other\n8 Odor: present or not\n9 Periwound skin\n10 Pain:\n• Associated with the wound dressing removal, cleansing,\ndebriding, or dressing application\n11 Infection\n• Yes or no. Describe signs or symptoms.\nReproduced with permission from Tilley, C.P. et al. (2019). Palliative Wound, Ostomy,\nand Continence Care. In Ferrell, B.R. and Paice, J.A. (Eds.). Oxford Textbook of Palliative\nNursing, Fifth Edition. New York, USA: Oxford University Press. Source: data from Tilley,\nC. et al. (2016). Palliative Wound Care for Malignant Fungating Wounds: Holistic\nConsiderations at End-​of-​Life. Nurs Clin North Am. 51(3):513–​531. DOI: 10.1016/​\nj.cnur.2016.05.006.\n\nencompasses the use of basic and advanced dressings, debridement,\ntraditional p"},{"id": "10.3","title": "Lymphoedema and Oedema in Advanced Disease","chapter": "10.3","section": "10","sectionLabel": "Skin and Oral Symptoms","start": 648,"end": 655,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "650\n\nSECTION 10 Skin and oral symptoms and disorders\n\nFig. 10.3.1 Severe skin changes in a lymphoedematous leg.\n\nSpecific situations\nAdvanced breast cancer\nOedema in advanced breast cancer can be particularly distressing.\nIt can occur as a result of recurrent disease in the axilla, when it may\nbe associated with a brachial plexopathy, which, by causing paralysis of the arm, can exacerbate the swelling.\nIn addition, metastatic cancer can develop in the skin of the chest\nwall (cancer en cuirasse) and upper arm. This tends to obstruct the\nskin lymphatics and may cause gross oedema of the arm with the\nskin becoming tense, stretched, and fragile. In these circumstances,\nthe limb can become useless, heavy, and painful. The fingers and\nhand can become deformed and may look like a ‘boxing glove’. The\nskin can break, leading to profuse lymphorrhoea, predisposing to\ninfection and ulceration.\nThe extreme nature of the oedema in this situation is probably\nexplained by the combination of damage to the deeper lymphatics\nby surgery, radiotherapy, and possibly tumour, and damage to the\nsuperficial skin lymphatics by tumour. It is believed that the superficial lymphatics act as a collateral system of drainage when the\ndeeper system is damaged, a process exploited by the compression\nand massage techniques used in the treatment of lymphoedema.\nWhen these are blocked by tumour, the collateral routes are no\nlonger available so severe oedema develops. There may be additional factors such as extrinsic compression of the axillary vein,\nwhich can contribute to the swelling.\nAdvanced pelvic and abdominal cancer\nGross oedema of the legs, genitalia, and abdomen can occur in patients with advanced pelvic and abdominal cancers. The clinical features may include:\n• Soft, pitting, or firm oedema of the leg(s)\n• Stretched, shiny, fragile skin\n• Lymphorrhoea\n\n• Ulceration\n• Genital oedema—​scrotal and penile or vulval\n• Pitting oedema of the abdominal wall\n• Ascites\n• Dilated veins on the abdominal wall in inferior vena caval\nobstruction\n• Stemmer’s sign may be negative.\nGross oedema can severely restrict mobility. Patients may be unable\nto walk, climb stairs, get up from a chair, or lift their own legs on to\ntheir bed. This may exacerbate existing problems resulting from the\nmuscle weakness of advanced cancer.\nPatients may find the appearance of their limbs and genitalia difficult to cope with. Furthermore, in men, penile oedema may lead\nto problems with micturition and sexual function. It may be difficult to insert a catheter per urethram, if needed, so sometimes a\nsuprapubic catheter is necessary.\nThe oedema can be part of a ‘pelvic syndrome’ which includes\nother symptoms such as neuropathic pain, bladder spasms, fistulae,\nhaemorrhage, and malodorous discharge (Sanz and del Valle, 2007).\nFacial oedema in advanced head and neck cancer\nPrevious treatment of head and neck cancer with radiotherapy and\nneck dissections can cause lymphoedema, commonly in the submental region. Howeve"},{"id": "10.4","title": "Oral Care in Palliative Medicine","chapter": "10.4","section": "10","sectionLabel": "Skin and Oral Symptoms","start": 656,"end": 671,"pages": 16,"weight": 0.0128,"text": "658\n\nSECTION 10 Skin and oral symptoms and disorders\n\nphysicians, and especially nurses. Dental professionals are important members of the extended palliative care MDT (i.e. dentists, dental hygienists). They have a number of key roles, including\ntraining of other members of the MDT, management of specific\noral problems (e.g. dental caries), and management of complex oral\nproblems (in combination with other members of the MDT). Many\ndental procedures can be performed in the home or hospice setting,\nalthough such ‘domiciliary dentistry’ requires specialized skills and\nappropriate equipment (Walls, 2005).\nOther members of the broader MDT team will, of course, have a\nmajor role in the management of certain oral problems (e.g. speech\nand language therapists, dietitians).\n\nManagement: evidence-​based practice\nThe oral care that is actually delivered in palliative care settings is\nfrequently based on traditional modes of practice rather than on\navailable research evidence. Consequently, many patients continue\nto receive relatively ineffective treatments for their oral problems\n(e.g. ice cubes for xerostomia), while some patients continue to\nreceive entirely inappropriate treatments for their oral problems\n(e.g. vitamin C tablets for ‘dirty mouth’) (Adkinson et al., 2014).\nGiven that there is now a substantial evidence base for oral care in\nthe palliative care population this ought to be the basis for therapeutic strategies and practice (Davies and Finlay, 2005; Davies and\nEpstein, 2010).\n\nOral hygiene\nMaintenance of good oral hygiene is important for the maintenance\nof good quality of life in patients with cancer and other life-​limiting\nillnesses (Sweeney and Davies, 2010). Oral care should ideally be\nundertaken by the patient, but debilitated patients may require\ninput from carers and/​or healthcare professionals. Patients with\nvery poor oral hygiene often benefit from initial input from dental\nprofessionals.\n\nDental care\nToothbrushing\nThe single most important oral hygiene measure is toothbrushing,\nwhich should be undertaken at least twice daily (Sweeney and\nDavies, 2010).\nA wide range of toothbrushes is available, including powered\n(‘electric’) toothbrushes. It is recommended that a small-​headed\nbrush, which has soft to medium texture bristles is used. ‘Ultra-​soft’\ntoothbrushes can be used for patients whose mouths are sore; such\ntoothbrushes include baby brushes and specialist brushes (e.g. TePe\nSpecial Care® toothbrush). Powered toothbrushes with a rotation\noscillation action appear to be better at removing dental plaque than\nmanual toothbrushes (and other types of powered toothbrushes)\n(Robinson et al., 2005).\nThe recommended life span of a toothbrush is about 3 months,\nbut it should be replaced sooner if the filaments of the brush become softened and/​or misshapen. (At this stage, the brush is no\nlonger effective at removing dental plaque). Toothbrushes should\nbe replaced sooner if the patient is immunosuppressed or receiving\nchemotherapy. Fu"},{"id": "11.1","title": "Dysuria, Frequency, and Bladder Spasm","chapter": "11.1","section": "11","sectionLabel": "Genitourinary Symptoms","start": 673,"end": 676,"pages": 4,"weight": 0.0032,"text": "CHAPTER 11.1 Dysuria, frequency, and bladder spasm\n\nTable 11.1.1 Medications for overactive bladder, listed in alphabetical order\nAnticholinergic medications\nDarifenacin\n\n7.5 mg oral daily, may increase up to 15 mg\ndaily\n\nDo not increase dose if taking concomitant CYP3A4 inhibitors\n\nFesoterodine\n\n4 mg oral daily, may increase up to 8 mg daily Severe renal impairment, do not exceed 4 mg daily\n\nOxybutynin\n\n5 mg oral daily, may increase up to 20 mg\ndaily\n\nDo not use in patients with narrow-​angle glaucoma, impaired gastrointestinal\nmotility, or urinary retention\n\nOxybutynin, topical gel\n\n3%: 3 pumps (84 mg/​day) applied once daily\nto clean, dry, intact skin on the abdomen, or\nupper arms/​shoulders, or thighs\n10%: the contents of one sachet applied once\ndaily to dry, intact skin on the abdomen,\nupper arms/​shoulders, or thighs\n\nApply immediately after actuating the dose; application sites may be rotated to\nreduce the potential for local site reactions\n\nOxybutynin, topical skin\npatch\n\n3.9 mg/​day applied to dry, intact skin on the\nabdomen, hip, or buttock twice weekly (every\n3 or 4 days)\n\nA new application site should be selected with each application to avoid\nreapplication to the same site within 7 days\n\nSolifenacin\n\n5 mg oral daily, may be increased up to 10\nmg daily\n\n5 mg may be used in combination with mirabegron 25 mg oral daily\n\nTolterodine\n\n2 mg oral daily, may increase up to 4 mg daily Not to be used in severe renal or hepatic impairment\n\nTrospium\n\n20 mg oral twice daily, extended release 60\nmg once daily\n\nMay titrate down to 20 mg immediate release daily based on tolerability\n\n25 mg oral daily, may increase up to 50 mg\ndaily\n\nMay be used as combination regimen: 25 mg oral daily plus solifenacin\n5 mg oral daily\n\nBeta-​3 adrenoceptor agonist\nMirabegron\n\nSource: data from Gormley, E.A. et al. (2015). Diagnosis and treatment of overactive bladder (non-​neurogenic) in adults: AUA/​SUFU guideline amendment. J Urol. 193(5):1572–​80.\nDOI: 10.1016/​j.juro.2015.01.087.\n\ninappropriate medication can lead to not only increased healthcare\ndollars, but also adverse drug reactions, hospitalizations, and mortality (Pasina et al., 2014; American Geriatrics Society 2015 Beers\nCriteria Update Expert Panel, 2015). The American Geriatric\nSociety created the Beers criteria evaluating potentially inappropriate medication use in older adults (Campanelli, 2012; American\nGeriatrics Society 2015 Beers Criteria Update Expert Panel, 2015).\nIncluded in this review was the use of anticholinergic medication\ntreatments for OAB as being considered potentially inappropriate.\nAnticholinergic–​\nanticholinergic drug–​\ndrug interactions were\nstrongly associated with harmful outcomes in older adults, and\nwere listed as medications to strongly avoid due to interactions\nthat increase the risk of cognitive decline. Interestingly, the Beers\ncriteria are applicable to all older adults with the exclusion of those\nin palliative and hospice care. Therefore, as clinicians should be\naware of"},{"id": "11.2","title": "Obstructive Urinary Disorders","chapter": "11.2","section": "11","sectionLabel": "Genitourinary Symptoms","start": 677,"end": 683,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 11.2 Obstructive urinary disorders\n\nis common practice. Monitoring treatment response can be done by\nre-​evaluating the post-​void residual on bladder scan, checking serial\nurine cultures, and/​or having the patient complete the American\nUrological Association Symptom Index (Barry et al., 1992).\nAlpha-​blockers\nAlpha-​\nblockers work by relaxing prostatic smooth muscle and\ndecreasing outflow resistance, and take approximately 1–​2 weeks\nto reach full effect (Lepor et al., 1993). Newer medications (e.g.\ntamsulosin and silodosin) are specific to the alpha-​1a receptor, the\ndominant alpha-​1 receptor in the prostate and bladder outlet, and\ntherefore have a better side effect profile without orthostatic hypotension. Tamsulosin is dosed 0.4 mg daily, although 0.8 mg is used\nif there is no improvement after 2–​4 weeks. Silodosin is dosed 8\nmg daily unless there is renal impairment with a glomerular filtration rate of 30–​50 mL/​min, in which case 4 mg daily is appropriate.\nIf the glomerular filtration rate is less than 30 mL/​min, silodosin\nis contraindicated. Alpha-​blockers have demonstrated efficacy in\nwomen and should be considered in cases of non-​obstructive retention, although this indication is less well studied (Reitz et al., 2004).\n5-​Alpha-​reductase inhibitors\nThe two 5-​alpha-​reductase inhibitors are finasteride and dutasteride.\nThese work by preventing the conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone to decrease the size of the prostate via inhibition\nof growth factor production, and take approximately 3 months to\nreach full effect (Gormley et al., 1992). Finasteride is dosed at 5 mg\ndaily, and dutasteride is dosed at 0.5 mg daily; no adjustments are\nrequired for renal impairment. These medications have no known\nrole in treating women with retention.\nClean intermittent catheterization\n\nprostatic urethra in men or any patient who has a tortuous urethra.\nUltimately, if a standard catheter does not work, urology consultation is recommended.\nWhile urethral catheters can improve patient comfort, they\ndo carry increased risks. Most notably, indwelling catheters\ncolonize the bladder; rates of bacteriuria are 3–​10% per day of\ncatheterization, so most patients are colonized after 30 days\n(Warren, 1997). Patients without UTI symptoms (e.g. suprapubic\ntenderness and fever) should not be treated for asymptomatic\nbacteriuria. However, many patients ultimately develop catheter-​\nassociated urinary tract infections (CAUTIs). Data from the\nNational Healthcare Safety Network in 2006 reported pooled\nmean CAUTI rates of 3.1–​7.5 infections per 1000 catheter-​days\n(Edwards et al., 2007).\nThere is a paucity of data supporting catheter change frequency,\nuse of antibiotic prophylaxis, and differing techniques in management, among other strategies, to reduce the incidence of CAUTIs\nin long-​term catheterized patients (Cooper et al., 2016). Although\nantimicrobial-​coated catheters have shown decreased rates of bacteriuria in short-​term catheterized"},{"id": "12.1","title": "Fatigue","chapter": "12.1","section": "12","sectionLabel": "Constitutional Symptoms","start": 685,"end": 697,"pages": 13,"weight": 0.0104,"text": "CHAPTER 12.1 Fatigue\n\nCentral nervous system abnormalities\nThe mechanisms by which fatigue is perceived or induced in the\ncentral nervous system (CNS) are poorly understood. Primary or\nsecondary tumours involving the CNS and leading to the invasion of brain tissue (particularly the pituitary gland, with resulting\nendocrine abnormalities) appear to be possible causes of fatigue in\ncancer patients. Disturbed cognitive functioning may be caused by\nfatigue but may also contribute to fatigue.\nBrain tumours can cause cognitive dysfunction and other tumours, such as small cell lung cancers, can affect brain function by\nproducing hormones or neurotransmitters. Antineoplastic treatments, such as chemotherapy and radiotherapy, and drugs used to\ntreat complications of cancer, such as opioids and corticosteroids,\ncan also affect the CNS. Recent research findings suggest that inflammatory cytokines play a role in mental fatigue.\nOther CNS mechanisms that have been proposed include\n(1) dysregulation of serotonin and/​or its receptors in the brain due\nto cancer or cancer treatment; (2) circadian rhythm disruptions,\nwhich negatively impact arousal and sleep patterns (prior studies\nsuggest that fatigue is positively correlated with decreased daytime\nactivity and restless sleep at night); and (3) dysregulation of the\nhypothalamic–​pituitary axis (Bower et al., 2005).\n\nmalnutrition. Our group found no correlation between fatigue and\nnutritional status or weight in a population of breast cancer patients\n(Bruera et al., 1989). However, severe malnutrition without fatigue\ncan be observed in patients with anorexia nervosa and in some patient populations with solid tumours. Fig. 12.1.2 illustrates the potential relationship between cachexia and fatigue.\nIt has been proposed that anorexia and fatigue may be an expression of the major metabolic abnormalities that occur in cancer\npatients, rather than simply an expression of malnutrition per se\n(Seruga et al., 2008). This situation would be similar to the occurrence of a catabolic state due to a viral infection or in the early postoperative period whereby patients experience anorexia and fatigue\nthat are secondary to the metabolic abnormalities rather than being\ncauses of those abnormalities.\n\nInfection\nFatigue is frequently associated with infections, particularly those\nthat are recurrent or protracted. It may occur as a prodrome, and it\nmay outlast the infection by weeks or even months. Chronic infection and cancer induce the same mediators for cachexia, including\ninflammatory cytokines (Seruga et al., 2008), and they may share\nsimilar mediators for fatigue as well.\n\nRelationship between fatigue and cachexia\n\nAnaemia\n\nFatigue and cachexia coexist in the great majority of patients with\nadvanced-​stage cancer, and it is likely that malnutrition is a major\ncontributor to fatigue. The loss of muscle mass resulting from progressive cachexia can cause profound weakness and fatigue. As previously discussed, structural and bioch"},{"id": "12.2","title": "Sexuality in Palliative Care","chapter": "12.2","section": "12","sectionLabel": "Constitutional Symptoms","start": 698,"end": 707,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "700\n\nSECTION 12 Constitutional symptoms and related disorders\n\nsome health professionals make assumptions about the patient’s\nsexuality; assumptions that are based on the patient’s age, gender,\nstage of disease, cultural identity, and partnership status. Similarly,\nKadwell (2016) found that health professionals often positioned palliative cancer patients as ‘too unwell’, ‘too fatigued’, ‘too nauseated’,\nor in ‘too much pain’ to engage in sexual practices, and thus avoided\nraising issues of sexuality as a result. According to Kadwell (2016),\nsome health professionals also reported that sexual expression within\nhospital settings was not always considered appropriate by some of\ntheir colleagues, and thus was discouraged. These health professionals reported that some patients and their partners had made an\nassumption that they would be judged or admonished by hospital\nstaff if they engaged in intimate acts in the hospital setting (including\nsome feeling it was inappropriate to lie and cuddle on the bed with\ntheir partners)—​which led to cessation of many intimate practices.\nHowever, two studies (Kadwell, 2016; Benoot et al., 2018) found that\nsome health professionals have reportedly assisted patients and their\npartners to feel comfortable to continue sexual and intimate expression in the hospital setting, by giving permission to couples to lie on\nthe hospital bed together, providing advice on how to safely navigate\nmedical equipment, and providing adequate and mutually agreed\nupon privacy norms.\nWhile research indicates that the topic of sexuality is rarely\nraised, the majority of palliative patients and their partners have\nconsistently reported that they wish to discuss issues of sexuality\nwith health professionals. Hordern and Street (2007c) interviewed\n50 patients across a range of ages, cancer types, and stages, with\nresults showing that patients want to play an active role in decision-​\nmaking. In particular, patients want information and support about\nhow to live with and manage the side effects of treatment, how\nothers cope, and the choices they could make to regain sexual confidence until the end of life. Similarly, McClelland (2016) found that\npeople with advanced cancer report wanting to receive information\nfrom health professionals on how to safely manage their bodies\nduring sex to reduce pain and enjoy pleasurable sex.\nAccording to Hordern and Street (2007b, 2007d), these ‘mismatched expectations’ between patient and health professionals\ncould be overcome by health professionals reflecting upon and recognizing the personal and professional influences that shape their\nbeliefs about patient sexuality, and checking their assumptions with\nthe patients in their care. Indeed, Kadwell (2016) outlines a range\nof positive outcomes for patients and partners when health professionals provided the opportunity to discuss sexual and intimate\nchanges, including facilitating a renegotiation of the amount and\ntype of sexual contact between patients and pa"},{"id": "12.3","title": "Sleep Disorders in Palliative Care","chapter": "12.3","section": "12","sectionLabel": "Constitutional Symptoms","start": 708,"end": 716,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "710\n\nSECTION 12 Constitutional symptoms and related disorders\n\nto be multiple pathophysiological processes that initiate or sustain\nthese disturbances. An increased vulnerability to sleep disturbances\nhas been associated with a positive family history of insomnia and,\npossibly, genetic factors, such as the presence of the short allele of\nthe serotonin transporter gene (Morin and Benca, 2012). A fatal familiar insomnia is an autosomal dominant inherited disease characterized by severe sleep disorder, dysautonomia, motor signs, and\nabnormal behaviour (Llorens et al., 2017).\nSome primary sleep disturbances are thought to be a disorder\nof hyperarousal. This may be experienced throughout the entire\nday and manifests as hypervigilance during the day and difficulty\nin initiating and maintaining sleep during the night (Roth, 2007).\nThis state has been demonstrated through measurements of the\nwhole-​body metabolic rate, heart rate variability, neuroendocrine\nmeasures, and functional neuroimaging. For example, a pattern of\nhyperarousal in patients with primary sleep disorders was shown by\nraised body temperature, increased 24-​hour metabolic rate, heart\nrate, and electromyographic activity (Bonnet and Arand, 2012).\nHypothalamic–​pituitary–​adrenal axis dysfunction has been confirmed through plasma and urinary measures of norepinephrine\n(noradrenaline), cortisol, and adrenocorticotropic hormone—​all of\nwhich appear to have higher levels in subjects with primary sleep\ndisturbances (Bonnet and Arand, 2012).\nUsing quantitative electroencephalogram analysis, subjects with\nprimary sleep disturbance also have been shown to have an increase\nin beta and gamma frequencies at sleep onset and during NREM\nsleep. These are thought to be associated with increased cognitive activity, as well as greater cerebral glucose metabolism during\nwaking and NREM sleep states (Nofzinger et al., 2004).\n\nObstructive sleep apnoea is associated with continued ventilatory effort (Luyster et al., 2015). Obstructive sleep apnoea is associated primarily with heavy snoring and excessive daytime sleepiness, although\nsome patients report frequent nocturnal wakening, morning headaches, choking or gasping, nocturia, and fatigue (Regestein, 1977;\nMorin and Benca, 2012). The syndrome is associated with obesity,\nmale sex, older age, short neck, and redundant pharyngeal tissues.\nPatients with serious illnesses also can develop periodic limb\nmovement in sleep (Regestein, 1977; Katz and McHorney, 1998).\nThis disorder consists of repetitive stereotyped leg and/​or arm\nmovements which occur at intervals of 20–​40 seconds, typically\nin clusters throughout the night. It can be secondary to sedative–​\nhypnotic withdrawal, tricyclic medication, anaemia, uraemia, leukaemia, diabetes mellitus, or peripheral neuropathy. In some cases,\nit might also be associated with restless legs syndrome (Regestein,\n1977; Katz and McHorney, 1998), which interferes with sleep onset\n(Morin and Benca, 2012).\nEnvironmental facto"},{"id": "12.4","title": "Assessment and Management of Thrombotic Complications","chapter": "12.4","section": "12","sectionLabel": "Constitutional Symptoms","start": 717,"end": 726,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 12.4 Assessment and management of thrombotic complications\n\nbefore considering a PE. Similarly, swollen legs may be managed as\ncellulitis, hypoalbuminaemia, or lymphoedema rather than DVT.\nFurthermore, such diagnoses are commonly seen in oncology and\nmay mask the symptoms of VTE if occurring concurrently.\nSecondly, tools and investigations embedded in clinical practice for\nthe assessment of suspected VTE might not be helpful in the context\nof cancer. The Wells score, a commonly used clinical prediction tool\nfor the presence of DVT or PE, has limited utility with cancer patients. With 1 point attributed to the presence of active cancer (as defined by treatment within 6 months or palliative), only 1 point more is\nrequired to support a 28% chance of VTE. As such, it is unlikely to be\nhelpful as an exclusory prediction model (Wells et al., 1997).\nD-​dimers are fibrin degradation products which are present in\nthe blood when a clot has undergone fibrinolysis. Similarly, elevated D-​dimer levels are commonplace with cancer due to the\ncomplex relationship between cancer metastasis progression and\nfibrin activity; therefore, D-​dimer is only of use as an exclusory test.\nNeither of these tests is recommended in the routine work-​up of\nsuspected CAT.\nA further challenge exists for palliative care teams managing patients within the community or as inpatients in stand-​alone hospices or SPCUs. Within these care settings, the decision whether\nto investigate for a suspected VTE is complicated by the fact that\npatients will need to be transferred, albeit temporarily, to a suitable\ndiagnostic facility (Sheard et al., 2013). For patients nearing the end\nof life, or those who are immovable, such an investigation may be\nconsidered inappropriately burdensome. Some SPCUs now have\non-​site Doppler ultrasound machines which can be used by suitably\ntrained members of staff. While unlikely to pick up small below-​\nknee thrombi, three-​point compression ultrasonography is being increasingly used within units in the UK as a bedside diagnostic tool.\nThe identification of PEs on CT scans performed for indications other than investigation of suspected VTE is a growing clinical problem. Most commonly identified on staging scans or those\nundertaken to evaluate the response to anticancer treatment, incidental PEs occur in 3.1% of all cancer patients. Describing them\nas ‘asymptomatic PEs’ is generally incorrect since a careful history\nwill usually identify symptoms that have not previously been volunteered. Current guidelines recommend using the same approach\nto type and duration of anticoagulation as is used for symptomatic\ncancer-​associated PE, particularly those as far down as segmental\nbranches of the pulmonary vasculature (Farge et al., 2013). However,\ndata regarding the significance of subsegmental PE in the oncology\nsetting are unclear; currently, survival data suggest there is no advantage in anticoagulating an isolated incidental subsegmental PE.\nTherefore, in th"},{"id": "12.5","title": "Assessment and Management of Bleeding Complications","chapter": "12.5","section": "12","sectionLabel": "Constitutional Symptoms","start": 727,"end": 736,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 12.5 Assessment and management of bleeding complications in the medically ill\n\n• Unintended critical ischaemia of organs at or adjacent to the site\nof treatment\n• Specific risks related to the proposed site of embolization.\n\nRadiotherapy\nThe use of external beam and internal radiotherapy to manage\nbleeding in cancer patients can be highly effective. Response rates\nvary from 45% to 100% depending on tumour site and histology\n(Cihoric et al., 2012). When treatment is with palliative intent, fractionation regimens are kept short in order to minimize disruption to\nthe patient, and moderate doses are used to ensure that the burdens\nof treatment-​related toxicity are outweighed by the potential benefits.\nLimitations of radiotherapy include anatomical site (some\nareas are less amenable to the side effects of radiotherapy), radio-​\nresponsiveness of the tumour, previous exposure to radiotherapy at\nthe affected site (which limits maximum radiotherapy dose), and\nthe proximity of radiotherapy services to the patient.\n\nSurgery\nRemoval of bleeding tissue or surgical ligation of blood vessels that\nsupply it has long been an established technique for controlling\nbleeding. Surgery is often technically difficult due to the abnormal\nanatomy of tumours, and confers the associated risks of general anaesthesia in ill patients. Due to the risks involved, surgery should be\nreserved for patients at an early stage of their disease, or those who\nhave exhausted other options such as pharmacological treatments,\nradiotherapy, or where vascular interventional radiology is not\npossible.\n\nManagement of bleeding disorders\nBlood and plasma products\nPlatelets\nMeta-​analysis has showed that for patients without active bleeding,\na platelet count of 10 × 109/​L was not associated with increased\nbleeding compared to a higher platelet count (Estcourt et al.,\n2011) and above this threshold platelet transfusion is not recommended in patients with asymptomatic chronic bone marrow\nfailure. In septic patients, however, clinicians may consider a higher\nplatelet threshold of 20 × 109/​L.\nHowever, when bleeding of any severity is present, the thresholds\nfor platelet support are different. In patients with bleeding that is not\nconsidered severe, maintaining a platelet count of 30 × 109/​L is recommended. In severe bleeding, the platelet count should be maintained at higher than 50 × 109/​L. In multiple trauma, traumatic brain\ninjury, or spontaneous intracerebral haemorrhage, a higher count of\ngreater than 100 × 109/​L should be adopted (Estcourt et al., 2017).\nSome procedures also require a higher platelet count, see Table\n12.5.2.\nPlatelet transfusions are also relatively contraindicated in patients with thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura because of the\nrisk of precipitating thromboses (Estcourt et al., 2017). Prophylactic\ntransfusion is not recommended in patients with increased platelet\ndestruction such as autoimmune or drug-​\nassociated immune\nthrombocytopenia. They may benefit from"},{"id": "13.1","title": "Coping and Resilience in Palliative Medicine","chapter": "13.1","section": "13","sectionLabel": "Psychiatric and Psychological","start": 739,"end": 746,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 13.1 Coping and resilience in palliative medicine\n\nstress and coping strategies that were not represented by a coping\ninventory (Gottlieb and Gignac, 1996). Information gained from\ninterviews can be further integrated into an inventory (Folkman\nand Moskowitz, 2004).\n\nProactive coping\nProactive coping is a strategy people employ in advance, in order to\nprevent or reduce the impact of an anticipated stressor. Aspinwall\nand Taylor (1997) describe the dynamic nature of proactive coping\nin five stages: resource accumulation, recognition of potential\nstressors, initial appraisal, preliminary coping efforts, and elicitation and use of feedback concerning initial efforts. According\nto this model, proactive coping requires individual and social resources and has to be coupled with specific actions (Aspinwall and\nTaylor, 1997).\nThe Proactive Coping Inventory is a tool designed to evaluate\nproactive coping (Greenglass et al., 1999). In a study of 120 adults,\nwho were anticipating the death of a loved one due to terminal\nillness, proactive coping had a predictive power in personal growth.\nSocial support was a significant mediator of this effect. These results\nsuggest that interventions to enhance proactive coping may benefit\nanticipatory grievers (Rogalla, 2018). A study in ageing individuals\nconcluded that proactive coping can be taught and may be used as\na tool to facilitate future-​oriented self-​regulation in ageing individuals (Bode et al., 2007).\n\nCoping flexibility\nCoping is a dynamic process, whereby one’s coping strategy changes\naccording to the situational demands, also known as ‘coping flexibility’ (Lester et al., 1994). Flexibility can be appreciated also at the\nappraisal stage of an event though it will not necessarily lead to\nflexibility in choosing coping strategies (Cheng et al., 2000). The five\nmajor measurements used to evaluate coping flexibility are broad\nrepertoire, balanced profile, cross-​situational variability, strategy–​\nsituation fit, and perceived ability (Cheng et al., 2014).\n\nSelf-​efficacy for coping with cancer\nAccording to the self-​efficacy theory, people who have greater confidence in their ability to execute courses of action, such as coping\nbehaviours, have higher chances to attain goals such as preserving\nquality of life and limiting stress. Self-​efficacy for coping with\ncancer is a specific construct that refers to the individual’s behaviours during the course of cancer. The Cancer Behaviour Inventory\ntargets seven specific coping strategies that show close alliance to\npositive outcomes in adjusting to cancer: maintenance of activity\nand independence, seeking and understanding medical information, stress management, coping with treatment-​related side effects,\naccepting cancer/​maintaining positive attitude, affective regulation,\nand seeking support (Merluzzi et al., 2001).\nIn a meta-​analysis of studies evaluating self-​efficacy for coping\nwith cancer using the Cancer Behaviour Inventory, Chirico and\ncolleague"},{"id": "13.2","title": "Depression, Demoralization, and Suicidality","chapter": "13.2","section": "13","sectionLabel": "Psychiatric and Psychological","start": 747,"end": 755,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 13.2 Depression, demoralization, and suicidality\n\nBarriers to recognition of depression\nThe potentially confounding effect of medical symptoms is only\none of several barriers to the recognition of depression in palliative\nmedicine. The stigma attached to mental illness may cause the patient to withhold data. For family and medical staff, acknowledging\ndepression may appear to deny the reality of the patient’s distress,\nor seem a criticism of the sufferer’s coping. ‘Isn’t this normal?’ or\n‘Wouldn’t you be depressed?’ are statements that both reflect suffering and express indignation that it should be observed. In fact,\nresponding to such complicated emotions, or acting in accord with\ncultural beliefs, family members may deliberately or inadvertently\nconceal their relative’s distress. The most basic barrier to recognizing depression, though, may be the limited time of clinicians.\nPhysicians may be trained to focus on physical symptoms and may\navoid opening what is feared to be a Pandora’s box of unsolvable\nproblems.\n\nScreening for depression\nTo assist clinicians in recognizing depression, the National\nComprehensive Cancer Network Distress Management Panel recommends periodic screening of all patients. Brief self-​\nreport\ninstruments are most practical, though they will return more\nfalse positives than structured psychiatric interviews. A systematic review of screening scales suggests that the Beck Depression\nInventory (BDI), the General Health Questionnaire-​28 (GHQ-​28),\nand Center for Epidemiological Studies—​Depression Scale (CES-​\nD) are reliable and valid (Vodermaier et al., 2009). The Patient\nHealth Questionnaire-​9 (PHQ-​9) is briefer than any of these measures, freely available, highly reliable, and widely used. The Distress\nThermometer is a single unitary measure with less reliability, but is\nrapid and straightforward. Even asking the single question ‘Are you\ndepressed?’ can identify the majority of patients who should have\nfurther evaluation.\n\nDemoralization\nDemoralization is a state of low morale and poor coping, characterized by hopelessness, helplessness, and meaninglessness, from\nwhich can develop a desire to die (Kissane, 2014). A systematic review showed the prevalence of clinically relevant demoralization to\nbe between 13% and 18% in patients with advanced cancer or progressive disease (Robinson et al., 2015).\n\nNature of demoralization\nPatients can begin to feel they cannot cope with stressful situations,\nfeeling helpless, hopeless, and even ashamed, until the pointlessness\nof their situation invokes disheartenment and despair. Ordinarily, a\nstrong generalized hope about the value and worth of life will preserve meaning when illness appears to destroy immediate hopes.\nSimilarly, robust self-​esteem will sustain self-​worth against the infirmity of illness. Demoralization ensues when these mechanisms\nbreak down.\nLoss of morale spans a spectrum of mental states, ranging from\ndisheartenment (a mild loss of confidence), through"},{"id": "13.3","title": "Fear, Anxiety, and Adjustment Disorder","chapter": "13.3","section": "13","sectionLabel": "Psychiatric and Psychological","start": 756,"end": 763,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "758\n\nSECTION 13 Psychiatric and psychological symptoms and disorders\n\nproviding patients with a ‘safe place’ that helps them to ‘handle\ndeath in a peaceful way’ (Nissim et al., 2012). Thus far, the CALM\nintervention has only been trialled in oncology settings; yet, given\nthat it addresses a range of concerns common to all individuals\nin the palliative setting, a modified version of this intervention\nmay be applicable for use in palliative settings more broadly and\nwarrants attention from researchers and palliative care health\nprofessionals alike.\n\nDepression, anxiety, adjustment disorder,\nand hopelessness\nIf left unchecked, existential threat can lead to feelings of depression,\nanxiety, worry, and hopelessness (Bekelman et al., 2011; Evangelista\net al., 2012, 2014; Wilson and McMillan, 2013), all of which can be\nmore distressing than symptoms underlying the physical condition\nitself (Cagle et al., 2017).\nUp to 30% of patients in palliative care report feelings of depression and 10% experience anxiety symptoms (Mitchell et al., 2011).\nMoreover, approximately one in seven individuals in palliative care\nmeet criteria for adjustment disorder, characterized by the short-​\nterm experience (i.e. up to 6 months’ duration) of anxiety and/​or\ndepressive symptoms that may be accompanied by functional or\nbehavioural issues, as a response to difficulties in coping with the\nsituation (Mitchell et al., 2011).\nSymptoms of depression and adjustment disorder may manifest\ndifferently in palliative care populations, compared with the general population. For depression, diagnosis in palliative care populations should focus on changes in dysphoric mood, loss of interest or\npleasure, and brooding, self-​pity, or pessimism (Huey et al., 2018),\nwhereas for adjustment disorder, a decrease in social functioning\nis a key predictor of prevalence (Kirsh et al., 2004; Thekkumpurath\net al., 2009). To further complicate issues, the distinction between\nadjustment disorder and depression is often difficult to determine\nin palliative care populations using standard diagnostic criteria, as\nthese populations typically experience shorter durations of symptoms that fluctuate in intensity due to changes in their physical condition (Caruso et al., 2017). Consequently, current prevalence rates\nof depression and adjustment disorder in these populations may be\nunderestimated.\n\nRisk factors\nDepression, anxiety, and adjustment disorder have all been associated with younger patient age, lower bodily functionality,\nconcerns about being a burden to one’s carers, and lower satisfaction with social support (Akechi et al., 2004; Fischer and\nWedel, 2012). As illustrated in the case examples of Greg and\nJill, anxiety can stem from fears regarding uncertainties of\nliving with an advanced illness, possible future pain, and fear\nof the dying process (Monforte-​Royo et al., 2012). One qualitative study reported that feelings of hopelessness and powerlessness are rooted in perceived loss of control regard"},{"id": "13.4","title": "Delirium","chapter": "13.4","section": "13","sectionLabel": "Psychiatric and Psychological","start": 764,"end": 772,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "766\n\nSECTION 13 Psychiatric and psychological symptoms and disorders\n\nEfforts to improve subtyping have included quantitative measurement of psychomotor activity (accelerometry), validated scales\nto rate agitated behaviours (not specific for delirium), and a scale\nto measure the delirium motor subtype, but poor concordance\nbetween measures remains (Meagher et al., 2008; Godfrey et al.,\n2010). The relationships between subtype and delirium aetiology\nand outcomes are complex (Gupta et al., 2008), and yet to yield\nuseful applications in clinical practice (Maldonado, 2018). The\nevidence suggests the hypoactive subtype has poorer outcomes\n(Meagher et al., 2011), including more pressure injuries and\nhospital-​acquired infections; there are more falls in hyperactive\npresentations (O’Keeffe, 1999).\n\nDiagnostic workup\nA detailed history and examination is needed to identify the aetiologies of delirium and determine whether they are reversible.\nMost episodes have an average of three precipitants with common\naetiologies including infection, substance withdrawal (alcohol and\nnicotine), metabolic abnormalities (e.g. hypercalcaemia), hypoxia,\nand psychoactive medications (corticosteroids, opioids, anticholinergics, and benzodiazepines) (Lawlor et al., 2000a; Breitbart et al.,\n2008; Leonard et al., 2008, Bush et al., 2018). Predisposing factors\ninclude older age, physical frailty, multiple medical comorbidities,\ndementia, admission to the hospital with infection or dehydration,\nhearing and/​or visual impairment, polypharmacy, renal impairment,\nand malnutrition (Inouye, 2006; Bush et al., 2018). In cancer patients, primary or secondary involvement of the brain or leptomeninges, cognitive effects of anticancer therapies, and paraneoplastic\nsyndromes also need to be considered (Bush et al., 2018).\nThe evaluation of delirium may require laboratory testing,\nimaging, and less commonly electroencephalography or lumbar\npuncture. The extent of the evaluation should be informed by the\npatient’s goals of care and preferences, prior function and disease\ntrajectory, potential reversibility of the precipitant(s), and potential adverse impacts of the treatment options (Leonard et al., 2008a;\nBush et al., 2018).\n\nDifferential diagnosis of delirium\nDelirium must be distinguished from psychiatric disorders,\nincluding depression, mania, psychosis, and dementia (Breitbart\nand Alici, 2008). The hypoactive subtype often is initially misdiagnosed as depression. In distinguishing delirium from depression,\nparticularly in the context of advanced disease, an evaluation of the\nonset and temporal sequencing of depressive and cognitive symptoms is particularly helpful. The degree of cognitive impairment in\ndelirium is much more severe than in depression, usually with a\nmore abrupt onset. Additionally, disturbance in level of alertness,\nwhich is characteristic of delirium, is not a feature of depression\n(Breitbart, 2008).\nA manic episode may share some features of a hyperactive\nor mixed sub"},{"id": "13.5","title": "Bereavement","chapter": "13.5","section": "13","sectionLabel": "Psychiatric and Psychological","start": 773,"end": 784,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "CHAPTER 13.5 Bereavement\n\nSeveral physiological changes have been identified in neuroendocrine functioning (e.g. challenge studies such as the dexamethasone suppression test), immune indices (e.g. natural killer\ncell functioning), and sleep efficiency. These physiological changes\nsuggest that grief and depression lie on a biological continuum, and\nexplain the morbidity, both somatic and psychosocial, found in\nbereavement.\n\nThe clinical presentations of grief\nAs the family journey through palliative care, the clinical phases\nprogress from anticipatory grief through to the immediate news of\nthe death, to the stages of acute grief and, potentially for some, the\ncomplications of bereavement.\n\nAnticipatory grief\nWhen news of disease progression reaches the patient and family,\ngrief is initiated as they anticipate eventual death. However, not all\nthis grief is about the final loss, as many changes unfold with the\nillness and its treatment. Loss of health can be accompanied by loss\nof work, leisure activities, financial security, independence, sense of\ncertainty about life, and further physical impairments. The clinician\nis challenged to understand the meaning of the loss to each person\nand evaluate therein their grief response.\nAnticipatory grief generally draws the supportive family into a\nconfiguration of mutual comfort and greater closeness as the news\nof the illness and its proposed management is grappled with. For a\ntime, this perturbation advantages the care of the sick, until the pressures of daily life draw the family back towards their prior constellation. Movement back and forth occurs as periods of grief become\ninterspersed with phases of contentment and happiness. When the\nfamily is engaged in care of their ill member, their cohesion potentially increases as they share their fears, hopes, joy, and distress.\nIn contrast, difficulties emerge for other families who exhibit\nimpaired coping through protective avoidance, denial of the seriousness of the threat, anger, or withdrawal from involvement.\nSometimes family dysfunction is so glaring that clinicians are rapidly drawn into its snares. More commonly, however, subthreshold\nor mild depressive or anxiety disorders develop gradually as individuals struggle to adapt to unwelcome changes. While anticipatory grief was historically suggested to reduce postmortem grief,\nintense distress is now well recognized as a marker of risk for\ncomplicated grief.\nDuring this phase of anticipatory grief, clinicians can help the\nfamily by encouraging them to openly share their feelings as they\npay attention to the material needs of their dying family member\nor friend. Saying goodbye needs to be recognized as a process that\nevolves over time, with opportunities for reminiscence, celebration\nof the life and contribution of the dying person, expressions of gratitude, and completion of any unfinished business. These tasks have\nthe potential to generate meaningful and positive emotional aspects\nof what is otherwise a "},{"id": "14.1","title": "The Oncologist's Role in Palliative Care","chapter": "14.1","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 787,"end": 799,"pages": 13,"weight": 0.0104,"text": "CHAPTER 14.1 The oncologist’s role in delivering palliative care\n\nby every patient continuously; palliative care, particularly when delivered by specialists, focuses on the special needs of patients who\nare either incurable or who have a very low likelihood of cure. ‘End\nof life care’ or ‘terminal care’, when defined by the imminence of\ndying, is an aspect of palliative care and is emphasized by specialists in recognition of the magnifying intensity of physical, psychological, existential, spiritual, and family issues that may occur when\ndeath is near.\nDespite the ESMO definitions, the terms supportive care and\npalliative care remain inconsistently applied by specialists across\ncountries (Cherny, 2009). Although ESMO recently issued an updated policy statement proposing use of the term ‘patient-​centred\ncare’ (Jordan et al., 2018), this is unlikely to lead to a uniform adoption of terms. The need to refine and reconcile various definitions\nwill likely remain and should not obscure the fundamental reality\nthat patients with cancer, and their families, may express unmet\nphysical, psychosocial, or spiritual needs at any point during the\ncourse of the illness. These needs require specific interventions that\naim to reduce distress, enhance coping, or otherwise improve the\nindividual’s quality of life (Cherny, 2009).\n\nThe oncologist’s role in palliative care\nBoth the American Society of Clinical Oncology (ASCO) (Smith\nand Schnipper, 1998; Ferris et al., 2009; Smith et al., 2012; Ferrell\net al., 2017) and ESMO (Jordan et al., 2018) have policy statements outlining the responsibilities of medical oncologists in the\nintegration of oncology and palliative care. ASCO states that it is\nthe oncologist’s responsibility to provide care along a continuum\nthat starts at the moment of diagnosis and extends throughout the\ncourse of the illness. In addition to appropriate anticancer treatment, this includes symptom control and psychosocial support\nduring all phases of care, including the last phase of life.\n\nThe oncological management of advanced cancer\nDisease-​modifying treatments can potentially prolong survival and\nimprove comfort and function. As treatment options become more\nvaried, complex, and expensive with the advent of new targeted\ntherapies, immunotherapy, and biologically personalized therapies\n(Kolata, 2018), the balancing of benefits and burdens is becoming\nincreasingly challenging. Decision-​making must take into account\nthe goals of care, likelihood of benefit, likelihood of harm, and\nthe desires, beliefs, and understanding of the patient and family.\nOncologists must develop familiarity with key concepts of patient\nbenefit, quality of life, and risk/​benefit analysis. When the therapeutic index of antitumour therapies is diminished and the likelihood of benefit is outweighed by either the risk or the burden of\nthe treatments, it is the oncologist who must help steer the patients\nand the family to care that focuses on symptom management and\nother eff"},{"id": "14.2","title": "Disease-Modifying Therapies in Advanced Cancer","chapter": "14.2","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 800,"end": 807,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "802\n\nSECTION 14 Palliative care in cancer\n\nAntimetabolites\nAntimetabolites interfere with incorporation of nucleic acid bases\ninto the DNA molecule. Their activity is greatest in the S phase\nof the cell cycle. Examples are 5-​fluorouracil (5-​FU), capecitabin,\nfludarabine, methotrexate, pemetrexed, and gemcitabine.\n\nTable 14.2.1 Common toxicity profiles of commonly used\ncytotoxic drugs\nDrug\n\nToxicity\nBone marrow\n\n5-​fluoruracil\n\n++\n\nAlkylating drugs typically form linkages between strands of DNA,\nwhich prevent them from separating during the M phase of the\ncell cycle but they also have other biochemical effects and are cycle\nspecific rather than phase specific. Examples include cyclophosphamide, ifosfamide, chlorambucil, and melphalan. Other drugs\nwith alkylating activity include the platinum compounds, cisplatin,\ncarboplatin, and oxaliplatin.\n\nMethotrexate\n\n++\n\nGemcitabine\n\n+\n\nPemetrexed\n\n++\n\nAntitumour antibiotics act through a number of different mechanisms but typically interfere with the binding of base pair molecules\nand prevent the separation of the DNA strands during the M phase\nof the cell cycle. Some drugs are phase specific such as bleomycin\nand others are cycle specific such as doxorubicin and epirubicin.\nPlant alkaloids\nPlant alkaloids are derived from natural sources. They are phase\nspecific and are either mitotic spindle inhibitors such as vincristine,\nvinblastine, and the taxanes, paclitaxel and docetaxel, or the topoisomerase inhibitors such as topotecan, irinotecan, and etoposide.\nThe cytotoxic drugs affect normal tissues with cells in division\nsuch as blood cells, the gastrointestinal tract, and skin and the degree of toxicity in normal tissues is the limiting factor in treatment\nwith cytotoxic drugs. Combinations of cytotoxic drugs with different toxicity profiles and sites of action have led to the development of more effective therapeutic regimens with less toxicity and\nalso led to the development of effective supportive care agents to\nameliorate the toxicity. While some cancer forms are not responsive to cytotoxic drugs at the start of treatment (primary resistance),\nothers lose the effect during treatment due to the selection of cancer\ncells that are not sensitive to the cytotoxic drugs (secondary resistance). In this case, other cytotoxic drugs may be tried in second-​\nline treatment if the performance status of the patient permits this\napproach.\n\nThe toxicity of cytotoxic drugs\nToxicity may be dose limiting for the use of cytotoxic drugs and\nbetter supportive care in counteracting the toxic effects has resulted\nin treatment with more effective chemotherapy regimens. The commonest toxicities arise from tissues that are under a constant state\nof regeneration such as the bone marrow, gastrointestinal tract, and\nskin, and will be referred to in the following sections (Table 14.2.1).\nBone marrow\nErythrocytes, neutrophiles, and platelets are produced by the\nhaemopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow and the dividing\nstem cells"},{"id": "14.3a","title": "Radiotherapy in Symptom Management: Principles","chapter": "14.3a","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 808,"end": 820,"pages": 13,"weight": 0.0104,"text": "810\n\nSECTION 14 Palliative care in cancer\n\nTable 14.3.2 Isotope use in brachytherapy\nTechnique\n\nIsotope\n\nSites\n\nIntracavitary\n\nIridium (Ir-​194)\nCobalt (Co-​60)\n\nIntrauterine\nIntravaginal\nEndo-​oesophageal\nEndobronchial\nEndorectal\n\nInterstitial\n\nIridium (Ir-​194)\nCobalt (Co-​60)\nIodine (I-​125)\nCaesium (Cs-​131)\n\nProstate\nBreast\nHead and neck\nAnal canal\nVulva/​vagina\n\nSurface (mould)\n\nIridium (Ir-​194)\nCobalt (Co-​60)\n\nSkin\nPenis\n\nusing techniques such as sandbags, or for more complex treatments, a plastic shell using an individualized face mask may be\nnecessary.\n• Treatment volume localization: superficial lesions which are visible or palpable can be easily defined on clinical examination\nbut deep-​seated tumours require radiographic localization. This\nwill usually be from a computed tomography (CT) scan taken in\nthe position in which the patient will be treated. This enables accurate three-​dimensional reproduction of the anatomical region\nof interest ensuring not only clear definition of the treatment\nvolume but also the surrounding normal tissues.\n• Dosimetric planning: once the volume has been defined, then the\nmeans of treatment delivery is determined. For simple treatments,\nsuch as those to bone metastases, a single beam or two opposing\nbeams to treat a block of tissue will be all that is required. For\ninternal volumes, more complex, three-​or four-​field arrangements may be optimal. Certain situations, such as tumour sites\nclose to the spinal cord, retreatments close to critical organs, and\nthe treatment of oligometastases (fewer than three metastases)\nwhen higher doses may be considered, will require more complex\nplanning which may employ intensity-​modulated or stereotactic\ntechniques.\n• Verification: the defined beam arrangement will be checked on\nthe treatment machine using the megavoltage treatment beam or,\non modern linear accelerators, integrated kilovoltage CT imaging.\nWith simple superficial fields, clinical measurement and observation are adequate. Accurate documentation of the beam position\nwith indelible marking of defined skin entry points on the patient\nwill facilitate this and ensure accurate day-​to-​day reproducibility\nwhere more than one fraction is to be given.\nA linear accelerator produces high-​energy radiation at a rate of\naround 1 Gy per minute which means that most treatments, even\nusing large single fractions in the palliative setting will last for only\na few minutes. There are no accompanying symptoms during radiation exposure provided the patient is comfortable at the outset.\nIt is important to facilitate patient compliance with the procedure\nto ensure that they can remain still in the required position.\nUnfortunately, some of the constraints of accurate radiation delivery may impinge upon this, for example, the need to immobilize\nthe patient in a fixed position, the use of hard wooden flat couches,\nand the need for staff to leave the patient isolated while radiation\ndelivery is taking place. The judicious admin"},{"id": "14.3b","title": "Radiotherapy in Symptom Management: Clinical Applications","chapter": "14.3b","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 821,"end": 828,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 14.3 Radiotherapy in symptom management\n\ntumours such as Ewing’s sarcoma or Wilms’ tumour. In general,\nhowever, chemotherapy or hormone therapy is the preferred treatment in this setting and only when this has failed should palliative\nirradiation be explored.\nThere is no proven advantage in terms of survival for treating the\nasymptomatic patient with inoperable lung cancer but there is evidence that tumours greater than 10 cm in diameter, whether primary or metastatic, carry a significant risk of haemorrhage and it\nhas been suggested that such lesions should receive prophylactic\ntreatment.\n\nHaematuria\nHaematuria may be related to bleeding from primary or metastatic\ndisease at any site along the urinary tract from the renal pelvis to\nthe urethra. Thus, before embarking upon palliative treatment,\ncareful localization of the site of bleeding including CT urography\nis required. Haematuria in patients with advanced cancer is usually\ncaused by bleeding from a bladder tumour, which may be primary\nor secondary to local infiltration of an advanced rectal or uterine\ncarcinoma, advanced renal cell carcinoma, or urethral infiltration\nby carcinoma of the prostate. Other causes that may be relevant to\nthe cancer patient are infective cystitis, chemical cystitis associated\nwith certain chemotherapy agents such as cyclophosphamide or\nifosfamide, bladder telangiectasia as a late change following high-​\ndose radiotherapy to the bladder (or adjacent pelvic organs), or as\na rare manifestation of thrombocytopenia or a blood coagulation\ndefect.\nThe main role of radiotherapy in this setting is to achieve haemostasis in patients with inoperable or recurrent tumours. Haematuria\nmay settle with conservative measures, such as bladder irrigation,\nadministration of antifibrinolytic drugs, such as tranexamic acid,\nand cystoscopic diathermy. Where this fails, modest doses of irradiation delivered to a small volume encompassing the site of haemorrhage will often be successful.\nIn advanced muscle invasive bladder cancer, a large randomized\ntrial comparing 35 Gy in 10 fractions with 21 Gy given in 3 fractions on alternate days over 1 week has shown equivalent symptomatic improvement of bladder-​related symptoms with no excess\ntoxicity from the shorter 21 Gy schedule (Duchesne et al., 2000).\nHaematuria was improved in 50% of patients at completion of treatment and 63% at 3 months after treatment. Careful localization of\nbladder tumours is important with CT planning. The same doses\nand techniques can be used for prostatic cancer causing haemorrhage from urethral or bladder base infiltration. In poor performance status patients, single doses of 8–​10 Gy may be equally effective\nand 17 Gy in 2 fractions has also been reported as a useful schedule\nin this setting, with a 59% response rate for haematuria (Srinivasan\net al., 1994).\nAs with other sites, haematuria may be the presentation of a potentially curable primary bladder or prostatic carcinoma, and full\nassessment of the p"},{"id": "14.4","title": "Surgery in Palliative Cancer Care","chapter": "14.4","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 829,"end": 838,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 14.4 The role of general surgery in the palliative care of patients with cancer\n\nImaging extent\nof disease\n\nFuture treatment options\nRecent chemotherapy\n\nNutritional status\n\nPatient functional\n& performance\nstatus\n\nObstruction site:\ngoo, sbo, Ibo\nPalliative surgery for\nbowel obstruction\n\nPrognosis\n\nPatient preference\n\u001f Risks/benefits\n\u001f Goals\n\nObstruction cause:\nadhesions, tumor,\nunknown\n\nSurgeon preference\n\u001f Risks/benefits\n\u001f Goals\n\nFig. 14.4.1 Multifaceted approach to surgical decision-​making\nReproduced courtesy of The University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center. Copyright © 2017 The University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center.\n\ncurrent functional status. Potential contraindications for surgery\nin patients with incurable cancer and MBO include ascites, carcinomatosis, and particularly the combination of ascites and carcinomatosis, multiple obstructions, or a palpable intra-​abdominal\nmass (Ripamonti, 1994; Blair et al., 2001).\nEndoscopic approaches for malignant bowel obstruction\nEndoscopic procedures are suited for patients who are poor operative candidates or who decline an open operative intervention. The\nmajor approaches include stenting and percutaneous endoscopic\ngastrostomy tube placement.\nEndoscopic stent placement may obviate the need for an intestinal stoma. While less durable for relief of obstruction, they are\noften more consistent with the patient’s goals of care. Stenting may\ninclude procedures to initially canalize the lumen (e.g. laser or balloon dilatation).\nPercutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy tubes are generally well-​\ntolerated ‘venting’ procedures that can alleviate symptoms of\nintractable vomiting and nausea for upper gastrointestinal obstructions and allow for discharge to home, typically with hospice care\n(Campagnutta and Cannizzaro, 2000; Zucchi et al., 2016). A study\nfrom the US MD Anderson Cancer Center, Texas, found that percutaneous gastrostomy tubes were utilized for palliation in 23% of\nsmall bowel obstructions in patients with advanced malignancy\n(Badgwell et al., 2011). In combination with other medical techniques, both open and percutaneous gastrostomy offers the possibility of intermittent oral liquid intake.\nOutcomes of malignant bowel obstruction\nAlthough it is recognized that improvement in QoL after surgery\nis variable (42–​85%) (Feuer et al., 1999; Miner et al., 2002), there\nis no consistent parameter used to determine this clinical outcome; operations may offer an advantage of an increased survival.\nSurgical risks must be carefully considered prior to an operation,\n\nas morbidity (42%) (Makela et al., 1991) and mortality (5–​32%)\n(Makela et al., 1991; Feuer et al., 1999; Legendre et al., 2001) are\ncommon, and the re-​obstruction rate is high (10–​50%) (Feuer et al.,\n1999; Miner et al., 2003).\nEndoluminal wall stents have a high success rate for relief of\nsymptoms (64–​100%) in complete and incomplete colorectal obstructions (Harris et al., 2001), and in over 70% of upper intestinal malignant obs"},{"id": "14.5","title": "Orthopaedic Surgery in Palliation of Cancer","chapter": "14.5","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 839,"end": 848,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 14.5 Orthopaedic surgery in the palliation of cancer\n\nshould encourage surgeons to use more durable reconstructions\n(Gutowski et al., 2019).\nPain management is always a top priority to improve patient\nfunction and quality of life. Bone pain can result from local environment changes caused by the tumour itself, resulting in abnormal\nstimulation of afferent nerve fibres, or it can be associated with the\nmechanical weakening of bone. Therefore, surgical interventions\ncan reduce pain either by mechanical stabilization of a metastatic\nsite or by decreasing the tumour burden at a given site.\nSome metastatic bone lesions associated with primary breast\ncancer or lymphoma are responsive to systemic therapy. Monitoring\nof bone lesions and protected weight bearing should always be considered when administering systemic therapy. The ultimate goal of\nalmost all orthopaedic interventions in patients with metastatic disease is immediate weight bearing as tolerated, which facilitates the\nquickest return to normal function.\n\n(a)\n\n(d)\n\nIndications for surgery\nThe most common indication for orthopaedic surgical interventions in patients with metastatic bone lesions is for treatment of\nimpending or existing pathological fractures. This allows efficient pain control, mechanical stability, and early mobilization\nwith subsequent restoration of function (Kinnane, 2007). Because\npathological fractures have a poor healing rate, surgical fixation is\nessential for providing long-​term stability to the area (Fig. 14.5.1).\nIn rare instances, resection of solitary metastases can be curative\n(Lin et al., 2007).\nPathological and osteoporotic fractures must be distinguished\nto determine the most effective treatment strategy in select populations. For example, in one population-​\nbased study, patients\nwith prostate cancer who were treated with luteinizing hormone-​\nreleasing hormone agonists had a 19% incidence of non-​pathological\n\n(b)\n\n(e)\n\n(c)\n\n(f)\n\nFig. 14.5.1 Examples of metastatic bone lesions and surgical fixation techniques. (a) A patient with metastatic prostate cancer who developed\nmultiple osteoblastic lesions of the pelvis and proximal femur. (b) Metastatic renal carcinoma of the right scapula, with involvement of the glenoid\nand entire scapula; (c) a titanium scapular replacement was used to reconstruct the area after resection of the native scapula. (d, e) A hemiarthroplasty\nwas performed on this 40-​year-​old female with metastatic breast cancer to the proximal femur. A cemented long-​stem component was used; note\nthat only one side of the joint was replaced with a large head that articulates with the native acetabulum. (f) A patient with metastatic breast cancer\ninvolving the proximal femur and acetabulum was treated with a total hip arthroplasty, including a Harrington reconstruction of the acetabulum. The\nlarge pins and surrounding cement provide support for the cup component of the arthroplasty.\nReproduced courtesy of John H. Healey, Memorial Sloan Lette"},{"id": "14.6","title": "Integrative Oncology in Palliative Medicine","chapter": "14.6","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 849,"end": 860,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "CHAPTER 14.6 Integrative oncology in palliative medicine\n\nIO services can help patients make their decisions based on an\nevidence-​based approach and open communication with the oncology and palliative HCPs.\nExpectations from integrative medicine should be focused on reducing symptoms and improving QoL, as opposed to ‘curing cancer’\n(Ben-​Arye et al., 2015). Patients and caregivers need to be directed\nto those therapies and activities which can help regain strength and\nempower them to take control of their lives, making the steps towards this goal on their own (Paul et al., 2013).\n\nCommunicating with patients on CAM use\nEffective communication with patients is key to any therapeutic\nprocess, with even more significant implications for oncology patients seeking non-​conventional treatments in an ‘alternative’ context of care. An antagonistic attitude to these therapies may be\ninterpreted by the patient as a lack of respect for their autonomy\nand health belief model. If instructed to avoid any and all alternative\ntherapies, some patients may feel that they need to choose between\nconventional or alternative treatment. This may have major consequences, especially in cases where delaying or refusing conventional\ntreatment may result in cure (Greenlee et al., 2016).\nDespite the importance of effective doctor–​patient communication on the use of non-​conventional medicine, a survey conducted by\nthe American Society for Clinical Oncology found that less than half\nof oncologists surveyed reported having initiated a discussion with\ntheir patients on the use of herbal and other dietary supplements.\nMany of the oncologists questioned identified a lack of knowledge on\nnon-​conventional medicine as a major barrier to such a discussion\n(Lee et al., 2014). In a study of oncology nurses, most respondents\nadmitted that they were unaware that their patients were using non-​\nconventional medicine in conjunction with conventional cancer care\n(Parker et al., 2013). The Clinical Oncology Society of Australia has\nissued a position statement encouraging HCPs to initiate an open discussion with their patients on this practice (Braun et al., 2014).\nThere are a number of steps which can help HCPs initiate a\nnon-​judgemental discussion with their patients on the use of non-​\nconventional medicine, especially herbal and other dietary supplements (Table 14.6.1). These should be part of a process which\nfacilitates trust through a respectful and non-​judgemental discussion, emphasizing patients’ rights in making their own decisions\nand acknowledging that they may have a different philosophy about\nhealthcare. Questions about the use of non-​conventional medicine\nshould be asked routinely, at the initial consultation and throughout\nsubsequent visits, even if the HCP is unfamiliar with the modalities\nbeing used.\nHCPs are advised to be active in talking to patients about non-​\nconventional medical practices, and not remain passive listeners.\nThe discussion should continue throughout"},{"id": "14.7","title": "Interventional Radiology in Palliation of Cancer","chapter": "14.7","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 861,"end": 871,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 14.7 Interventional radiology in the palliation of cancer\n\nmany decades the main long-​term treatment for malignant pleural\neffusions, a growing body of evidence supports the use of tunnelled\nlong-​term indwelling pleural catheters (Thomas et al., 2017).\nThese catheters are made of a soft silicone polyester cuff to promote fibrosis to the subcutaneous tissue and multiple side holes to\nenhance drainage. A valve in its hub is opened only when a dilator is\npassed through it. This prevents inadvertent entry of air or leakage\nof fluid. The drainage system consists of a vacuum bottle with a pre-​\nconnected tube that has a dilator at its end to pass into the hub of\nthe catheter. Drainage will typically take no longer than 15 minutes\nand should be performed at least every other day. In the outpatient\nsetting, this can be done by a visiting nurse, family members, or the\npatient.\n\nMalignant ascites\nThe accumulation of large volume ascites is a common occurrence for patients with intraperitoneal spread of tumour. These\npatients have a poor prognosis, and it is one of the most common\ncause of readmission for patients with terminal cancer. Patients\noften experience symptoms of abdominal pressure, shortness of\nbreath, nausea, early satiety, and limited mobility because of the\nmass effect of the fluid. Management of symptoms is palliative and\nmethods used include percutaneous drainage, diuretics, shunt\nplacement, and intraperitoneal drug therapy. Paracentesis is not\nonly the most common treatment method used by physicians, but\nalso the most effective at relieving symptoms (Becker et al., 2006).\nUnfortunately, management of recurrent ascites with paracentesis requires frequent trips to the hospital and has greater risk of\ncomplications associated with multiple needle passes into the abdomen. There is an increasing number of published reports which\nshow that a 15.5 Fr tunnelled draining catheter, the PleurX® catheter, provides effective palliation with a complication rate similar\nto that for large volume paracentesis, while obviating the need for\nfrequent trips to the hospital for repeated percutaneous drainage\n(Qu et al., 2016).\n\nDilatation/​stenting techniques\nThese techniques are employed for the treatment of a variety of malignant strictures and occlusions in many systems, including the\ngastrointestinal tract, the respiratory system, and the renal and biliary tracts (as already discussed).\n\nGastrointestinal tract\nOesophagus\nThe aim of palliation in patients with inoperable oesophageal cancer\nis to relieve dysphagia with minimal morbidity and mortality, and\nthus improve quality of life. The use of a self-​expanding metal stent\nis a well-​established modality for palliation of dysphagia in such\npatients (Sabharwal et al., 2005). Placement of the stent can be\nachieved under fluoroscopic (Fig. 14.7.2) or endoscopic guidance,\nor both. The procedure is relatively straightforward with negligible\nmortality and low morbidity. Advantages of radiological placeme"},{"id": "14.8","title": "Neurological Problems in Advanced Cancer","chapter": "14.8","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 872,"end": 889,"pages": 18,"weight": 0.0144,"text": "874\n\nSECTION 14 Palliative care in cancer\n\nand disrupting cerebrovascular autoregulation. The consequences\nof reduced CPP are cerebral ischaemia, and dilatation of cerebral\nvessels, with further increase of ICP. Since hypovolaemia reduces\narterial pressure and therefore CPP, the patient with elevated ICP\ndoes not require fluid restriction, but should be kept euvolaemic\nwith adequate fluid intake.\nInterventions that assist in maintaining CPP and reducing\nvasogenic oedema are varied. Consideration of these interventions\ndepends on the goals of care. Aggressive management strategies,\nsuch as assisted ventilation to lower the partial pressure of carbon\ndioxide, may not be considered when the goals are purely palliative.\nPositioning\nA neutral head position should be adopted, with the head at least 30\ndegrees above the heart to facilitate venous drainage from the head.\nInfusion of hypertonic solutions\nRapid reduction of ICP and cerebral oedema with hypertonic solutions has been utilized since 1925. Nowadays, used hyperosmolar\nsolutions are mannitol, and hypertonic saline (Ropper, 2012).\nHyperosmolar solutions are only effective if the blood–​brain barrier\nis intact; action is by removal of water from normal brain parenchyma, as ICP is lowered in proportion to the volume of undamaged brain. There is little value on oedema around a lesion where\nthe blood–​brain barrier is damaged. In addition, such solutions do\nnot have a role in asymptomatic cerebral oedema.\nMannitol is the most commonly used agent (Ropper, 2012). Its activity is based initially on an increase in blood flow, leading to improved\ncerebral perfusion. Only later does it create an osmolar gradient between blood and brain and extract water from the cerebral compartment. Usually more water than sodium is eliminated, resulting in\nhypovolaemia and hyponatraemia. There is no interaction between\nmannitol and glucose metabolism. There are a number of other actions associated with the therapeutic effect of mannitol, including a\ndiuretic effect, an increase in red cell deformability, and a rapid reduction of the diameter of arterioles and small veins of the brain surface. Mannitol is not metabolized and is excreted by the kidneys; with\nmoderate reduction of glomerular filtration, it can accumulate in the\ncentral compartment. Although it can be administered orally, bioavailability is very poor and the usual approach is intravenous (IV)\ninfusion, aiming to achieve concentrations higher than 5 mmol/​L,\nwhich are active osmotically and persist for 4–​6 hours. Mannitol 18%\nor 20% (18–​20 g/​100 mL) solutions are used and the suggested dose\nregimen for both adults and children is 1 g/​kg delivered over 15–​30\nminutes immediately, then 0.25 g/​kg every 6 or 8 hours (e.g. 100 mL\n18% solution every 6–​8 hours per 70 kg patient weight). The regimen\ncan vary according to the severity of symptoms and the presence of\nacute and symptomatic brain herniation. Daily doses should never\nbe higher than 150–​200 g/​day. "},{"id": "14.9","title": "Endocrine and Metabolic Complications of Cancer","chapter": "14.9","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 890,"end": 903,"pages": 14,"weight": 0.0112,"text": "892\n\nSECTION 14 Palliative care in cancer\n\nIntravenous fluids\n\nCorticosteroids\n\nFor patients with mild hypercalcaemia who are asymptomatic,\nrehydration by increasing oral fluid intake to 3–​4 L per day is recommended. Avoiding prolonged periods of immobility is also recommended, when possible, to avoid exacerbating hypercalcaemia.\nFor patients with symptomatic hypercalcaemia or severe\nhypercalcaemia, most often defined as a serum calcium concentration of greater than 3.00 mmol/​L, intravenous rehydration is an essential first step of acute therapy. It is recommended to commence\n4–​6 L of 0.9% saline in the first 24 hours with careful monitoring of\nvolume status to avoid fluid overload (Sternlicht and Glezerman,\n2015). In practice, however, strict monitoring of volume status is\noften not achievable in the hospice setting and most palliative care\nguidelines recommend the administration of 1–​3 L of fluid in the\nfirst 24 hours depending on risk of fluid overload and degree of\ndehydration (Scottish Intercollegiate Guidelines Network, 2016).\nLoop diuretics are now only recommended if the patient develops\nclinical symptoms or signs of volume overload and not as a calcium-​\nlowering therapy.\n\nGlucocorticoids have been widely used in cancer-​related hyper­\ncalcaemia and rapidly inhibit osteoclastic bone resorption in vitro,\nas well as reducing calcium absorption from the gut. However, their\nlimited clinical benefit is chiefly confined to tumours that respond\nto the cytostatic effects of steroids, such as myeloma, lymphoma,\nleukaemia, and, occasionally, breast cancer when hypercalcaemia\noccurs as a flare effect caused by endocrine therapy. Thus, their role\nin severe hypercalcaemia is limited to haematological malignancies\nand oral prednisolone 40–​100 mg/​day is usually effective in these\ncircumstances, although it may take 4–​10 days to lower the serum\ncalcium.\n\nBisphosphonates\nBisphosphonates are synthetic pyrophosphate analogues. They reduce bone resorption by binding hydroxyapatite crystals with a\nhigh affinity, with resultant inhibition of hydroxyapatite breakdown and promotion of osteoclast apoptosis (Drake et al., 2008). In\nhypercalcaemia of malignancy, bisphosphonates cause a gradual fall\nin serum calcium over a few days. They do not alter PTHrP levels,\nrenal calcium reabsorption, RANKL, or OPG levels and so they may\nfail to control humoral hypercalcaemia of malignancy without bone\nmetastases (Walls et al., 1994; Zojer et al., 2005).\nThe most commonly prescribed bisphosphonate is pamidronate,\nadministered as a single infusion of 30–​\n90 mg, depending on\nserum calcium, and administered at a rate of 20 mg/​h. Zoledronate\n(zoledronic acid) is an alternative bisphosphonate, which is administered as an infusion at a dose of 4 mg over 15 minutes. It corrects hypercalcaemia faster and for longer than pamidronate (Major\net al., 2001). The differences between the two drugs are not marked,\nhowever, and the choice is based largely on cost and convenience.\nDo"},{"id": "14.10","title": "Malignant Bowel Obstruction","chapter": "14.10","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 904,"end": 917,"pages": 14,"weight": 0.0112,"text": "906\n\nSECTION 14 Palliative care in cancer\n\ndecrease/​stop. Rectal examination might reveal an empty rectum or\nobstructing mass.\nGoals of care and patient preferences must be established. The lack\nof consistent or confirmed clinically meaningful patient-​relevant\noutcome measures for MBO has led to varied evaluation of MBO\nacross clinical trials, with inconsistent recommendations in clinical\nguidelines (https://bmjopen.bmj.com/content/10/6/e039154.long).\nTherefore, an individualized approach is needed.\nThe assessment of patients with suspected MBO should include:\n• Other causes of nausea, vomiting (see Chapter 8.2), and constipation (see Chapter 8.3)\n• Bowel movements and the presence of overflow diarrhoea\n• Nutritional and hydration status\n• Drug dosages and frequencies\n• The presence of abdominal faecal masses, distension of the whole\nabdomen or only above the obstruction, ascites, and painful sites\n• The presence of faeces in the rectal ampulla (rectal examination)\n• Metabolic abnormalities.\n\nRadiological investigation\nIntestinal obstruction is suspected on clinical grounds and confirmed, if appropriate, with diagnostic imaging to verify the site(s),\nseverity, likely cause of obstruction, and any complications. Plain upright or supine abdominal radiographs demonstrate air–​fluid levels\nwith dilated loops of bowel. Abdomen/​pelvis computed tomography\n(CT) scanning with intravenous contrast is recommended in small\nbowel obstruction. Oral contrast is usually not given as patients are\nnauseated and vomiting risks aspiration, and it rarely shows the\nbowel proximal to the obstruction (Paulson and Thompson, 2015).\nIn large bowel obstruction, abdomen/​pelvis CT scanning helps diagnose bowel perforation or ischaemia (Jaffe and Thompson, 2015).\nUsually CT scans are reserved for patients who are well enough to\nundergo interventions or surgery (Tuca et al., 2012).\n\nTable 14.10.3 shows the possible radiological investigations that\nmight be performed in patients with symptoms and signs of bowel\nobstruction (Maglinte et al., 1996; Suri et al., 1999; Beall et al., 2002;\nLow et al., 2003; de Bree et al., 2004; Mallo et al., 2005; Filippone\net al., 2007; Thompson et al., 2007; Branco et al., 2010; Wu et al.,\n2013). These should only be used if they will inform clinical decisions. Fig. 14.10.1 shows an algorithm for the MDT management of\npatients with MBO.\n\nManagement of malignant bowel obstruction\nThe treatment of MBO needs to be individualized and depends\non the location of the obstruction, the clinical stage of the cancer,\nthe patient’s general health, and recent changes in functional\nstatus, wishes, and prognosis. An MDT often makes the decision.\nPhysicians are guided by the clinical situation, patient preferences,\ngoals of care, response to therapy, medication availability, and local\npractice/​guidelines.\nIn patients with a single-level obstruction and good functional\nstatus, surgical intervention including bowel resection, stoma formation, or endoscopic ste"},{"id": "14.11","title": "Palliative Care in Head and Neck Cancers","chapter": "14.11","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 918,"end": 926,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "920\n\nSECTION 14 Palliative care in cancer\n\nthe goal of providing a better quality of life is obtained. When\napproached in this manner, however, palliative surgery can help\nassist with a number of different aspects of care, including the\nfollowing:\n• Tumour debulking—​\nthis may be used to relieve obstructive\nsymptoms using a carbon dioxide laser, photodynamic therapy\n(using a systemic photosensitizer and an argon dye-​pumped\nlaser), or cryosurgery (using a process of rapid freezing); alternatively, debulking may aid as a temporary measure to help with the\nphysical appearance of a fungating lesion.\n• Fistula closure—​such as an orocutaneous or pharyngocutaneous\nfistula; the procedure would involve opening the tract and\ndebriding necrotic tissue before instituting local wound care.\n• Maintaining airway patency—​by creating a surgical tracheostomy.\n• Protection of the sclera by conducting a lateral tarsorrhaphy\nwhere simple measures such as eye patches have failed—​this\nhelps prevent drying out of the sclera which in turn can lead to\ncorneal ulceration, pain, and ultimately blindness if untreated\n(Roland and Bradley, 2014).\nOther situations where surgery may have a role are discussed within\nthe context of the ‘Common symptoms’ section of this chapter.\n\nRole of chemotherapy and targeted therapies\nOver the last decade, there have been developments in terms of the\nmultimodality therapy given with radiotherapy (chemotherapy regimens or specific targeted therapies). For recurrent or metastatic\ndisease, cytotoxic chemotherapy has been the standard therapeutic\noption. Being treated with single-​agent chemotherapy, however,\nhas had limited success with median survival ranging from 6 to\n10 months (Economopoulou et al., 2016). Combination therapies for recurrent or metastatic disease now tend to include regimens involving platinum-​based agents (cis-​platin, carbo-​platin),\n5-​fluorouracil (5-​FU), and taxanes (docetaxel, paclitaxel). An increased understanding about the role of the immune system has\nled to the development of a range of novel agents. Monoclonal\nantibodies, such as cetuximab which targets an epidermal growth\nfactor receptor, have shown some modest improvements in survival (Vermorken et al., 2008). Cetuximab tends to be used in\ncombination with platinum and 5-​FU for those with a good performance status and who are sufficiently fit to receive this regimen\n(Mehanna et al., 2016). Ongoing clinical trials have led to a better\nunderstanding of the mechanisms between head and neck cancer\nand immune resistance. Further development of ‘immune checkpoint inhibitors’ (drugs which block specific proteins made by certain immune system cells and cancer cells and can prevent T cells\nfrom killing cancer cells) presents an area for ongoing research\nand the potential for more novel strategies (Economopoulou\net al., 2016). Nivolumab, a monoclonal antibody which binds to\nthe programmed death-​1 (PD-​1) receptor, showed evidence of\nsurvival benefits (median overal"},{"id": "14.12","title": "Haematological Malignancies in Palliative Care","chapter": "14.12","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 927,"end": 936,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "CHAPTER 14.12 Palliative care issues in populations with haematological malignancies\n\nover many years may enter a terminal stage, punctuated by markedly decreased responsiveness to treatment, progressive decline,\nand steady disease progression. Furthermore, some patients unfortunately also suffer a ‘transformation’ of their disease, wherein it becomes more aggressive, and appears more like a large cell lymphoma\nunder the microscope. Transformed lymphoma generally confers a\npoor prognosis.\n\ntwo-​or three-​drug regimens. Given the cumulative toxicity conferred by these therapies, and the length of time that many MM patients live today, there are many opportunities for IPC to collaborate\nwith HM specialists to improve patients’ experiences of illness with\nMM. Novel approaches to MM management include the development of CAR T-​cell therapies, which appear promising, but are not\nyet approved at the time of this writing.\n\nSpecial considerations\nWith the more recent emergence of targeted therapies, and more\nrecently chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T-​cell immunotherapy,\nthere is growing uncertainty about patients’ prognoses in many\ncases of lymphoma. For example, response rates in CAR T-​cell therapies range from 50% to 80%, with durable responses seen in over\n40–​50% of patients in recent studies. These novel treatments provide hope for a good outcome in historically poor-​prognosis settings, for aggressive and indolent lymphomas alike, but it is difficult\nto predict which patients are likely to benefit. PC specialists can play\nan important role in helping patients manage and cope with this\nuncertainty.\n\nMultiple myeloma\nMM is a cancer of the plasma cell, a mature type of B cell (a white\nblood cell). Plasma cells make antibodies, and the accumulation\nof these clonal antibodies (protein) causes many of the signs and\nsymptoms of MM. Significant advances in MM have ushered in an\nera where most patients do not receive chemotherapy initially, but\ninstead receive immunomodulatory agents, usually in combination\nwith steroids.\nThe most common three-​drug regimens in use today confer\nresponse rates approaching 100%, but toxicities can be significant, including frequent and progressive peripheral neuropathy,\ncytopenias, steroid-​associated side effects, and risk of viral reactivation or thrombosis. However, the overall prognosis has improved\nmarkedly in MM. Today, a patient with ‘standard risk’ myeloma\n(without any ‘high-​risk’ abnormality) probably has a median overall\nsurvival of about 5–​10 years.\nSome clinicians utilize the ‘international staging system’ (ISS),\nwhich stratifies patients into three prognostic groups on the basis\nof serum albumin, beta-​2 microglobulin, and in its most recent version, also the serum lactate dehydrogenase. Median overall survival\nin ISS stage 3 myeloma is about 43 months, whereas median overall\nsurvival has not even been reached in ISS stage 1 disease per published estimates. Other risk stratification schemas incorporate molecu"},{"id": "14.13","title": "Anaemia, Cytopenias, and Thrombosis","chapter": "14.13","section": "14","sectionLabel": "Palliative Care in Cancer","start": 937,"end": 947,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 14.13 Anaemia, cytopenias, and thrombosis in palliative medicine\n\nare incurable, it is usually not clinically necessary (Agarwal and\nPrchal, 2010).\nMild to moderate marrow infiltration is frequently asymptomatic\nwith minimal blood count changes. With more significant marrow\ninvolvement, anaemia can be more severe and accompanied by an\nelevated white blood cell count. Platelets can be low, normal, or elevated. Treatment is focused at managing the underlying disease and\nsymptom control.\nPatients with haematological malignancies (Franchini et al.,\n2013) and bone marrow failure disorders such as myelodysplastic\nsyndrome (Foran and Shammo, 2012) have diseased marrows that\nare unable to produce adequate blood cells, often resulting in pancytopenia. While thrombocytopenia can result in easy bruising, it\nis unlikely to result in spontaneous bleeding at a platelet count of\nmore than 20 × 109 or in fatal intracranial haemorrhage at a platelet\ncount of more than 5 × 109 (Franchini et al., 2013).\n\nNeutropenia\nBackground\nNeutropenia in the palliative setting is most commonly due to bone\nmarrow failure from myelosuppressive chemotherapy, disease infiltration of the bone marrow, or from intrinsic bone marrow failure.\nThe definition of neutropenia is defined as an absolute neutrophil\ncount (ANC) less than 1500 cells/​microlitre with severe neutropenia\nbeing an ANC less than 500 cells/​microlitre. Patients with neutropenia are at high risk of developing severe bacterial and fungal infections. The Infectious Diseases Society of America defines fevers\nin neutropenic patients as a single oral temperature of greater than\n38.3°C or a sustained temperature of greater than 38.0°C for more\nthan 1 hour (Freifeld et al., 2011).\nFebrile neutropenia\nPatients at highest risk of severe febrile neutropenia are those with\nan ANC less than 500 cells/​microlitre for more than 7 days. Those\nwith active comorbidities or significant hepatic or renal dysfunction\nare also considered to be high risk of severe bacterial infections.\nPatients with prolonged neutropenia with an ANC less than or\nequal to 100 cells/​microlitre for more than 7 days should be considered for fluoroquinolone prophylaxis with levofloxacin or\nciprofloxacin. In patients with fevers and neutropenia, the decision\nabout management is dependent on the patient’s values and disease\nstage. If life prolongation is deemed appropriate, then a discussion\nabout the extent of investigation and management should be discussed on a per case basis.\nStandard investigations for febrile neutropenia include complete\nblood cell count with differential leucocyte count and platelet count,\nserum electrolytes, hepatic enzymes, total bilirubin, and creatinine.\nAt least two sets of blood cultures are recommended, one from each\nlumen of a central venous catheter and one from a peripheral vein.\nCultures from other sites should be taken as appropriate and a chest\nradiograph should be performed if respiratory findings are present.\nHigh-​ri"},{"id": "15.1","title": "HIV/AIDS and Palliative Care","chapter": "15.1","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 949,"end": 963,"pages": 15,"weight": 0.012,"text": "CHAPTER 15.1 HIV/AIDS\n\nAging Population\n\nHIV infection\n\nStressors\n\nCo-Morbidities\n\nPsychosocial Issues\n\nDrug Toxicity\n\nFig. 15.1.2 Palliative care for HIV/​AIDs as a complex, multifactorial chronic disease in an ageing population.\n\nPulmonary disease\nHIV-​\ninfected patients develop numerous pulmonary complications. Some opportunistic infections, such as Pneumocystis jirovecii\npneumonia, are almost always seen only in the setting of low CD4\ncounts (generally <200 cells/​mm3); others, such as pneumococcal\npneumonia (Turett et al., 2001) and tuberculosis (Selwyn et al.,\n1989), are common and may be seen at higher CD4 counts as well\n(generally <400 cells/​mm3). A relatively high prevalence of chronic\nobstructive pulmonary disease (Madeddu et al., 2013), pulmonary\nhypertension (Isasti et al., 2013), and lung cancer (Dubrow et al.,\n2012) in the current era may be due to risk factors such as smoking\nor to the HIV infection itself. Pulmonary comorbidities may cause\nmore symptoms than the infection itself and symptom management\nshould mirror other populations.\n\nLiver disease\nHIV infection is associated with increased rates of non-​alcoholic\nfatty liver disease and co-​infection with hepatitis C virus (HCV).\nNon-​alcoholic fatty liver disease may be due to the infection itself or\nto ART-​related lipodystrophy (Vallet-​Pichard, 2012). Co-​infection\n\nwith HCV affects between 4 and 5 million people worldwide and\nis associated with high rates of progressive liver disease and other\ncomplications. Patients with HCV co-​infection have relatively rapid\nprogression to fibrosis, high HCV viral load, and high rates of viral\npersistence, end-​stage liver disease, and death (Operskalski and\nKovacs, 2011). They also experience relatively high rates of peripheral neuropathy; HIV-​related kidney disease; insulin resistance,\nglucose intolerance, and diabetes; neurocognitive impairment; abdominal pain; and bleeding risk (Braitstein et al., 2005; Aronow\net al., 2008; Wyatt et al., 2008; Butt et al., 2009).\n\nRenal disease\nHIV-​associated nephropathy, immune complex kidney disease,\nand thrombotic microangiopathy usually occur in those who are\ndiagnosed late or who are not receiving treatment. Drug-​related\nnephrotoxicity also occurs and has been associated with most ART\nclasses, but particularly the NRTI tenofovir—​a first-​line NRTI (de\nSilva et al., 2007; Schmid et al., 2007). Serious renal events, such\nas renal failure and Fanconi syndrome, have been reported in\n0.5% of patients taking tenofovir, and 2.2% of patients experience\n\n951\n\n952\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nTable 15.1.1 Classes of antiretrovirals, recommended first-​line regimens, and common antiretroviral toxicities\nDrugs\n\nToxicities\n\nNucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NRTIs)\nStavudine, (d4T)\n\nPeripheral neuropathy, lipoatrophy, pancreatitis, lactic acidosis, hepatic steatosis\n\nDidanosine (ddI)\n\nPancreatitis, peripheral neuropathy, nausea/​vomiting\n\nZidovudine (AZT)\n\nAnaemi"},{"id": "15.2","title": "Advanced Diseases of the Lung","chapter": "15.2","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 964,"end": 975,"pages": 12,"weight": 0.0096,"text": "966\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nactive, through enjoyable, sustainable activities (e.g. gardening or\ndog walking) is important.\nPulmonary rehabilitation\nPulmonary rehabilitation aims to improve the physical and psychological condition of patients with COPD and to promote\nlong-​term adherence to health-​enhancing behaviours. Supervised\nindividualized exercise training is the cornerstone; other elements include self-​management education, behaviour change, nutritional intervention, and psychosocial support (Spruit et al.,\n2013). Patients usually attend two supervised group sessions\neach week for 6–​8 weeks, while also undertaking a home exercise\nprogramme.\nPulmonary rehabilitation is associated with reduced symptoms,\nexacerbations, and anxiety and depression, together with improved\nhealth-​related quality of life, muscle function, and exercise capacity\n(Bolton et al., 2013; Moore et al., 2016; Alison et al., 2017). While\nthe benefits are greatest for patients with moderate to severe disease,\nthese patients often struggle to attend programmes due to severe\nbreathlessness. Home pulmonary rehabilitation programmes are\ntherefore an alternative (Holland et al., 2017).\nSupport groups\nWhile support groups have not been formally evaluated, they offer\nCOPD patients and their carers emotional support, social interaction, and opportunities to gain new knowledge and learn coping\nstrategies. Pulmonary rehabilitation provides a good opportunity to\ninitiate support group attendance.\nOxygen therapy\nAlthough oxygen therapy may be required to treat acute hypoxaemia, excessive oxygen can worsen hypercapnia. Therefore, low\nflow rates or fixed delivery devices should be used, aiming to keep\noxygen saturations between 88% and 92%.\nHypoxaemia is only one of the mechanisms causing breathlessness and oxygen therapy will not reduce day-​to-​day breathlessness\nif hypoxaemia is not the cause. Oxygen therapy is potentially expensive, burdensome, and associated with risks (falls, burns, and\nfires), restricted activities, and psychological dependence. It should\nbe prescribed only for those with evidence of benefit. Long-​term\noxygen therapy (LTOT) for at least 15 hours/​day reduces mortality\nin COPD patients with severe respiratory failure (Cranston et al.,\n2005) and is appropriate for stable, non-​smoking patients with severe resting hypoxaemia (PaO2 <55 mmHg or 7.3 kPa) or less severe\nhypoxaemia (PaO2 55–​60 mmHg or 7.3–​8 kPa) and coexisting pulmonary hypertension, congestive cardiac failure, or polycythaemia\n(haematocrit >55%). For most patients, oxygen is titrated to keep\noxygen saturation at 90% or greater.\nIn patients with only moderate resting hypoxaemia and\nexercise-​induced desaturation, long-​term oxygen therapy does\nnot alter mortality, time to first hospitalization, or quality of life\n(Long-​\nTerm Oxygen Treatment Trial Research Group, 2016).\nSimilarly, long-​term oxygen therapy does not improve breathlessness experienced during dail"},{"id": "15.3","title": "Advanced Heart Disease","chapter": "15.3","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 976,"end": 986,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "978\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nspecialist best able to help patients and collaborate effectively with\nother clinicians.\n\nDiuretics\n\nHF may manifest with fluid retention and/​or symptoms of low cardiac output, such as fatigue, breathlessness, and altered mentation.\nDrug therapies for heart failure with reduced\nFluid retention may cause oedema, abdominal fullness, early satiety,\nejection fraction\nnausea, and breathlessness due to pulmonary congestion. Diuretic\nThe cornerstone of treatment for HFrEF is neurohormonal blockade treatment to remove excess fluid is essential for symptom relief\nusing (1) an angiotensin-​\nconverting enzyme inhibitor (ACEI), (Yancy et al., 2013, 2018; Ponikowski et al., 2016). Thiazide diurangiotensin receptor blocker (ARB), or angiotensin receptor–​ etics may satisfactorily maintain euvolemia in mild cases of HF, but\nneprilysin inhibitor (ARNI); (2) a beta-​blocker with demonstrated loop diuretics such as furosemide cause more potent diuresis and\nefficacy for patients with HF; and (3) a mineralocorticoid antagonist typically are required as HF worsens (Yancy et al., 2013; Ponikowski\n(Table 15.3.3). These drugs typically slow the progression of cardiac et al., 2016; NHFA CSANZ Heart Failure Guidelines Working\ndysfunction and may facilitate improvement or recovery, as well as Group et al., 2018).\nreduce mortality and prevent hospitalization (Heart Failure Society\nDiuretics may be given orally, but gut oedema may impair bioof America et al., 2010; Yancy et al., 2013; Ponikowski et al., 2016). availability. The most commonly used loop diuretic, furosemide, is\nDiuretics also are indispensable because of their ability to reduce particularly affected by gut oedema, and if oral therapy is needed,\nfluid retention and congestion even though a placebo-​controlled alternative agents such as bumetanide or torsemide, or addition\ntrial testing their effect on mortality has never been performed and of a thiazide diuretic, may be necessary. In the hospital setting, an\nis unlikely to ever be undertaken (Yancy et al., 2013; Ponikowski intravenous loop diuretic usually is administered to ensure bioet al., 2016). Other medications, including digoxin, ivabradine, availability and promote a rapid onset. The practice of combining\ntolvaptan, and the vasodilator combination of hydralazine and classes of diuretics may be called sequential nephron blockade; it is\nlong-​acting nitrates, play a role in subgroups of HF patients (Yancy an option for the outpatient setting, effectively mobilizes fluid, but\net al., 2013; Ponikowski et al., 2016; Psotka and Teerlink, 2016).\nis associated with higher rates of hyponatraemia and hypokalaemia.\nAlthough neurohormonal antagonists are initiated for their Intravenous diuretic administration may be possible at home or in\nlife-​prolonging effect, they also alleviate symptoms, reduce hospi- the emergency department, and may help avoid hospitalization for\ntalizations, and improve funct"},{"id": "15.4","title": "Dementia","chapter": "15.4","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 987,"end": 995,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 15.4 Dementia\n\nperceived to have a life expectancy of less than 6 months, but 71%\ndied within that period (Mitchell et al., 2004). Perceiving dementia\nas a terminal illness can significantly influence decision-​making in\nadvanced dementia. One study found that a family’s perception of dementia as ‘a disease you can die from’ predicted higher patient comfort during the dying process (van der Steen et al., 2013). However,\nonly 43% of family members in this study perceived dementia as a\nterminal illness (van der Steen et al., 2013). Another recent study\nfound that patients with advanced dementia were less likely to have\ninterventions such as feeding tubes, hospital transfers, and parenteral therapy, when their proxy’s estimate of their life expectancy was\nshorter than 6 months (Loizeau et al., 2018).\nIn the US, patients insured by government insurance (Medicare\nor Medicaid) may receive hospice services, usually in the home or\nthe nursing home, if there is physician attestation of a life expectancy of 6 months or less if the disease runs its expected course. The\neligibility guidelines are based largely on whether a patient meets\nstage 7 on the FAST scale and whether they have at least one complication (aspiration, upper urinary tract infection, sepsis, multiple stage 3–​4 ulcers, persistent fever, or weight loss >10% within\n6 months) (Luchins et al., 1997). The FAST criteria are widely used,\ndespite their limited reliability for prognostication and the observation that many patients do not follow FAST stages sequentially.\nWhile other validated models have been developed to predict survival in advanced dementia, their accuracy are only moderately\nbetter in predicting the risk of death within 6 months (Yaffe, 2010).\nThe Advanced Dementia Prognostic Tool (ADEPT) (Mitchell et al.,\n2010) is one such tool and is intended to identify nursing home residents with advanced dementia who are at high risk of death within\n6 months (http://​eprog-​nosis.ucsf.edu/​mitchell.php).\n\nPlace of death and multiple transitions\nMost patients with advanced dementia require nursing home level\nof care at some point during their illness. Many of these patients die\n‘in place’ at the nursing home. For example, a US study reported\nthat nearly half (49%) of Medicare patients with dementia died in a\nnursing home (Teno et al., 2013).\nSimply knowing where someone dies may not say much about\nthe care they received at the end of life. While US patients with advanced dementia who received hospice at end of life increased from\n19.5% in 2000 to 48% in 2009, the proportion of patients with very\nshort hospice stays (<3 days) doubled, from 5% to 10% (Teno et al.,\n2013). In addition, 65% of advanced dementia patients were hospitalized in the last 90 days of life (with 10% hospitalized more than\nthree times) and 22% were hospitalized in the intensive care unit\nin the last 30 days of life (Teno et al., 2013). The median number\nof transitions per decedent increased from two in 2000 to thre"},{"id": "15.5","title": "Neurological Disorders Other Than Dementia","chapter": "15.5","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 996,"end": 1003,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "998\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nMucous congestion of the airways\n\nInsomnia and fatigue\n\nMucous congestion is difficult to manage in patients with impaired coughing. Treatment with mucolytics such as ambroxol or\nN-​acetylcysteine may be attempted, but is of limited benefit. A combination of nebulized beta receptor antagonists, saline, and furosemide has been recommended (Andersen et al., 2012). Guided\nrespiratory exercise may be considered helpful by patients, and\nmechanical aids, such as the CoughAssist®, high-​frequency chest\nwall oscillation, or a home suction device, can be applied.\n\nInsomnia has many potential causes in those with ALS. If symptom\nmanagement does not improve sleep, drug therapy is considered.\nBased on experience, various antidepressants (amitriptyline,\nmirtazapine) and hypnotics (zolpidem) may be used.\nFatigue is another common and potentially debilitating symptom.\nIf severe, modafinil or another psychostimulant such as methylphenidate may be tried (Andersen et al., 2012).\n\nMalnutrition\n\nPseudobulbar affect results from corticobulbar degeneration and\nmanifests in inappropriate laughter or crying incongruent to the\npatient’s mood. It can negatively affect social interactions and strain\nboth patients and caregivers. Relatives and caregivers must be informed that the patient is completely unable to control outbursts that\nappear emotionally charged but may not reflect the patient’s mood.\nA combination of dextromethorphan and quinidine has been\napproved by the US Food and Drug Administration for use in\npseudobulbar affect, but there also is evidence to suggest a positive\ntreatment effect of antidepressants, mainly citalopram and amitriptyline (Pioro, 2011). Antidepressants might be attempted especially\nif concomitant depression is suspected.\n\nMalnutrition in ALS, which mainly results from dysphagia and\nhypermetabolism, worsens prognosis treatment of dysphagia\n(Marin et al., 2011). Management usually starts with speech and\nlanguage therapy to reduce swallowing deficits and referral to a\ndietician. Feeding tube placement should be discussed early, since\nmany patients are reluctant to undergo this measure. This discussion should note that a positive effect of artificial nutrition on\nsurvival has not been confirmed in studies (Cui et al., 2018). The\ndecision to proceed with gastrostomy may be influenced by the\npresence of neurobehavioural dysfunction, which is associated with\nrelatively poorer outcomes (Chio et al., 2012). Gastrostomy can be\nperformed under endoscopic control; radiological guidance is preferred in patients with respiratory insufficiency or severe mouth\nopening dystonia.\nSialorrhoea\nSialorrhoea and drooling are commonly associated with swallowing\ndeficits. Non-​pharmacological treatment options include sage tea\nand consultation with a speech and language therapist to improve\nswallowing. If available, pharmacological treatment may begin with\nlow-​dose amitriptyline or a hyoscine hydrobrom"},{"id": "15.6","title": "Palliative Care and End-Stage Liver Disease","chapter": "15.6","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 1004,"end": 1009,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "1006\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nneurotoxin (Tapper et al., 2015). It affects 16–​21% of patients with\nESLD (D’Amico et al., 2006). HE symptoms are often classified\nusing the West Haven criteria (Ferenci et al., 2002): ‘Minimal HE’\nis limited to subtle alterations in psychometric testing. Grade I HE\nhas impaired attention span, cognitive tasks, and sleep-​wake cycles.\nGrade II and grade III features include lethargy, obvious disorientation, asterixis, and emotional lability, and grade IV HE is coma.\nClinically, patients with minimal or grade I HE are referred to as\nhaving ‘covert’ HE while grade II or higher is referred to as ‘overt’\n(Vilstrup et al., 2014). Both are associated with dramatic reductions\nin HRQL, as well as increased caregiver burden (Bajaj et al., 2011).\nInitial therapy for HE is lactulose, a non-​absorbable disaccharide,\nthat promotes conversion of ammonia to ammonium and subsequent excretion through the gastrointestinal tract. It is given typically in 25 mL doses and titrated to at least two or three bowel\nmovements per day (Vilstrup et al., 2014). For patients with refractory encephalopathy with comfort-​oriented goals who no longer\nhave nasogastric tube placement within goals of care, rectal administration of lactulose can be attempted, but often focus transitions\nto symptoms at the end of life (Walling and Wenger, 2020). Oral\npolyethylene glycol has similar efficacy to lactulose in hospitalized\npatients and may be used as an alternative (Rahimi et al., 2014).\nRifaximin, a non-​absorbable antibiotic, is often added for patients\nwho are unable to tolerate lactulose alone or experience progression\nin symptoms despite lactulose therapy. Both lactulose and rifaximin\nare associated with improvements in HRQL, though rifaximin is\nassociated with fewer gastrointestinal side effects (Kalaitzakis and\nBjornsson, 2007; Price, 2012).\nHE can be provoked by infection, dehydration, and constipation,\nand worsened by concomitant sedating medications. When caring for\npatients with overt HE, it is important that these causes be identified\nand treated in order to hasten recovery. Maintaining adequate nutrition also is important and daily energy intake should be 35–​40 kcal/​\nkg of ideal body weight. Frequent small meals and late-​night snacks\nhave been shown to be beneficial (Vilstrup et al., 2014). Contrary to\npast assumptions, patients with HE should be encouraged to maintain\nhigh amounts of protein intake, around 1.2–​1.5 g/​kg of body weight.\n\nManagement of other symptoms related to poor\nhealth-​related quality of life\nPatients with ESLD experience a number of symptoms that have\na significant impact on HQRL, which is becoming an increasingly\nrecognized priority for management. Fatigue, depression, sleep disturbance, pain, cognitive impairment, and dizziness are the most\ncommonly reported symptoms (An et al., 2015), though functional\ndecline has also been reported in patients waiting for liver transplant (Lai et"},{"id": "15.7","title": "End-Stage Kidney Disease","chapter": "15.7","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 1010,"end": 1019,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "1012\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nFatigue\nTiredness or fatigue is also difficult to define, and therefore to quantify. Despite this, there is evidence that it is one of the most common\nsymptoms experienced by renal patients; in most studies, between\n70% and 97% of dialysis patients are affected by fatigue (Murtagh\net al., 2007b; Almutary et al., 2013). A very high proportion (as\nmany as 90%) of conservatively managed stage 5 CKD patients are\nalso affected by fatigue, and 35% of patients are severely distressed\nby it (Murtagh et al., 2007c). Qualitative studies suggest that fatigue\none of the most difficult symptoms for patients to cope with (Chang\net al., 2001; Murtagh et al., 2007c).\nOther symptoms\nOther symptoms are important for patients with ESKD, including\nnausea and vomiting, drowsiness, breathlessness, leg oedema, dry\nmouth, lack of appetite and altered taste, poor concentration, dry\nskin, and constipation. Some symptoms, for example, breathlessness, are frequently linked to comorbidity, such as coexisting cardiac or respiratory disease, and their prevalence very much reflects\nthe demographics of the population, with older populations and\nthose conservatively managed (without dialysis)—​who are almost\nalways older patients—​displaying a notably higher prevalence of\nthese symptoms (Murtagh et al., 2007c).\n\nSymptoms due to comorbid conditions\nSymptoms may be due to uraemia, dialysis, or comorbid conditions,\nand many patients have a combination of causes and triggers that contribute to symptom burden. Comorbid conditions are particularly important in older patients, who often have vascular disease, cardiac or\npulmonary problems, diabetes mellitus, or other comorbidities. When\nESKD is due to diabetics, other symptoms often relate to comorbid\ndiabetic complications, such as diabetic gastroparesis (potentially\ncausing anorexia, early satiety, nausea, gastric reflux, or dyspepsia), intestinal autonomic neuropathy (leading to alternating diarrhoea and\nconstipation), painful peripheral neuropathies, and varied skin and\nsoft tissue problems (causing pain, itch, and other problems).\n\nAssessment of symptoms\nSome validated symptom measures evaluate multiple symptoms\nand may be useful in the clinical setting. They include several\nused in other advanced diseases, such as the Edmonton Symptom\nAssessment System (Parfrey et al., 1989; Davison et al., 2006a, 2006b)\nand the Memorial Symptom Assessment Scale (MSAS) short form\n(Weisbord et al., 2003; Murtagh et al., 2007c). Those validated specifically for renal disease include the Dialysis Symptom Index, developed from the MSAS (Weisbord et al., 2004), and the renal version of\nthe Patient Outcome Scale (symptom module) (Murphy et al., 2009).\nThe recently validated Integrated Patient Outcome Scale—​Renal version (IPOS-​Renal) measures physical and psychological symptoms,\nand also other concerns, such as information, family support, and\npractical matters (Raj et al., 2018); it was"},{"id": "15.8","title": "Palliative Care in Disasters and Humanitarian Crises","chapter": "15.8","section": "15","sectionLabel": "Non-Cancer Illnesses","start": 1020,"end": 1027,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "1022\n\nSECTION 15 Issues in populations with non-cancer illnesses\n\nhumanitarian crisis situations (Marston et al., 2015, 2017; Powell\net al., 2017; Smith and Aloudat, 2017).\nAltered standards of medical care\nWhether ‘big bang’ or ‘rising tide,’ established community healthcare\npractice standards may be temporarily altered in response to the\ndemands of the situation and the needs of the entire affected community (TariVerdi et al., 2018). Altered standards of medical care\n(e.g. what care is to be given, to whom, when, and by whom) refers\nto a shift from providing the optimal highest level of care for each\nindividual patient to a more utilitarian approach of allocating scarce\nequipment, supplies, and personnel in a way that saves the largest\nnumber of lives (Hick et al., 2012).\nAltered care practices commonly include requiring clinicians to\nration critical care resources only to patients with the best chance\nfor long-​term survival, practising in unfamiliar settings, providing\ntreatment beyond their medical expertise or training, restricting the\nuse of ventilators to surgical situations and other short-​term use,\nchanging infection control standards to permit group isolation, or\nto having to rely more on clinical judgement and less on testing procedures (Hanfling, 2011; Becker et al., 2013).\nThe initial evaluation and care provided to an individual with a\nlife-​limiting illness or injury is crucial because these decisions, such\nas providing life-​prolonging measures (e.g. resuscitation, intubation) and even the decision to transport the patient or not, largely\ndetermine the course of future care (Lamba et al., 2013).\nIt is not clear, however, to what degree the general public\nrecognizes the need for or understands the implications of altered\nstandards of care. There is also a widespread assumption by response personnel that this ‘shift’ will be a neat and tidy transition,\nwith clear indicators for when it is the time to make that transition, who should make the call, what it will look like, and what the\nlegal duty of care will be when it is determined that casualties outstrip supply. However, this is rarely the case because there are, as\nyet, no consistent or widely accepted set of criteria identifying when\nor under what specific circumstances this shift from individual\nmanagement to scarce resource management or a shift back again\nshould occur (Cusack and Gebbie, 2017). The wider community\nwill need to understand that crisis situations require the rationing\nof care in the face of extreme demand and/​or limited resources, or\nboth, in order to focus on the greatest good for the greatest number.\nConventional disaster triage and its implications\nfor palliative care\nIn the event of a disaster, emergency medical services will be called\non to provide first-​responder rescue, assessment, care, transportation,\nand access to the emergency medical healthcare system. The emergency medical services’ initial duty is to triage patients following a pre-​\nestablishe"},{"id": "16.1","title": "Involving Children When Someone is Dying","chapter": "16.1","section": "16","sectionLabel": "Very Young and Very Old","start": 1029,"end": 1034,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "CHAPTER 16.1 Involving children and families when someone important is dying or has died\n\ndeath, and so they may also offer solutions to death, and expect the\nperson to be ‘all better’. They may also attribute the grief and distress\nof other adults to their own behaviour and need frequent reminders\nthat they are not the cause of everyone’s upset feelings. Preschoolers,\ntherefore, need regular reassurance about how nothing they say or\ndo can make someone ill or die. Adults need to enquire about how\nthe child thinks the person became ill or died, and dispel misconceptions repeatedly. In addition, caregivers may need to be patient\nwith a natural disconnection of feelings and content, such that a\nchild might talk about the death very matter-​of-​factly or make up\na song about it, and yet might become cranky or have trouble with\nroutine activities or changes in schedule. Parents of preschoolers\ncan also expect some regression, so that a fully toilet-​trained child\nmay have trouble using the potty, or a child may get upset being\ndropped off at a previously beloved nursery.\nIn discussing death with young children, it is important to be\nhonest but in a concrete way, avoiding euphemisms, and using\nobservable examples. Descriptions of death as ‘going to sleep’ can\ncreate worries about bedtime or not waking up. Heaven may be conceptualized as a place that one can visit or come back from. ‘Losing’\nsomeone might be mean that they can be found again. It is therefore\nhelpful to talk about death as meaning that ‘the body doesn’t work\nanymore’, that the person cannot move or breathe, or think or feel,\nand so on. Adult caregivers are sometimes surprised and disturbed\nby how often young children need this explanation. Likewise, children of this age need simple explanations about the different emotions that they observe in adults so that they can be reassured that\nthese emotions are not a result of anything they have done, such as\n‘Mummy is crying because she is sad that Grandma has died’.\n\nSchool-​age children (6–​12 years)\nSchool-​age children are immersed in mastering academic, physical,\nand social skills, and are working to understand cause and effect\nlogic. They are often quite invested in fairness and are sensitive to\nthings that set them apart from their peers. By the ages of 6–​8 years,\nmost young children will understand the inevitability and permanence of death. Their conceptions may still be very concrete, though,\nand they may have difficulty understanding more abstract or spiritual ideas. In fact, this age group of children can be preoccupied\nwith factual, medical, or physical aspects of death and dying that\nadults find difficult to discuss. As with ‘preschoolers’, in discussing\ndeath it is important to be honest but in a concrete way, avoiding euphemisms, and using observable examples. The uncertainty about\ntime that is inherent in terminal illness may be particularly hard for\nyounger children to grasp, and so anticipating the death itself may\nbecome di"},{"id": "16.2","title": "Care of Children with Advanced Illness","chapter": "16.2","section": "16","sectionLabel": "Very Young and Very Old","start": 1035,"end": 1045,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 16.2 Care of children with advanced illness\n\nFollowing this interchange, Tom’s conversations about drugs and\ntheir side effects became less frequent. The drugs were not the answer that he and his parents had once thought them to be. As with\nother children who were aware of the prognosis, he made little reference to his condition or progress.\nMaria, a five-​year-​old Mexican American whose leukaemia was no\nlonger responding to treatment and had gone home to die, also used\nthe death of another child to elicit further information, in this case\nfrom her mother. Her awareness as well as her expressions and\nqueries about death were bound up in reference to two other Mexican\nAmerican children with leukaemia who had died.\nMaria: Do children play in heaven?\nMother: Yes, yes they do.\nMaria:\t\u0007Good, now I can play with Julio and Jorge. (Bluebond-​Langner,\n1978, p. 190)\n\nAwareness of the possibility of death from one’s disease, however,\nwas not necessarily indicative of internalizing it as a certainty for\noneself, as illustrated in this conversation between Lakshmi, a 5½-​\nyear-​old child born in the UK to first-​generation British Indian\nparents. Using various bits of information, she comes up with a coherent and hopeful view of her prognosis in the face of predicted\npoor survival.\nLakshmi, was diagnosed with juvenile myelomonocytic leukaemia\n(JMML) when she was three years old. After receiving aggressive\nchemotherapy and a bone-​marrow transplant with donor cells from\nher mother, Lakshmi went into remission and was well for about a\nyear. Then, at five and a half, she relapsed. Four months into her relapse, she causally told Bluebond-​Langner, while they were colouring,\n‘Alexa died. You know her. She had JMML just like me. I am going to\nget more cells’. Continuing to colour Lakshmi added, ‘From my mom,\nand be all-​better’. (Bluebond-​Langner et al., 2010, p. 333)\n\nNote that Lakshmi begins with the mention of someone who has\ndied, Alexa. She makes an attempt to establish the cause through\na statement or a hypothesis. JMML is the proposed cause of death.\nShe compares the dead child to herself but does not assume that\njust because they both have the same disease, she will die. Lakshmi\nholds out hope that she will recover, based on her previous experience, when she went into remission after receiving cells from her\nmother.\nAs noted in Bluebond-​L angner’s (1978) earlier work, while\nchildren can know of another child’s death, in the absence of\ndeterioration the child will not necessarily come to view themselves as dying. While acknowledging the possibility of death\nfrom a particular disease, one does not necessarily immediately\napply it to oneself. The conclusion may emerge over time. Thus,\nwe find that information is internalized or assimilated in a process, which is less dependent on the child’s age than on their\nexperiences.\nChildren can apply the information about their condition which\nthey have assimilated not just to themselves but to their relation"},{"id": "16.3","title": "Palliative Medicine and Care of the Elderly","chapter": "16.3","section": "16","sectionLabel": "Very Young and Very Old","start": 1046,"end": 1061,"pages": 16,"weight": 0.0128,"text": "1048\n\nSECTION 16 Issues of the very young and the very old\n\n2008). Several international guidelines including the National\nComprehensive Cancer Network guidelines (2018) and the\nAmerican Society of Clinical Oncology Geriatric Oncology\nguideline (Mohile et al., 2018) recommend integrating multidimensional geriatric screening and assessment to inform the\ntreatment and care planning for all people aged over 65–​70 years\nwith cancer. This assessment should include the domains of\nfunctional status, comorbidity, cognition, mental health, fatigue,\nsocial status and support, nutrition, and presence of geriatric\nsyndromes (Wildiers et al., 2014). Geriatric assessment informs\nadditional support needed and helps to identify remediable conditions influencing treatment decisions, establishes treatment\ngoals, and, if required, allows a modified treatment plan to be\ndeveloped (Mohile et al., 2018; National Comprehensive Cancer\nNetwork, 2018).\n• Heart failure: referral to a heart failure clinic is highly relevant\nfor many older people with this condition. Heart failure clinics\naim to reduce mortality and rehospitalization rates, and improve\nquality of life through individualized patient care (Hauptman\net al., 2008). These positive outcomes are achieved through the\nconsistent application of guidelines with a focus on:\n■ Management of the underlying heart failure\n■ Assessment of function, nutrition, and quality of life\n■ Optimizing medical therapy and drug evaluation including optimizing adherence and, where appropriate, de-​prescribing\n■ Implantable cardiac device evaluation\n■ Longitudinal follow-​\nup, in particular after hospitalization or\nperiods of destabilization\n■ Shared decision-​\nmaking, meeting information needs, and advance care planning\n■ Continuing professional education for heart failure clinicians,\nand provide a point of training for other health professionals\nand informal carers\n■ Embedding ongoing quality assessment and improvement of\nthe model of care (Hauptman et al., 2008).\n• Attendance at these specialist clinics provides older patients and\ntheir caregivers with an opportunity to be involved in shared decision-​making and to have timely conversations about palliative\nand end of life care preferences (Waterworth and Gott, 2010).\n• Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD): COPD is a\ncommon disorder with a high prevalence among older people and\nan increasing mortality rate (Gelberg and McIvor, 2010). Older\npeople affected by COPD have a significant symptom burden\nand are also at an increased risk of cardiovascular events, osteoporosis, fractures, peripheral muscle wasting, frailty, depression,\nand anxiety. This array of problems makes a multidisciplinary approach optimal with comprehensive assessment considering the\nindividual’s disease severity and prognosis (Gelberg and McIvor,\n2010; Reticker et al., 2012). Importantly, if older people with\nCOPD are well enough to participate in pulmonary rehabilitation,\nthey are likely to derive a clinicall"},{"id": "17.1","title": "Spiritual Issues in Palliative Medicine","chapter": "17.1","section": "17","sectionLabel": "Spiritual Issues","start": 1063,"end": 1071,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 17.1 Spiritual issues in palliative medicine\n\nand Strang, 2002). This acknowledges that suffering can include\nphysical pain and the reciprocal interaction between somatic pain\nand existential suffering.\nSuffering based on a perception of lost autonomy and control\nmay express itself in patient requests for death hastening measures. McClain and colleagues demonstrated significant negative\ncorrelations between spiritual well-​being and desire for hastened\ndeath (r = −0.51), hopelessness (r = −0.68), and suicidal ideation\n(r = −0.41) (McClain et al., 2003). These findings suggest that\nspiritual well-​being may offer some protection against end of life\ndespair based on the additional findings that depression was significantly correlated with desire for hastened death in patients with\nlow spiritual well-​being (r = 0.40) but not in those high in spiritual\nwell-​being (r = 0.20).\nResearch by Chochinov and colleagues also demonstrates the salience of existential issues as they affect the wish to go on living in\nthe face of a progressing terminal illness. Examination of the concurrent influences on the will to live in a sample of 189 end-​stage\ncancer patients revealed that physical issues played a secondary role\nto existential, psychiatric, and social variables, all of which were\nhighly correlated with the will to live. Stepwise regression modelling\nwas conducted to examine the relationship between will to live and\npatient characteristics. Hopelessness, burden to others, and dignity\nentered into the final model, demonstrating the profound influence\nof existential variables on patient outlook in the context of terminal\nillness (Chochinov et al., 2005b). Given their prominent influence\non will to live among patients nearing death, healthcare providers\nare well advised to more fully appreciate their importance.\n\nSpirituality and patient perspectives\nDo terminally ill patients and those with life-​threatening\nillnesses want healthcare providers to be attuned\nto spiritual needs?\nPublic opinion and empirical literature suggest that such attention would be welcomed by at least some patients. A Gallup survey\n(Gallup International Institute, 1997) examining spiritual beliefs\nand the dying process (N = 1200) indicated that in addition to\nturning to family (81%), close friends (61%), and clergy (36%) for\ncompanionship and support at the end of life, 30% of respondents\nwould look to doctors for such support. Forty per cent of respondents indicated that it would be very important to have a physician\nwho was spiritually attuned to them if they were dying.\nKing and Bushwick conducted a cross-​sectional survey of family\npractice adult inpatients at two hospitals in the US (N = 203).\nThough limitations of the study include patient homogeneity and\nvariations in regional religiosity, the findings revealed that 77%\nof patients felt that physicians should consider patients’ spiritual\nneeds, and 37% of patients wanted their physicians to discuss religious beliefs with"},{"id": "17.2","title": "Integration of Spiritual Care into Palliative Care","chapter": "17.2","section": "17","sectionLabel": "Spiritual Issues","start": 1072,"end": 1081,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "1074\n\nSECTION 17 Spiritual issues in palliative medicine\n\nThe International Consensus Conference addresses and provides recommendations to advance the integration of spiritual\ncare into the healthcare provision. These include (1) building research in spirituality and palliative care to guide and advance practice; (2) building best practices for standard inclusion of spiritual\ncare within care teams; (3) development of spiritual care curricula\nand core competency standards; (4) advocacy and policy efforts to\nstandardize inclusion of spiritual care within healthcare; (5) communication regarding research, clinical care, education, and policy\nefforts to ensure broad dissemination; and (6) engaging community\ngroups to ensure spiritual care provision in healthcare setting connects to the broader communities being served.\n\nSpirituality, religiousness, and palliative\ncare outcomes\nThe inclusion of spiritual care within palliative care guidelines is\nbased on a large body of evidence informing the importance of\nspirituality within the experience of serious illness for patients and\ntheir families. Spiritual needs in the context of serious illness are\ncommon. Furthermore, spirituality, religiousness, and spiritual\nneeds are frequently associated with important palliative care outcomes (Steinhauser et al., 2017b). This evidence provides critical\ncontext and rationale for the integration of spiritual care within\npalliative care.\n\nPatient spirituality, religiousness, and perceptions\nof spiritual care\nApproximately 80–​90% of patients view religion or spirituality as\npersonally important (El Nawawi et al., 2012). A mixed qualitative–​\nquantitative study demonstrated that religion or spirituality is important to the illness experience for 78% of patients, and functions\nwithin illness in multiple ways, including coping, practices, beliefs,\ntransformation, and communities (Alcorn et al., 2010). Though\ndata are limited, the available evidence for caregivers of seriously ill\npatients suggests that caregivers are similarly religious and spiritual\n(Ernecoff et al., 2015; Steinhauser et al., 2017b). Two studies also\nfound that approximately 80% of seriously ill patients have spiritual\nneeds (El Nawawi et al., 2012; Astrow et al., 2018). Additionally,\nmost seriously ill patients believe spiritual care is an important and\nappropriate component of clinical care. Furthermore, when spiritual care is provided, large majorities of patients and clinicians view\nit positively (Phelps et al., 2012). However, spiritual care has been\nshown in multiple studies of patients to be infrequent (T. A. Balboni\net al., 2007; Epstein-​Peterson et al., 2015).\n\nSpirituality, religiousness, and palliative care outcomes\nA large body of evidence indicates that various domains of spirituality and religiousness impact palliative care outcomes in seriously\nill patient populations. Herein, data regarding these relationships\nare addressed in three categories: (1) spirituality, religiousness, and\nqualit"},{"id": "18.1","title": "Predicting Survival in Advanced Disease","chapter": "18.1","section": "18","sectionLabel": "Terminal Phase","start": 1083,"end": 1093,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 18.1 Predicting survival in patients with advanced disease\n\ntumour-​related factors held significant weight when formulating\na clinician-​based prognosis (Tannenberger et al., 2002). In 2000,\nChristakis and Lamont found oncologists consider social support\nin addition to biological parameters when making predictions\n(Christakis and Lamont, 2000). Formulation methods clinicians\nmight use include recalling similar previous patients, considering\nstatistical knowledge of population survival rates, assessing functional or cognitive status, referring to guidelines, or possibly some\ncombination of these methods. A semi-​structured approach has\nbeen posited (Mackillop, 2006), beginning with the general prognosis, based on the clinical and pathological findings (e.g. median\nsurvival of 6 months for stage 4 lung cancer). From there, clinicians customize the prediction based on the clinical situation,\nincluding comorbidities, symptoms, laboratory abnormalities,\nand psychosocial issues.\n\nAccuracy and reliability\nA systematic review of 42 prediction studies by White and colleagues in 2016 found CPS is frequently inaccurate (White et al.,\n2016). Analysis was complicated since only few studies qualified\nwith different methods to estimate CPS. Twenty studies used a categorical temporal approach, 16 provided continuous temporal estimates, three used probabilistic estimates, and the three remaining\nstudies using mixed methods. While few studies examined probabilistic estimates, this approach was considered more accurate\nthan using temporal predictions.\nOverall, the predictions were more likely to overestimate survival, but a number of studies were more likely to underestimate\nsurvival. Accuracy errors occur bidirectionally, so one should not\npresume predictions are always likely to be overestimated.\nAccuracy may change depending on characteristics of the clinician, but the small number of CPS studies and lack of consistent\nmethods prevent making strong conclusions. Studies have examined differences in experience, discipline, specialty, and length of\ndoctor–​patient relationship. Clinician factors which may improve\naccuracy include increased experience and working as a multidisciplinary team instead of as an individual (Mendis et al., 2015). No\nparticular specialty, including palliative care, is necessarily better or\nworse at prediction. Many prognostic studies should be replicated\nbefore we can firmly conclude that factors such as length of doctor–​\npatient relationship, interval since last exam, discipline, or specialty\nmake a significant difference in accuracy.\n\nThe surprise question was not developed as a prognostic tool but\nrather a trigger for identifying clinical needs and it is not considered\na tool for prognosis communication.\n\nConfounding influence of new therapeutic options\nSurvival data based on accumulated outcome data depending on\nstage and severity of illness commonly informs prognostication.\nBecause these prognostic models take years for vali"},{"id": "18.2","title": "Physiology of Dying","chapter": "18.2","section": "18","sectionLabel": "Terminal Phase","start": 1094,"end": 1103,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "1096\n\nSECTION 18 The terminal phase\n\nTable 18.2.1 Definition of signs of impending death\nPhysical sign\n\nDescription\n\nNeurological\nNon-​reactive pupils\n\nLack of pupillary reflex to light stimuli\n\nCheyne–​Stokes breathing\n\nAlternating periods of apnoea and hyperpnea with a crescendo–​decrescendo pattern\n\nDecreased response to verbal stimuli\n\nUnable to follow verbal commands. No verbal communication\n\nDecreased response to visual stimuli\n\nNo eye tracking movement\n\nApnoea periods\n\nProlonged pauses (≥20 seconds) between each breath\n\nNeuromuscular\nInability to close eyelids\n\nEyes open and no blinking observed. Not able to close when asked\n\nGrunting of vocal cords\n\nSound produced predominantly on expiration, related to vibrations of the vocal cords\n\nRespiration with mandibular movement\n\nDepression of jaw with inspiration\n\nDeath rattle\n\nGurgling sound produced on inspiration and/​or expiration related to airway secretions\n\nDrooping of nasolabial fold\n\nDecrease in prominence/​visibility of the nasolabial fold\n\nHyperextension of neck\n\nNeck extension when patient in supine position\n\nCardiovascular\nPulselessness of radial artery\n\nInability to palpate radial pulse on one or both sides\n\nUrine output over last 12 h <100 mL\n\nMeasured volume of urine ≤100 mL over a 12 h period\n\nUpper gastrointestinal bleed\n\nHaematemesis or melena\n\nPeripheral cyanosis\n\nBluish discoloration of extremities\n\nSource: data from Hui, D. et al., (2014). Clinical signs of impending death in cancer patients. Oncologist. 19(6):681–​7. DOI: 10.1634/​\ntheoncologist.2013-​0457; and Hui, D. et al., (2015). Bedside clinical signs associated with impending death in patients with advanced\ncancer: Preliminary findings. Cancer. 121(6):960–​7. DOI: https://​doi.org/​10.1002/​cncr.29048.\n\nAcute symptomatic complications and deteriorating\norgan function\nWith an overall decline in function, patients are at high risk of acute\ncomplications such as infections, thrombosis, acute kidney injury,\nmyocardial infarction, and stroke. In the Investigating the Process\nof Dying Study, over 90% of patients admitted to an inpatient unit\nhad at least one acute symptomatic complication, with a median\nof two complications on admission and five complications before\ndischarge (Hui et al., 2015b). Understandably, a greater number\nof complications is associated with a shorter survival (Hui et al.,\n2015b).\nThe alterations in physiological and organ function as a result of\nprogressive disease and acute complications can be monitored biochemically. Reid and colleagues conducted a systematic review of\n30 studies examining various laboratory-​based prognostic markers\nassociated in patients with advanced cancer (Reid et al., 2017). As\npeople approach the last months or weeks of life, they often have\ndeveloped systemic inflammation associated with characteristic\nchanges in haematological parameters (elevated C-​reactive protein,\nleucocytosis, lymphocytopenia, thrombocytopenia), nutritional\nfailure (hypoalbuminemia, low pre-​albumin"},{"id": "18.3","title": "Management of the Actively Dying Patient","chapter": "18.3","section": "18","sectionLabel": "Terminal Phase","start": 1104,"end": 1120,"pages": 17,"weight": 0.0136,"text": "1106\n\nSECTION 18 The terminal phase\n\nTable 18.3.1 Families’ support and information needs during the terminal phase\nPatient comfort\n\nPrompt and effective relief of patient symptoms is essential to support the family as a whole\n\nInformation and communication\n\nCommunication needs to be honest, direct, and compassionate, and must allow for the concerns and opinions of the\nfamily to be heard and appreciated. Family members need information about the likely course of the patient’s illness.\nPotential symptoms and plans for their monitoring and management should be explained\n\nEvaluation of family needs and\nresources\n\nThe degree with which the family is able and willing to participate in care is a major determinate in formulating a care\nplan\nIf the family are considering caring for a patient at home, family members need information regarding the daily care\nneeds of the patient, likely clinical problems, available resources for routine care, and availability of emergency care\n\nCare education\n\nIrrespective as to whether the patient is at home or in hospital, family members require guidance regarding ways in which\nthey can contribute to the comfort care of the patient\n\nEmergency provisions\n\nIf the family are considering caring for a patient at home, the family need to know what to do and who to call in case of\nuncontrolled symptoms and when the patient dies\nLink to a 24-​hour phone support service is important in this situation\n\nReview of family coping\n\nFamily coping should be regularly assessed to enable early intervention to address unmet emotional or supportive needs\nof the family or previously unappreciated patient problems\n\nCare of the family when the\npatient is unconscious\n\nContinued vigilance and reassurance that comfort is being achieved are essential for the well-​being of the family\n\nPreparing the family for the\ndying process\n\nWhen death is imminent, the family should be forewarned of the process that they are likely to witness\n\nReproduced with permission from Lacey, J. and Sanderson, C. (2010). The Oncologist’s Role in Care of the Dying Cancer Patient. Cancer J. 16(5): 532–​41. DOI: 10.1097/​\nPPO.0b013e3181f2894c. Source: data from Cherny, N.I. et al. (1996). Guidelines in the care of the dying cancer patient. Hematol Oncol Clin North Am. 10(1):261–​86. DOI: 10.1016/​\ns0889-​8588(05)70338-​5.\n\nall stakeholders: patient, family members, and professional caregivers. Indeed, situations in which these issues are unaddressed, or\naddressed ineffectually or insensitively are a major cause of conflict, stress, and sometimes moral distress. Furthermore, in many\njurisdictions there is a medico-​legal requirement to discuss and to\ndocument these issues. Patients approaching death commonly became incapacitated and unable to express opinions regarding care\nchoices. Encouraging discussions about care preferences in advance\nof the terminal phase reduces the burden (and potential for added\ndistress) otherwise placed on the substitute decision makers and\nensures "},{"id": "19.1","title": "Practical Bioethics in Advanced Illness","chapter": "19.1","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1121,"end": 1131,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "CHAPTER 19.1 Practical bioethics in the care of patients with advanced illness\n\n4 Box Method\nMedical Indications\n\nPatient Preferences\n\nPrinciples of Beneficence and\nNonmaleficence\n\nPrinciple of Respect for Autonomy\n\nWhat are the goals of treatment?\nWhat are the probabilities of success?\nIs the problem acute? chronic? reversible,\nemergent?\n\nIs patient mentally capable and legally\ncompetent?\nEvidence of incapacity?\nHas patient been informed and understands?\nIs patient unwilling or unable to cooperate?\nWhy?\n\nQuality of Life\n\nContextual or External\n\nPrinciples of Beneficence and Nonmaleficence\nand Respect for Autonomy\n\nPrinciples of Loyalty and Fairness\n\nWhat are prospects for return to normal life?\nAre there biases which might prejudice\nprovider’s evaluation of patient’s quality of\nlife?\nAre there plans for comfort and palliative\ncare?\n\nAre there family issues that might influence\ntreatment decisions?\nAre there financial and economic factures?\nAre there limits on confidentiality?\nAre there religious or cultural factors?\nProblems with allocation of resources?\n\nFig. 19.1.1 Four-​quadrant approach to ethical decision-​making.\nReproduced with permission from Macauley, R.C. (2018). Ethics in Palliative Care: A Complete Guide. Oxford, UK: Oxford University Press. Source: data from Jonsen, A.R. et al.\n(2010). Clinical Ethics: A Practical Approach to Ethnical Decisions in Clinical Medicine, Seventh Edition. New York, USA: McGraw-​Hill Companies Inc.\n\npatient’s goals and values and how they relate to projected quality\nof life. It is imperative here to use the patient’s own measure of an\nacceptable quality of life, given that physicians tend to underestimate patients’ quality of life, especially in subjective domains such\nas emotion and pain (Janse et al., 2004).\nThe fourth quadrant is ‘contextual features’, which takes into\naccount familial, social, religious, cultural, and financial factors.\nAttention to these factors recognizes that a variety of considerations\nplay into a patient’s or surrogate’s decision. In addition, it acknowledges that most patients have substantive personal relationships,\nsuch that what happens to the patient influences others, as well. And\nwhile some might argue that the medical team’s concern should be\nsolely focused on the patient, even a modest recognition of interrelationship necessitates consideration of other people’s feelings, beliefs, and values, as well (McCullough, 1984).\nIn many situations, a review of available data reveals that some\npertinent information has not yet been obtained. There are several\nreasons for this. First, the situation may be sufficiently critical that\nthe medical team has been so caught up in stabilizing the patient\nthat they haven’t had the time or resources to acquire supporting information. Alternatively, the additional information may lie outside\nthe traditional realm of data acquired in the care of a patient, especially one who is critically ill. For instance, it is not uncommon for\nthe clinical t"},{"id": "19.2","title": "Requests for Futile or Inappropriate Interventions","chapter": "19.2","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1132,"end": 1138,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "1134\n\nSECTION 19 Ethical issues\n\n1999: American Medical Association\n\n2005: World Medical Association\n\nThe American Medical Association (AMA) is the largest medical professional organization in the US with approximately 240,000 members.\nIn the late 1990s, the AMA argued that providing a specific definition\nof futility was not possible. The AMA advocated for a process-​based\napproach in cases where surrogate decision makers demanded interventions that the doctors believed were futile (AMA, 1999).\nThe AMA’s seven-​step process included the following:\n\nThe World Medical Association, founded in 1947, is an international organization representing physicians globally with 114 national medical association members. In 2005, the World Medical\nAssociation published its Medical Ethics Manual which also favours\nthe term inappropriate over the term futile (which is not used). In\nthat publication, the World Medical Association stated that physicians should refuse requests for inappropriate interventions if the\ninterventions are unlikely to be beneficial or if they are convinced\nthat the interventions would produce more harm than benefit\n(World Medical Association 2005).\n\n1. Discussions with patients prior to becoming critically ill to\n\nfind mutually agreeable treatment options. If the doctor and\npatient cannot find a mutually agreeable option, the patient’s\ncare should be transferred to another doctor prior to the patient\nbecoming ill.\n2. If the patient becomes critically ill and the patient or surrogate\ndecision maker wants interventions that the doctor believes are\nfutile, they should discuss the medical facts, prognosis, and values\nto attempt to find a mutually agreeable course of treatment.\n3. If that fails, a consultant, who can assist in communication between the patient/​surrogate decision maker and the doctor,\nshould attempt to facilitate conversations with a goal of finding a\nmutually agreeable course of treatment.\n4. If that fails, the hospital ethics committee should be consulted.\n5. If disagreement persists, then the patient should be transferred\nto another doctor within the institution.\n6. If no other doctor at the institution will accept the patient, then\nthe patient should be transferred to another institution.\n7. If no other institution will accept the patient in transfer, then the\nfutile interventions should be withheld or withdrawn.\n\n2001: UK joint statement\nIn 2001, the British Medical Association, the Resuscitation\nCouncil (UK), and the Royal College of Nursing issued their joint\nstatement. Interestingly and importantly, the statement avoids\nthe term futility and it frames the issue in terms of ‘appropriateness’. They stated: ‘Neither patients nor relatives can demand\ntreatment which the health care team judges to be inappropriate,\nbut all efforts will be made to accommodate wishes and preferences’ (British Medical Association et al., 2001, p. 310). The organizations defined non-​beneficial treatment stating: ‘No benefit\nis gained if only a "},{"id": "19.3","title": "Autonomy and Shared Decision-Making","chapter": "19.3","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1139,"end": 1146,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 19.3 Autonomy and shared decision-making in a multicultural world\n\nWhile expressing concern, it is useful to explain that the patient\nmay want more information than they think or more than is usual\nfor people from their cultural background. It is worth adding that\nwhen this issue has been studied, patients often wanted more information than their family members have previously thought.\nA second issue worth addressing is that patients are often aware\nwhen they are being deceived with either edited information or\nmis-​information and that this may produce a sense of enhanced\nanxiety rather than reduced anxiety.\nIt is often useful to address the issue of fairness reflectively by\nasking the concerned family member to imagine how it would feel\nif it were them who were ill and their family members were making\ndecisions for them without bothering to ask how they felt about either receiving information about their diagnosis or potential treatment options.\nFinally, it is generally appropriate to make a concrete proposal to\nsit with the patient to clarify from them as to whether they would\nlike to receive information and what sort of information they would\nlike to receive. The family should be reassured that should the patient choose not to receive information or details relating to the\nexact nature of the diagnosis or prognosis, the patient’s preferences\nwill be respected.\n\nAutonomy\nPatient autonomy is generally understood to imply that physicians\nought to disclose as much information as desired by the patient to\nfacilitate participation in decision-​making to the degree preferred\nby the patient (Pellegrino, 1992). Disclosure, in this context, refers\nto the imparting of information necessary to make informed decisions about ongoing care; the key elements include the diagnosis,\nthe extent of disease, the range of therapeutic options available, the\nlikelihood of benefit or harm from each of the treatment options,\nthe potential severity of such adverse effects and the anticipated\nscope of benefit, and issues related to prognosis (such as if the illness\nis curable, the duration of anticipated survival, and the proximity\nto death).\nWhat is often overlooked, however, is that autonomy has a spectrum of expressions including isolated autonomy, relational autonomy, and voluntary diminished autonomy (Cherny, 2012; Gilbar\nand Miola, 2014).\n\nCultural and interpersonal factors may influence the degree to\nwhich the patient involves family or other stakeholders and the\ndegree to which they allow these considerations to impact their\ndecision-​making. So long as these relationships do not involve coercion over the patient by family members or other people, this is a\nnormative and valid expression of autonomy (Ho, 2008).\n\nVoluntary diminished autonomy\nSome patients have valid concerns that they may be harmed by excessively candid diagnostic or prognostic information, or by the\nburden of decision-​making. They may not want to know the exact\nnature of the disease, it"},{"id": "19.4","title": "Truth Telling and Consent","chapter": "19.4","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1147,"end": 1154,"pages": 8,"weight": 0.0064,"text": "CHAPTER 19.4 Truth telling and consent\n\nwhile others argue that clinicians have the responsibility to elicit\nor respond to the patient (Chewning et al., 2012). Self-​help books\nurge individuals to proactively ask questions about diagnosis and\nprognosis (Lynn et al., 2011). However, large variations exist in\ndecision-​making role preferences (Tariman et al., 2009). Fewer patients actually participate in decisions than state a desire for full information (Gaston and Mitchell, 2005). The nature of the decision\nand stage of the therapeutic relationship can also influence preferences (Chewning et al., 2012). Further, shared decision-​making\nrequires a thorough understanding of process and a lack of organizational barriers.\nAll of these are important considerations, given that involvement\nin shared decision-​making can improve quality of life at the end of\nlife (Steinhauser et al., 2009). Communications between family and\nprofessionals during goals-​of-​care discussions, family conferences,\nand family involvement in decision-​making just before death, show\nhow important collaborative decision-​making can be for symptom\nmanagement (Mentes et al., 2004), difficult invasive treatment\nchoices (Deshpande et al., 2005), the initiation of palliative care\n(Nolan et al., 2008), and end of life discussions in intensive care settings (Brooks et al., 2017). Family caregiving research, also referred\nto as family systems in nursing research, has also shown how family\ninvolvement in healthcare decision-​making can strengthen collaboration and trust between families and healthcare teams (Anderson,\n2000; Rempel et al., 2007). Family engagement can also reduce the\nrisk of providing unwanted care (Fineberg, 2005), and unnecessary\nand distressing hospital admissions among older persons (Ahearn\net al., 2010). Guidelines can be effective decision-​making aids for\nboth clinicians and family members. Guidelines for palliative care\nin dementia, for example, have been linked to a decrease in the prescription of antibiotics and increases in the use of analgesics with\n\npersons who are unable to verbally communicate their wishes\n(Volicer and Ganzini, 2003).\n\nHow to accomplish truth telling\nSome suggest that communication functions correlate with good\noutcomes (Back et al., 2009). The taxonomy illustrated in Fig. 19.4.1\nshows six communication functions delivered at six stages along\nthe cancer continuum that can improve survival and health-​related\nquality of life. Epstein and Street (2007) propose that a key task for\nresearchers is to ‘specify what [types of behaviours] will improve\noutcomes for a particular person at a given point in time on the\ncontinuum’.\nStepwise protocols can help healthcare teams by structuring\ngoals-​of-​care discussions with persons and their families. Protocols\nare essentially guidelines, which can be adapted to local context\nand tailored for each transaction. SPIKES, the stepwise protocol recommended in the Education for Physicians in End-​of-​Life Care\n"},{"id": "19.5","title": "Ethics in Paediatric Palliative Care","chapter": "19.5","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1155,"end": 1160,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "CHAPTER 19.5 Ethics in paediatric palliative care\n\nRelationality\nWhere autonomy, beneficence, and non-​maleficence all relate primarily to decisions made in the context of a relationship between\nan individual child and an individual doctor, the principle of justice\nrefers instead to ‘states of affairs’ (Smart and Williams, 1973). While\nthe other three principles focus on the needs of an individual patient,\njustice can make individuals subordinate to the needs of society.\nA 3-​year-​old boy with advanced metabolic degenerative condition was described by his paediatrician as ‘almost in a permanent\nvegetative state’. After several chest infections of increasing severity\nand frequency, his parents brought him to hospital with signs of another pneumonia, insisting that he should be ventilated again. The\nintensive care paediatrician explained that ventilation would be inappropriate, because it would mean their son occupying a bed that\nanother child could use more effectively.\nFew clinicians would disagree with the conclusion that the child\nshould not be ventilated. The ethical reasoning also appears sound.\nIt is, however, cruel, unreasonable and coercive to expect parents to\nsacrifice their child to the well-​being of others (American Academy\nof Pediatrics, 1996; Nuffield Council on Bioethics, 2006). It ignores\nthe child’s nature as a dependent being in the care of a family.\nThe relationship of physician and child is also of ethical relevance\n(Bartholome, 1985, 1996; Ramsey, 2002). While the starting point\nThe starting point for designers of an ethical healthcare system must\nbe that all patients, real or hypothetical, are equally important. But\nit is outside the scope of a physician’s relationship with a particular\nchild to considering the impact of an intervention on hypothetical\n‘other children’. Clinicians may need to make ethical decisions in\nboth modes: in the context of their relationship with individual patients, and in designing and maintaining fair systems. That duality\nacknowledges the tension between the needs of an individual actual\npatient and those of hypothetical other patients, and is both consistent and necessary.\n\nEthics in children: underlying theories\nDeontology\nDeontological arguments suggest there is an absolute moral code\nthat is equally relevant to all people, in all situations, irrespective\nof the consequences. There are many possible sources for such a\ncode. One is the authority of God through religious scripture. Most\nscripture, however, was not designed primarily as an exposition of\na consistent ethical code and is sometimes elliptical and/​or subject\nto interpretation. Ethical accounts derived from religious understanding are rarely completely agreed, even among those who share\nthat faith. A second source might be the universe itself. Ancient and\nmediaeval understanding was that the universe was rationally ordered, and coherence with that rational order was the yardstick by\nwhich the rightness of behaviour should be measure"},{"id": "19.6","title": "Physician Aid-in-Dying: Ethical Issues","chapter": "19.6","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1161,"end": 1169,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 19.6 Ethical issues in physician aid-in-dying\n\nactive intervention. The root of this problem is the New England\nJournal of Medicine article ‘Active and passive euthanasia’ by philosopher James Rachels (1975), which has gained the status of a\nclassic work and is often cited. Unfortunately, even some medical\nassociations have adopted this confusing distinction and terminology in their position statements (Materstvedt, 2016a).\nWhat many in the past designated as passive euthanasia in the\nincurably ill is better characterized as a non-​treatment decision\n(Chambaere et al., 2012), which includes withholding and withdrawing life-​sustaining treatment, followed by natural death due to\nthe underlying disease (sometimes called ‘allowing to die’). In the\nNetherlands, and in many other parts of the world, such decisions\nand acts are seen as forming part of routine and mainstream medicine (see Chapter 19.7).\nIn Holland, this distinction is reinforced by the legal requirement\nof a doctor who performs euthanasia to report the patient’s death as\nunnatural (and state that on the death certificate) because then the\npatient could not have died of natural causes; instead, death would\nhave been caused by an injection of lethal substances.\n\nPalliative sedation\nPalliative sedation refers to the use of pharmacological depression of the level of consciousness in order to alleviate suffering that\ncannot be relieved in any other way (Førde et al., 2015; Twycross,\n2019; Koksvik et al., 2020). The depth of the sedation required to\nprovide adequate relief is variable.\nIn its most radical form—​deep and continuous palliative sedation (DCPS)—​the patient dies in that state of unconsciousness\n(Materstvedt and Bosshard, 2009). For all practical purposes, due\nto being unable to communicate, the patient is accordingly socially\ndead before he or she becomes biologically dead. Still, DCPS is a\ntherapeutic intervention the success of which is determined by\nthe adequacy of relief and not, in contrast to PAD, by the (non-​\ntherapeutic) accelerated death of the patient (Materstvedt, 2012,\n2020b). Furthermore, it is noteworthy that the Government of the\nNetherlands (2021b) is clear that palliative sedation is ‘a normal\nmedical procedure’ (as is an non-​treatment decision, as previously\ndescribed).\nPalliative sedation, however, can be misused by intentionally\noverdosing the patient far beyond what is required for symptom\ncontrol (Koksvik et al., 2020). If such overdosing were done\non purpose at the patient’s request, then what was asked for\nand what was performed would be in line with the Dutch definition, namely euthanasia, albeit slow. If there was no such request but intentional overdosing was done anyway, it would not\nbe euthanasia but would, in principle, be a slow case of murder\nunder the Dutch penal code (Materstvedt, 2012; Materstvedt and\nMagelssen, 2016).\nTo prevent misuse and to safeguard appropriate medical practice, guidelines have been developed for DCPS as a treatmen"},{"id": "19.7","title": "Withholding and Withdrawing Life-Sustaining Treatment","chapter": "19.7","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1170,"end": 1179,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "1172\n\nSECTION 19 Ethical issues\n\nreligions (Loike et al., 2010; Wilkinson and Savulescu, 2014) add to\nthe misconception that withholding LST is prima facie more ethically justifiable than withdrawing LST. Furthermore, withdrawing\nLST is an act of commission (as opposed to withholding LST, which\nis an act of omission), and death usually follows more quickly\n(Sprung et al., 2003). Taken together, withdrawing LST may carry\na greater psychological burden for patients, families, and healthcare\npractitioners and therefore in practice, a distinction between withholding and withdrawing LSTs remains (Solomon et al., 1993;\nDickenson, 2000; Willmott et al., 2014).\n\nEthical considerations\nDecisions about the withholding/​withdrawing of LST are informed\nby bioethical considerations. These are strongly influenced by cultural and societal norms, which inform the context through which\nindividuals experience illness, suffering, and death (Singer and\nBowman, 2002; Sprung et al., 2007b).\nGeneral principles of modern bioethics\nBeneficence, non-​maleficence, autonomy, and justice are the four\nguiding principles of US-​derived modern bioethics and any decision\nto withhold/​withdraw LST should include careful consideration of\nthese, noting that no one principle necessarily takes precedence\nover any other, and remain sensitive to the impact of culture and\nsociety on individual end of life views (Singer and Bowman, 2002;\nBeauchamp and Childress, 2009).\nIn managing LSTs, clinicians act to benefit their patients (beneficence) and refrain from causing harm (non-​maleficence) (Will,\n2011a). Withholding/​withdrawing LST may superficially be seen to\nrun counter to the principle of beneficence. However, clinicians must\nbe mindful that LSTs may be associated with significant physical harm\n(e.g. rib fractures following CPR) and be in violation of a patient’s\nvalues and goals. Clinicians also act in support of patient autonomy, a\nconcept derived from the moral obligation of respect for persons, and\nbroadly defined as the human capacity for self-​determination—​the\nright to define one’s own goals and make choices to achieve them (Kant\nand Gregor, 1998). Patient autonomy is the basis for both informed\nconsent and the right to refuse treatment (President’s Commission\nfor the Study of Ethical Problems in Medicine and Biomedical and\nBehavioral Research, 1982; Will, 2011b). It is related to the concept of\ndignity, which may be understood as respect for individual autonomy\nor reflecting the inherent value of humankind (Horn and Kerasidou,\n2016). While some ethicists argue that dignity and autonomy are redundant concepts (Macklin, 2003), others highlight their distinctions\n(Beyleveld and Brownsword, 2001); the concept of dignity may aid in\ntranslating international guidelines to local practice.\nSupport for autonomy is challenging when it conflicts with other\nprinciples. When patients request interventions that the physician\nconsiders harmful, the physician may be conflicted between suppor"},{"id": "19.8","title": "Palliative Sedation at End of Life","chapter": "19.8","section": "19","sectionLabel": "Ethics","start": 1180,"end": 1190,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "1182\n\nSECTION 19 Ethical issues\n\nWhen DPS is considered in cases of refractory suffering of terminally ill patients, deep sedation as a means to relieve suffering must\nbe the intended good effect. Possible adverse effects such as respiratory depression, hypotension, and hastening death may be foreseeable but must not be intended. The act of giving medicine to relieve\nsuffering is not immoral as long as the patient or surrogate requests\nrelief and accepts the risk of adverse effects, and there are no safer\nmeans to achieve an acceptable degree of relief. Such serious adverse effects must be risked only for a proportionally grave reason\nsuch as the relief of severe refractory suffering of a terminally ill patient who does not wish to suffer (Krakauer et al., 2000).\nSome have criticized the principle of double effect or questioned\nits applicability to DPS, in part because the principle relies on the\ndistinction between the intended and the merely foreseen (Quill\net al., 1997a). It is argued that clinical intentions may be ambiguous\nand difficult to discern. Because of the complexity and potential ambiguity of clinical intentions, physicians working to relieve the suffering of terminally ill patients should think through their intentions\ncarefully, document them in the medical record, and demonstrate\nthem with their actions (Hallenbeck, 2000). The least toxic medicines should be used at the minimum doses that achieve the desired\neffect. The patient’s response to the treatment and level of comfort\nshould be assessed and documented frequently, and changes in the\ndose or type of medicine should be made and documented based on\nthese assessments. In this way, clinical intentions are made as clear\nas possible, the benefits of the intervention maximized, and the risk\nof adverse effects minimized (Cherny et al., 2009).\n\nDistinguishing deep palliative sedation from voluntary\nactive euthanasia and physician-​assisted suicide\nIt is widely accepted that DPS can and should be clearly distinguished in theory and in practice from both voluntary active euthanasia and physician-​assisted suicide (see Chapter 19.6) (De\nGraeff and Dean, 2007; Russell et al., 2010; ten Have and Welie,\n2014; Raho and Miccinesi, 2015; Soh et al., 2016). In DPS, the\nphysician intends only to relieve severe refractory suffering using\nsedation as a last resort. There is no intent to hasten death as there\nis with euthanasia and physician-​assisted suicide (Cherny, 2006).\nIn practice, DPS entails titration of medicines to achieve the goal of\ncomfort. Once comfort is achieved, the lowest doses that maintain\ncomfort are used. Euthanasia and physician-​assisted suicide entail\nno titration, no calculation, or maintenance of minimum doses\nneeded for comfort, because the goal is death (Hallenbeck, 2000).\n\nWithholding and withdrawal of artificial nutrition\nand hydration\nThe decision whether to use any life-​sustaining medical intervention, including artificial nutrition and hydration, should be based"},{"id": "20.1","title": "Palliative Care Needs Assessment Tools","chapter": "20.1","section": "20","sectionLabel": "Assessment Tools","start": 1191,"end": 1208,"pages": 18,"weight": 0.0144,"text": "CHAPTER 20.1 Palliative care needs assessment tools\n\nDISEASE\nMANAGEMENT\nPrimary diagnosis, prognosis,\nevidence\nSecondary diagnoses (e.g., dementia,\npsychiatric diagnoses, substance\nuse, trauma)\nCo-morbidities (e.g., delirium,\nseizures, organ failure)\nAdverse events (e.g., side effects,\ntoxicity)\nAllergies\n\nPHYSICAL\n\nPSYCHOLOGICAL\n\nPain and other symptoms*\nLevel of consciousness, cognition\nFunction, safety, aids:\n\nPersonality, strengths, behaviour,\nmotivation\n\n• Motor (e.g., mobility, swallowing,\nexcretion)\n\n• Senses (e.g., hearing, sight, smell,\ntaste, touch)\n\nMourning\n\nEND OF LIFE CARE/\nDEATH MANAGEMENT\nLife closure (e.g., completing\nbusiness, closing relationships, saying\ngoodbye)\nGift giving (e.g., things, money,\norgans, thoughts)\nLegacy creation\n\nFears (e.g., abandonment, burden,\ndeath)\nControl, dignity, independence\n\n• Sexual\n\nConflict, guilt, stress, coping\nresponses\n\ncirculation)\n\nFluids, nutrition\nWounds\nHabits (e.g., alcohol, smoking)\n\nSelf-image, self-esteem\n\nSOCIAL\nSOCIAL\n\nLoss\n\nBereavement planning\n\nEmotions (e.g., anger, distress,\nhopelessness, loneliness)\n\n• Physiologic (e.g., breathing,\n\nLOSS/GRIEF\nGrief (e.g., acute, chronic,\nanticipatory)\n\nDepression, anxiety\n\nCultural values, beliefs, practices\n\nPATIENT AND FAMILY\nCharacteristics\nDemographics (e.g., age,\ngender, race, contact\ninformation)\n\nRelationships, roles with family,\nfriends, community\nIsolation, abandonment,\nreconciliation\nSafe, comforting environment\nPrivacy, intimacy\n\nCulture (e.g., ethnicity,\nlanguage, cuisine)\n\nRoutines, rituals, recreation, vocation\n\nPersonal values, beliefs,\npractices, strengths\n\nLegal (e.g., powers of attorney for\nbusiness, for healthcare, advance\ndirectives, last will/ testament,\nbeneficiaries)\n\nDevelopmental state, education,\nliteracy\nDisabilities\n\nFinancial resources, expenses\n\nFamily caregiver protection\nGuardianship, custody issues\n\nPreparation for expected death\nAnticipation and management of\nphysiological changes in the last\nhours of life\n\nPRACTICAL\n\nSPIRITUAL\n\nPronouncement, certification\n\nActivities of daily living (e.g.,\npersonal care, household activities)\n\nMeaning, value\n\nPerideath care of family, handling of\nthe body\n\nDependents, pets\n\nValues, beliefs, practices, affiliations\n\nTelephone access, transportation\n\nSpiritual advisors, rites, rituals\n\nRites, rituals\n\nFunerals, memorial services,\ncelebrations\n\nExistential, transcendental\n\nSymbols, icons\n\n* Other common symptoms include, but are not limited to:\nCardio-respiratory: breathlessness, cough, edema, hiccups, apnea, agonal breathing patterns\nGastrointestinal: nausea, vomiting, constipation, obstipation, bowel obstruction, diarrhea, bloating, dysphagia, dyspepsia\nOral conditions: dry mouth, mucositis\nSkin conditions: dry skin, nodules, pruritus, rashes\nGeneral: agitation, anorexia, cachexia, fatigue, weakness, bleeding, drowsiness, effusions (pleural, peritoneal), fever/chills, incontinence,\ninsomnia, lymphoedema, myoclonus, odor, prolapse, sweats, syncope, vertigo\n\nFig. 20.1.1 Domain"},{"id": "20.3","title": "Validated Assessment Tools: Psychological and Spiritual","chapter": "20.3","section": "20","sectionLabel": "Assessment Tools","start": 1216,"end": 1231,"pages": 16,"weight": 0.0128,"text": "1218\n\nSECTION 20 Assessment tools and informatics\n\nTable 20.3.1 Selected assessment tools for psychological distress\nMeasures\n\nScoring\n\nDescription\n\nDT: Distress Thermometer (Donovan\net al., 2014; National Comprehensive\nCancer Network, 2014)\n\n• \u0007Cut-​scores between 3 and 5 used worldwide for\nscreening\n• \u0007Median sensitivity 0.83; median specificity 0.68\n• \u0007Score >4 most commonly used\n\n• \u0007Single 0–​10 Likert scale measuring self-​reported psychological\ndistress in the past week\n• \u0007Used in combination with five-​domain Problem Checklist\n\nESAS-​r: Edmonton Symptom\nAssessment System-​revised (Teunissen\net al., 2007; Watanabe et al., 2011)\n\n• \u0007Palliative cut-​score >5\n• \u00070.90 sensitivity and 0.76 specificity for anxiety\n• \u00070.61 sensitivity and 0.73 specificity for depression\n\n• \u00079-​item multi-​symptom assessment measure, including single\n0–​10 Likert scales for anxiety and depression\n• \u0007Validation in palliative populations based on original ESAS\nversion\n\nDistress and combined measures\n\nPHQ-​4: Patient Health Questionnaire-​4 • \u0007Sum score range 0–​12\n(Kroenke et al., 2009, 2010)\n• N\n\u0007 ormal: 0–​2\n• \u0007Mild: 3–​5\n• \u0007Moderate: 6–​8\n• \u0007Severe: 9–​12\n\n• \u0007First 2 items of the PHQ-​9 and GAD-​7, screening for DSM-​5\nmajor depression and generalized anxiety disorder\n• \u0007Anxiety and depression subscales with range 0–​6\n\nHADS: Hospital Anxiety and\n• \u0007Subscale range 0–​21\nDepression Scale (Zigmond and Snaith, • N\n\u0007 ormal: 0–​7\n1983)a\n• \u0007Mild: 8–​10\n• \u0007Moderate: 11–​14\n• \u0007Severe: 15–​21\n\n• \u000714-​item self-​report measure excluding somatic symptoms\n• \u0007Subscales for anxiety and depression\n• \u0007Separate scoring ranges for total HADS\n• \u0007copyrighted\n\nStressor-​related measures\nADNM-​20: Adjustment Disorder—​New • \u0007Sum score range: 20–​80\n• \u000720-​item self-​report version of the ICD-​11 Adjustment\nModule (Lorenz et al., 2016; Kazlauskas • C\n\u0007 ut-​score >47.5 differentiates high and low risk for Disorder Scale\net al., 2018)\nadjustment disorder (not validated in medical or\n• \u00076 subscales; 8-​item version focuses on 2 core subscales of\npalliative populations)\npreoccupation and failure to adapt\nSASRQ: Stanford Acute Stress Reaction\nQuestionnaire (Cardeña et al., 2000;\nPedersen and Zachariae, 2010)\n\n• \u0007Sum score range: 0–​150\n• \u0007cut-​score >18 for possible ASD\n• \u0007diagnosis based on rating ≥3 on at least 3\ndissociative, 1 intrusive, 1 avoidant and 1\nhyperarousal symptoms\n\n• \u000730-​item self-​report measure of ASD\n• \u0007includes symptoms of dissociation, re-​experiencing, avoidance,\nhyperarousal on 0–​5-​point Likert scale\n• \u0007Provides ASD diagnostic guidance based on DSM-​IV-​TR criteria\n\nIES-​R: Impact of Events Scale-​Revised\n(Creamer et al., 2003)a\n\n• \u0007PTSD is a clinical concern: 24–​32\n• \u0007Probable PTSD: 33–​37\n• \u0007Severe PTSD symptoms: 37–​88\n\n• \u000722-​item self-​report measure for PTSD\n• \u00073 subscales for intrusion, avoidance, and hyperarousal\n\nGAD-​7: Generalized Anxiety Scale-​7\n(Spitzer et al., 2006; Esser et al., 2018)a\n\n• \u0007Mild: 5–​9\n• \u0007Moderate: 10–​14\n• \u0007Severe: 15–​21\n• \u0007Cut-​sco"},{"id": "21.1","title": "Teaching and Training Physicians in Palliative Medicine","chapter": "21.1","section": "21","sectionLabel": "Teaching and Training","start": 1233,"end": 1241,"pages": 9,"weight": 0.0072,"text": "CHAPTER 21.1 Physicians\n\nstudents attending an optional palliative care course reported ‘it was\na new area of knowledge’ with transferrable skills to patients with\nnon-​palliative care needs, which prepared them better to work as\ndoctors (Centeno et al., 2016). As palliative medicine and end of life\ncare have gained increasing credibility, more diverse and imaginative\nteaching methods have been employed, for example, at the time of\nanatomy dissection (Marks and Bertman, 1980) or communication\nskills teaching (Charlton, 1993). Skills can be encouraged through\nproblem-​based learning, role-​play (Torke et al., 2004), goldfish bowl\ndiscussions (D. Jeffrey, 2002), consultations with simulated patients\n(actors or expert patients) (Kahn et al., 2001), and supported observed hospice visits and clinical attachments. Pain and symptom\nmanagement, psychological and ethical issues, professional roles,\nand teamwork have been taught within facilitated multiprofessional\nworkshops (Gadoud et al., 2018), some involving family caregivers\n(Wee et al., 2001). Other approaches include involving bereaved\nfamily members in teaching communication skills (Schillerstrom\net al., 2012); the use of literature, drama, and film to teach palliative\ncare competencies (Ring and Reilly, 2003; Dietz et al., 2012; E. J.\nJeffrey et al., 2012; Ozcakir and Bilgel, 2014); and the use of combinations of e-​learning and simulation to teach spiritual and cultural aspects of care (Ellman et al., 2012). Some students have been\ntaught within virtual family meetings with standardized examinations and one-​to-​one feedback. Tasks during the family meeting\nincluded discussion about prognosis, establishing goals, and conflict resolution (Hagiwara et al., 2017).\nIn some schools, students spend time with patients with cancer\nand their families, attending appointments and investigations, and\nvisiting them at home (Maughan et al., 2001). Students’ learning is\nsupported through tutorials and written reflective portfolios. While\nsuch longitudinal learning is usually evaluated highly, supporting\nstudents is critical and may be particularly difficult for those students who have personal experience of illness or bereavement.\nThere is a growing emphasis on experiential clinical learning\nmethods and reflective practice in the literature. Corcoran and co-​\nworkers highlight the utility of formal reflection after medical student half-​day hospice attachments in the US (Corcoran et al., 2013),\nand Borgstrom and colleagues the use of reflective written assignments following meetings with patients in the UK (Borgstrom et al.,\n2016). Short bedside clinical experience in palliative care with integrated reflection enabled understanding of palliative care and its\ncore medical values (Roji et al., 2017).\nThere has been concern that involving patients (and their families) within undergraduate teaching will place pressure and burden\non patients and staff, however, studies show patients are willing\nto see medical studen"},{"id": "21.2","title": "Teaching and Training Nurses in Palliative Care","chapter": "21.2","section": "21","sectionLabel": "Teaching and Training","start": 1242,"end": 1251,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "1244\n\nSECTION 21 Teaching and training in palliative medicine\n\nBuilding on palliative care nursing education\nGeneralist and specialist palliative care nurse\nThe ideal model of palliative care involves a specialized healthcare\nteam providing holistic treatment towards patient-​centred goals.\nHowever, poor access to palliative care is still a global issue due to\nnon-​existent or insufficient training of health professionals, among\nother significant barriers (World Health Organization, 2018c).\nAdditionally, most seriously ill patients and those at the end of life\ndo not access hospices or university medical centres, where most\nspecialized teams are available. Consequently, non-​specialist staff,\nand very frequently the generalist nurse, deliver ‘generalist end of\nlife care’.\nTheoretically, generalist nurses have extensive clinical competencies to meet a varied range of patient needs. They hold wide\nknowledge of health/​disease conditions in key areas of practice. All\ngeneralist nurses have training to provide palliative care, effectively\ngood nursing. However, there are differences in nursing undergraduate curricula content and professional practice varies among\nand within countries. In addition, evidence of inadequate symptom\ncontrol and preparation of nurses to care for patients and their families confirm a generalized educational deficit (Kwon, 2014; Unroe\net al., 2015; Smets et al., 2018).\nSuch challenges have led nurses to delineate nurse’s palliative competences, minimum curricula, and recommendations at\nundergraduate and postgraduate levels, leading to certification\nand postgraduate courses (De Viegler et al., 2004; Lynch et al.,\n2011; American Association of Colleges of Nursing, 2018). The\nspecialist palliative care nurse requires expert knowledge to care\nfor individuals with serious life-​\nthreatening diseases and the\ndying, including advanced symptom assessment and management,\ncounselling and communication skills, and advance care planning (Schroeder and Lorenz, 2018). Definitions of the specialist\nnurse vary widely and it is not always a formally recognized title\nobtained through academic postgraduate training. The specialist\nnurse designation can be obtained in different ways, according to\neducational and professional regulations of each country where\nit is recognized as a specialization. Examples are the US, Canada,\nand Japan, where palliative care is a specialty for nurses offered\nthrough master’s degree programmes (Sherman and Free, 2015),\nbut there is also a possibility for nurses with experience in palliative care to take an exam to obtain a certification in this specialty.\nOther countries including Australia, Brazil, and the UK have\nlong-​\nterm postgraduate courses at different levels (fellowship,\nspecialization, master, and PhD). In addition, clinical experience\nin palliative care has also been considered a distinguishing factor\nand therefore, residency, fellowship, and immersion courses in\nthe subject are considered resources tha"},{"id": "22.1","title": "Research in Palliative Care","chapter": "22.1","section": "22","sectionLabel": "Research","start": 1261,"end": 1267,"pages": 7,"weight": 0.0056,"text": "CHAPTER 22.1 Research in palliative care\n\nand meta-​analyses have become increasingly important, the latter\ncombining results from multiple studies, preferably RCTs, aiming\nto increase power, improve estimates of effect sizes, and resolve\nuncertainty when reports disagree. Systematic reviews adhere to a\nstrict scientific design to make them more comprehensive and reduce bias, thereby increasing their reliability. These methods are\npowerful as they aggregate large amounts of data, and provide evidence from palliative research.\nDespite being of great concern for patients, families, and\nhealthcare providers, death and dying is an underprioritized research area that receives low recognition within the academic medical community. Thus, this is rarely prioritized in the competitions\nfor funding, where sophisticated treatments and basic research\nadvocating cure receives the attention.\nThese factors hamper the quality and quantity of research in this\nfield. Systematic early integration of clinical palliative care with\nother medical disciplines may actually improve this, as the patient-​\ncentred approach counteracts the misconception that palliative care\nis end of life care only (Kaasa et al., 2018). It could be argued that\nthe field of palliative care research is immense, and that the patient-​\ncentred approach is challenged by the increasing demand for clinical effectiveness and service efficiency. The request from patients,\nfamilies, and society for tumour-​directed treatment in the very last\nstages of disease adds to the complexity.\nHowever, patient-​centred research does by no means compromise\ntumour-​centred research, as these are and should be regarded as\ncomplementary. As palliative care is multidimensional, the research\nshould be multiprofessional, and built on research traditions and\nmethods within clinical research, such as medical, nursing, and allied health professions, health services research, and epidemiology.\nNevertheless, there is a need for palliative care research to navigate\naway from small, inconclusive studies with non-​comparative designs\ntowards larger, multiprofessional, multicentre interventional studies.\n\nEpidemiological research\nDescriptive epidemiology seeks to describe the prevalence, incidence, and patterns of disease or other health-​related characteristics in populations. The major categories are individuals,\ntime, and place. Epidemiological information can help determine\nhealth needs and access, hence guiding the planning and delivery\nof healthcare services and adjusting for unwanted inequalities in\nthese, for example, in terms of effectiveness, efficiency, and accessibility. The most frequent quantitative, epidemiological methods that\nuse a public health approach to palliative research are population-​\nbased surveys, use of death certificate data to study place of death,\nand studies of routine administrative data at the population level\n(Pivodic and Cohen, 2018). Clinical audits, observational studies,\nor experimental s"},{"id": "22.2","title": "Evidence-Based Medicine in Palliative Care","chapter": "22.2","section": "22","sectionLabel": "Research","start": 1268,"end": 1278,"pages": 11,"weight": 0.0088,"text": "1270\n\nSECTION 22 Research in palliative medicine\n\nHierarchy of evidence\nThe first EBM principle is that not all evidence is of equal strength,\nand that clinical practice should be based on the best available evidence. As methods of generating evidence have developed and\nevolved, an evidence hierarchy has taken shape to assign relative\nmerit to different sorts of evidence (Fig. 22.2.2). In general, experimental studies are believed to generate higher-​level evidence than\ncomparative (observational and non-​randomized) studies for assessing clinical interventions. Among the latter, study designs are\nranked in strength of evidence (low to high) as follows: case series,\nhistorical controls, case–​control study, cohort study, and consecutive cohort studies. The RCT remains the ‘gold standard’ of study\ndesign, considered to generate the highest-​strength and most reliable evidence for evaluating new interventions.\nNot all questions can be answered using an experimental approach and patient experience must be taken into account in\npractice to fulfil the third EBM principle (to take into account patients’ values and preferences) (Greenhalgh et al., 2014). In order to\nachieve the second principle of EBM (the pursuit of truth should\ninclude evaluation of all the available evidence and not just that\nwhich supports a particular favoured claim) the range of evidence\nshould include different approaches to explore the research question. This importance is seen in the rise of the systematic review\nand meta-​analysis and also the inclusion by Cochrane of methods\nto combine data from observational, diagnostic tests and prognostic\nstudies (https://​training.cochrane.org/​handbook) and the methodologies developed for synthesis of qualitative data (Hannes and\nLockwood, 2011).\n\nQuality appraisal\nEvidence varies in strength and quality. Assessment and evaluation\nof biases in evidence are important but challenging and subjective.\nIn 2002, there were 106 systems available to rate the quality of research evidence (West et al., 2002). However, when applied by a\nrange of investigators, extensive disagreement has been found\n(Juni et al., 1999) and questions have been raised about their usefulness (Atkins et al., 2004) even with well-​accepted tools such as\n\nPseudorandomized\nCohort study controlled\ntrial\n\nCase\nstudy/\nseries\n\nRandomized\ncontrol trial\n\nCase\ncontrol\nstudy\n\nFig. 22.2.2 Evidence hierarchy for primary clinical research into new\ninterventions.\n\nthe Cochrane Risk of Bias tool (Jørgensen et al., 2016). An understanding of possible bias is important in appraisal of the published\nliterature.\nGenerally, the quality of evidence reported in a clinical trial is\ndefined by its ‘internal validity’, a term referring to the extent to\nwhich the investigators have minimized bias in study design and\nexecution (Juni et al., 2001). Various types of bias can threaten the\ninternal validity of a study. Selection bias results when participants\nin a sample do not truly represent the popu"},{"id": "22.6","title": "Ethical Issues in Palliative Care Research","chapter": "22.6","section": "22","sectionLabel": "Research","start": 1312,"end": 1317,"pages": 6,"weight": 0.0048,"text": "1314\n\nSECTION 22 Research in palliative medicine\n\nprocedure itself (whether sham or real) poses few if any additional\nor ‘incremental’ risks above and beyond usual care also can reduce\nconcerns about ethical acceptability. For example, investigators\nmight insert a sham epidural catheter that would then be used for\npostoperative analgesia (Haak van der Lely et al., 1994) or a crossover design can be used to ensure that all subjects who bear the\nrisks of the sham procedure also have access to the real procedure’s\npotential benefits. This crossover sham design has been used in\nother settings (Hahn et al., 1996), and might be appropriate for pain\nresearch when the risks or discomforts of the sham procedure are\nsubstantial.\n\nMinimizing burdens\nFor the most part, opportunities to minimize burdens are readily\napparent. For instance, it seems reasonable wherever possible to\nminimize surveys, interviews, and additional study visits (Bruera,\n1994). The importance of these actions may be accentuated when\nstudy subjects are very ill and an additional appointment or the requirement to complete another measure may increase distressing\nsymptoms, such as fatigue. Investigators who conduct palliative care\nresearch should be particularly attuned to strategies that minimize\nthese burdens, such as telephonic data collection.\nPalliative care investigators may also need to consider the burdens that a study creates for friends and family members who often\ntake on substantial burdens as caregivers (Steele and Fitch, 1996;\nEmanuel et al., 1999). By building flexibility into a study design (e.g.\nuse of brief telephone interviews, multiple options for timing of\nclinic visits), investigators may be able to reduce the burdens of research participation on others. At the same time, it is important for\npalliative care researchers to be cognizant that they are not inappropriately ‘gatekeeping’ by imagining burdens where they do not exist.\nGatekeeping, ‘the process whereby healthcare providers prevent access to patients for research recruitment’ (Hudson et al., 2005) is\nan obstacle in palliative care research (White et al., 2008) and may\nunjustly (Sharkey et al., 2010) prevent palliative care patients from\nparticipating in research to which they would otherwise consent.\nThe fear of burdening vulnerable patients is the most reported\nreason for gatekeeping in the end of life context (Kars et al., 2016).\n\nEnsuring decision-​making capacity\nPatients who consent to participate in research should have adequate decision-​making capacity, which refers to subjects’ ability\nto understand relevant information, appreciate the significance of\nthat information, and reason through to a conclusion that makes\nsense for them (Grisso and Appelbaum, 1998). Concerns have been\nraised about capacity in research involving patients with dementia\n(Marson et al., 1994) and psychiatric illness (Elliott, 1997), and patients in the intensive care setting (Lemaire et al., 1997), among\nothers.\nConcerns about th"},{"id": "22.7","title": "Quality of Life and Patient-Reported Outcome Measures","chapter": "22.7","section": "22","sectionLabel": "Research","start": 1318,"end": 1327,"pages": 10,"weight": 0.008,"text": "1320\n\nSECTION 22 Research in palliative medicine\n\nPlethora of publications and instruments\nThe substantial increase in publications indexed under the subject heading QoL in MEDLINE reflects the increased focus on\npatients’ QoL during the last 35–​40 years. Seven papers were published in the period of 1966–​1970 while more than 120,000 papers\nwere published in 2013–​2017. A textbook published in 1996 included more than 200 different measures of QoL and derivatives\n(Spilker, 1996). A database of PRO instruments established in\n2002 (the PROQOLID) now includes more than 1600 instruments\n(PROQOLID, 2018). The rapidly increasing number of papers and\nnewly developed instruments represents a challenge for the researcher and the clinician when they select the most appropriate\nassessment tool for their purpose.\nThis increase in papers and questionnaires also points to a need\nfor collaboration on the development of a common vocabulary,\nas well as standardized and agreed-​upon assessment tools. These\nsuggestions have been put forward by several research groups for\ndecades both in HRQoL assessment in general (R. T. Anderson\net al., 1993) and in palliative care specifically (Kaasa et al., 2007;\nKaasa and Radbruch, 2008). Despite these suggestions, new instruments for assessment of pain are being developed and published\n(Hjermstad et al., 2008). Most of these instruments are rarely used\nin later studies.\n\nOrganisation for Research and Treatment of Cancer (EORTC) measurement system for cancer which includes modules for different\ndiagnosis and clinical encounters, is presently being converted to\na computerized version based upon statistically derived algorithms\n(Petersen et al., 2013). In palliative care, a computer-​based tool for\nassessment of different PRO, communication support, and decision\nsupport, the so-​called Eir system, is under development (Krogstad\net al., 2017). Unlike the two other initiatives, this system is based\nupon clinical algorithms.\nComputer systems allow for more flexible ways of administering\nthe tool, including downloading it from the internet, administration by proxies, and the employment of handheld devices. An ePRO\ncan be programmed with skip instructions so that a patient does not\nhave to answer all items within a domain in order to obtain a score.\nFor example, a patient reporting physical functioning at the highest\npossible level does not have to answer other items that are included\nin the scale in order to differentiate between lower levels of functioning. Further, scores will be computed immediately and in digital\nformats and can be merged with other digitalized information. In\ntotal, such a development can make integration with other clinical\nparameters easier, support clinical decision-​making, and finally be\nstored in the EPR assuming that the security and data protection\nrequirements are in place.\n\nComputer-​based assessment\n\nBarriers to the use of patient-​reported outcomes\nin the clinic\n\nThe progress in information technolog"},{"id": "22.9","title": "Clinical Audit and Quality Improvement","chapter": "22.9","section": "22","sectionLabel": "Research","start": 1335,"end": 1349,"pages": 15,"weight": 0.012,"text": "CHAPTER 22.9 Clinical audit, quality improvement, and safety in palliative medicine\n\ncan arise in palliative and end of life care (Dy, 2016). A common\nreason for visiting the hospital is feeling ‘unsafe’ in the community\n(Henson et al., 2016), and a valued component of home care is a\nfeeling of security brought about by both available and competent\nstaff (Sarmento et al., 2017).\n\nCosts of not auditing\nThe costs of not auditing are increasingly critical (Higginson, 1994;\nShort and Scott, 2015a, 2015b; Dincer et al., 2018; Grant and Collier,\n2018; Jansen et al., 2018). These include:\n• Extra inappropriate treatment or services, wasting staff time and\nresources which could be used elsewhere where they may be\nmore effective\n• Uncontrolled symptoms that may cause undue patient suffering,\nadmission to hospice or hospital, or delay discharge\n• Harms to patients or families, medical mistakes, poor continuity\nof care, and coordination.\n\nRecourses necessary for audit\nClinical audit takes time and resources (Shaw, 1980a, 1980b, 1980c,\n1980d, 1980e; Higginson, 1994) and, indeed, it may be impossible\nto undertake audit if a service is struggling, with insufficient staff to\ngive even basic care. Consequently, assessing the capacity to audit\ncould be the initial step of an audit and may limit the scope of what\ncan be reasonably undertaken. Indeed, simple assessments, such\nas whether follow-​up occurs, can be useful in assessing practice\n(Selman and Harding, 2010) and may provide important insights\nin resource-​limited settings. The costs of audit mean that it is important to ensure that the audit itself is as effective as possible and\nthat findings are acted upon.\nThe resources needed for audit and quality assessment can include:\n• Time from all staff to prepare for audit, to agree the standards or\ntopic, and to review the findings\n• Time from some staff to carry out the audit and to analyse its results and document the findings and recommendations\n• Commitment from all staff, managers, nurses, doctors, and so on\nto consider the results and act upon them\n• Resources to pay for the staff time involved, plus any other analytical or computing support needed\n• Resources to pay for evaluating that changes have occurred.\nAudit needs to work with existing clinical systems, which usually\ninvolve computing devices, and data entry and storage systems\nsuch as the UK Rehabilitation Outcome Collaborative (UKROC)\nDatabase (Turner-​Stokes et al., 2012) and Electronic Palliative Care\nCoordination Systems (EPaCCS) (Petrova et al., 2018). These systems are comprised of software applications which bring together\nkey clinical and administrative data and can help if they are used\nto streamline the information collected specifically if they include\nready-​prepared programmes to facilitate analysis.\nThe audit measures can be included within these systems.\nHandheld devices such as tablets are increasingly used by staff and\npatients to complete clinical information. However, if the aud"}];
